<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>David Schoenbrun</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenbrun </PERSON>, 73, a war correspondent who was recruited for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> by <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON>, died Monday of heart failure. He was 73. <PERSON> Schoenbrun </PERSON> was introduced to <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON> by Gen. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> at the end of World War II. <PERSON> Schoenbrun </PERSON> had gone to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1941 with the <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> as an editor. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in 1943 and covered the invasion of southern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1944. <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON> hired <PERSON> Schoenbrun </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> correspondent. He was <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> bureau chief from 1947 until 1961. <PERSON> Schoenbrun </PERSON> later served in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, as <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' main political correspondent.
