<BYLINE>Dino Grandi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dino </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON>, who lost out to <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> in a 1921 bid for leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and helped depose the dictator in 1943, died Saturday at age 92. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> fought in World War I and joined the fascist squads that terrorized the Italian countryside. He failed to win the leadership of the fascists at a national congress in 1921 but successfully made a bid for a seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. He participated in the October 1922 march on <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> that led to <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>'s installation as head of government. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> served as undersecretary of the interior in 1924 and was foreign minister from 1929 to 1934.
