<HEAD>Congress Gets Special Showing of Broadway Show on Arms Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The producers of a Broadway play about arms control negotiations brought their performance to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Monday night, where it was viewed by an appreciative audience that included the secretary of state and two men involved in such talks. `` It bore no resemblance to reality, that's what made it so good,'' said Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> after viewing `` A Walk in the Woods.'' `` It was a good characterization and a lot of laughs,'' he said. The play, starring <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> as the American negotiator and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosky </PERSON> as his Soviet counterpart, was performed in the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> auditorium, across the street from the Capitol. A dozen senators, having just finished a day of debate about the U.S.-Soviet medium-range arms control treaty, were among the 250 people who attended the play, along with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glitman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON> was the American who formed the basis of <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON>'s character, while <PERSON> Glitman </PERSON> was the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator on the medium-range missile treaty <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON> and <PERSON> Glitman </PERSON> agreed with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. `` It did n't bear any relationship to anything we talked about,'' said <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON>. `` It's a dramatization, and while it's good, it's not like reality,'' said <PERSON> Glitman </PERSON>. The play, a black comedy, is based on <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON>'s 1982 private talk with <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kvitsinsky </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nitze </PERSON>'s Soviet counterpart. That discussion produced an agreement between the two men on the framework for a medium-range missile treaty, but the plan was later rejected by both gov