<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The medieval fantasy `` Willow,'' a $ 55 million gamble in an often-disastrous film genre, found an audience and box office figures Monday show moviemaker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> apparently has another hit on his hands. `` Willow,'' released early to avoid first-week competition from certain blockbusters `` Crocodile Dundee II'' and `` Rambo III,'' was the nation's top-grossing film in its debut weekend with an $ 8.3 million take. <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said he was buoyed by the figures and was confident `` Willow'' could maintain its box office appeal despite the two sure-fire sequels that will flood 2,000 screens each on Wednesday. `` Willow'' surpassed the opening weekend business of `` Raiders of the Lost Ark'' -LRB- $ 8.26 million in June 1981 -RRB- and `` Top Gun'' -LRB- $ 8.19 million in May 1986 -RRB-, <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said. In addition to high expectations from `` Star Wars'' creator <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> and `` Cocoon'' director <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, `` Willow'' has received interest because of the amount of money it cost to make the film over a two-year period. It also comes after two expensive <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> flops _ `` Labyrinth'' and `` Howard the Duck.'' One `` Willow'' critic recently called it `` <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> the Duck.'' <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who monitors box office trends for <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Variety </ORGANIZATION>, noted that only five motion pictures in history have ever done $ 8 million-plus during May's traditional pre-Memorial Day holiday movie slump. Other Top 10 films pulled in considerably less during the weekend. Last week's top performer, `` Friday the 13th Part VII - The New Blood,'' took in $ 3.43 million to place second in the latest sweepstakes. It made almost as much as `` Willow'' in its debut with an $ 8.2 million take on 1,796 screens. In third was `` Colors'' with $ 2.9 million, followed by `` Beetlejuice'' with $ 2.7 million and `` Shakedown'' in fifth with $ 1.2 million. In `` Willow,'' the main character lives in a village of little people and finds a baby floating in the river, but it's a special baby who will threaten the throne of the evil Queen <PERSON> Bavmorda </PERSON>. The queen orders her warriors to find and kill the baby and the story revolves around the perilous trek to a castle sanctuary. `` Willow,'' which opened Friday at 1,024 theaters nationwide with little enthusiasm from reviewers, is the latest effort from <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, whose `` Star Wars'' and `` Indiana Jones'' films have grossed $ 1 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reviewer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kehr </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>: `` In ` Willow,' the Force has left him. He's imitating himself and he's moping while he does it. Daily Variety termed the film `` a medieval mishmash'' but predicted `` kids will probably love it.'' The Hollywood Reporter praised the production values but complained the storyline `` never really kicks into overdrive.'' Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in release, and estimated production costs when available. 1. `` Willow,'' <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, $ 8.31 million, 1,024 screens, $ 8,106 per screen, $ 8.3 million, one week, n-a. 2. `` Friday the 13th Part VII - The New Blood,'' Paramount, $ 3.43 million, 1,796 screens, $ 1,912 per screen, $ 13.24 million, two weeks, n-a. 3. `` Colors,'' <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.94 million, 1,388 screens, $ 2,122 per screen, $ 34.4 million, six weeks, $ 12 million. 4. `` Beetlejuice,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.72 million, 1,546 screens, $ 1,764 per screen, $ 58,8 million, eight weeks, $ 20 million. 5. `` Shakedown,'' Universal, $ 1.22 million, 938 screens, $ 1,703 per screen, $ 8.12 million, three weeks, n-a. 6. `` Moonstruck,'' <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.17 million, 771 screens, $ 1,525 per screen, $ 73.97 million, 23 weeks, $ 17 million. 7. `` Above The Law,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.14 million, 715 screens, $ 1,604 per screen, $ 17.45 million, seven weeks, $ 14 million. 8. `` Salsa,'' Cannon, $ 1.13 million, 757 screens, $ 1,510 per screen, $ 6.79 million, three weeks, n-a. 9. `` <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blues </LOCATION>,'' Universal, $ 1.12 million, 876 screens, $ 1,282 per screen, $ 39.3 million, nine weeks, $ 16 million. 10. `` The Last Emperor,'' <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, $ 930,729, 792 screens, $ 1,175 per screen, $ 40.29 million, 27 weeks, $ 25 million.
