<FIRST>r w PM-Summit-Afghanistan Bjt   05-23 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Afghanistan, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Pullout Saves Gorbachev From Reagan Lecture</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet decision to withdraw troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is more than a life-saving step. It has rescued <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> from another `` leave-the-Afghans-alone'' lecture from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. As the leaders prepare for their fourth summit, in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> May 29-June 2, the first <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units have come home to <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> and the Soviets seem determined to meet a February 1989 deadline for the removal of all 115,000 troops. The erasure of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> as the topmost regional issue at the summit will give <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> more time to push <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> toward settlements in other global hot spots _ <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. At least for now, `` there has been a resolution, or at least the formula for resolving the Afghan issue,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON>, undersecretary of state for political affairs and head of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team preparing for the summit discussion of regional issues. `` At the summit there just is n't that much more to say to them, except perhaps, ` thanks' and ` keep up the good work,''' said another <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity. This official, and <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> as well, suggested, however, that Afghan issues could re-emerge as a summit topic because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are still actively engaged in the settlement process as the Soviets wind down their eight-year war. `` In terms of military arrangements, one of our biggest concerns is that they take out whatever minefields they have sown over the past eight years,'' the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said. `` This is an issue of safety for civilians coming back to their villages.'' Earlier this year, before the Soviets signed a pledge to withdraw their troops, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> beseeched <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to take the further step of ceasing military assistance to the government headed by Afghan leader <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. In return, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said it would stop giving military support to the mujahadeen, the anti-Soviet resistance fighters, matching Soviet restraint with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> restraint. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> rejected the proposal and on May 14, the Soviet military commander in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> announced he would leave behind up to $ 1 billion in arms and installations for use by the Afghan army. `` That does n't strike me as a demonstration of tremendous restraint,'' <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said. He reiterated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> determination to keep helping the guerrillas and said, bluntly, `` we'll have practical ways of accomplishing that purpose.'' Asked if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> might seek <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s help in getting the resistance to let the Russian troops retreat home without being harried by attacks, <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said the Soviets would do better by seeking `` local arrangements'' with mujahadeen leaders. Though these issues remain, the fundamental decision to withdraw and evidence last week that the agreement is being carried out, removed an irritant that has nagged U.S.-Soviet relations since December 1979, when <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> forces entered what had been a civil war. President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> protested the invasion by keeping the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic team home from the 1980 <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> games and he embargoed grain sales to the Soviets. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> resumed the grain deals, but he made clear that better U.S.-Soviet relations hinged to a large extent on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s willingness to pull its troops home from the Afghan conflict Indeed, before his met <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in 1985, in <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> in 1986 and in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1987, he devoted speeches to the issue and signaled his intention to berate the Soviet leader about <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> when they met. For example, in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> eight days before the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` It's time for them to pack up, pull out and go home. It's time that they set a date certain for the complete withdrawal of all Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said it appeared that even the Soviets were writing off the current regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. `` The Soviets pride themselves on recognizing objective reality. Well, it's time for them to bite the bullet.'' By contrast, two weeks before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit, the White House found itself praising Soviet actions, calling the pullout `` a welcome first step.''
