<FIRST>r a PM-OpenEnrollment Bjt   05-23 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Open Enrollment, Bjt,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Open Enrollment Puts Students, Parents On Honor System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new state law allowing students to choose their schools will improve education, proponents say. But some educators fear the plan could hurt smaller schools and bring unhealthy competition. `` We realize there may be some poor choice-making in the free market, but the challenge is to educate parents in how to make sound choices,'' says <PERSON> Nan </PERSON> <PERSON> Skelton </PERSON>, assistant state education commissioner. The measure gives <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> the nation's broadest open enrollment plan, <PERSON> Skelton </PERSON> said. Schools may refuse students only if the transfer would interfere with desegregation ratios in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, or if the school is too crowded. State funding, about $ 3,000 per youngster, follows the student to the new district. Previously, parents had to pay tuition to the new district. Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> signed the measure into law May 6. It takes effect in the 1989-90 school year in larger districts and applies statewide in 1990-91. State education officials hope schools will improve their programs in the competition to attract students. A 1986 National Governors' Association project recommended open enrollment as a way to boost school quality. `` I have mixed feelings,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON>, an assistant to the superintendent of the 89-student Humboldt-St. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> school district, one of the state's smallest `` If they're put on the honor system, are they going to transfer for the right reasons?'' A champion debate coach worries about students transferring for non-academic reasons. `` For some students, those activities are a very important part of what they're about,'' said <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, whose teams have won three state titles in six years and one national title. But <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> says he sees the value of such plans. `` If the concept is to allow parents and students some choice, you have to recognize that's important for them,'' <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> said. Students could transfer to schools where their chances of making an athletic team might be better or to join friends, but it's debatable whether those are poor reasons to switch, <PERSON> Skelton </PERSON> said `` It's just who gets to judge,'' she said. `` The people who get to make the decisions are the parents and the students. If the Education Department thinks it's a frivolous reason, it does n't matter. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON> of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, who lives on the border between two districts, took advantage of a forerunner of the law and sent her two children to a different district so they could be with their friends. `` They just love going to school. If they -LRB- children -RRB- are n't happy being at a school, they are n't happy doing anything there,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON> said The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> opposes allowing students to transfer for non-academic reasons. `` I do n't think students should be permitted to exchange districts for athletic reasons or for some personality reasons. It seems to me that really could cause some chaos or problems,'' said Executive Director <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, whose association represents 435 districts. The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 20,000 teachers, has not taken a position. `` There's a possibility that small districts could end up losing students,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, federation president. `` They may have to look at cooperative ventures with other districts or consolidation.'' <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> began open enrollment on a voluntary basis this school year, with 137 students in 95 districts choosing to participate. Under the voluntary program, districts had the option of accepting transfers from outside their districts. For the 1988-89 school year, 435 students in 153 districts applied, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Zastrow </PERSON>, director of support services for the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> officials have applauded <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s efforts. `` The overwhelming majority will not make decisions like these for frivolous reasons,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearlstein </PERSON>, spokesman for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> and Improvement. `` Indeed, most students will not change school districts. But choice is valuable even when people decide to stay where they are.'' <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> said he hopes the new law will prompt more schools to offer debate programs, but worries about the effect of transfers on his own program. `` If we had even four students transfer into our school and they were good, that would lock up all positions so kids from <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> would not have a shot,'' <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> said. On the other hand, <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> said, `` If open enrollment provides a marketplace for education, then, shoot, that's going to get more schools looking at adding this program.''
