<FIRST>r a PM-NoPhones     05-23 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No Phones,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses, Residents Learn To Cope With Limited Phone Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Duntley </PERSON> has traded in his ties and starched shirts. Casual dress will do these days, when instead of calling customers from his comfortable office, he stands in line to make his pitch on a pay phone. `` It's like fighting with one arm tied behind your back,'' said <PERSON> Duntley </PERSON>, 55, as he scanned a legal pad filled with names of potential buyers around the country for <ORGANIZATION> Ameristate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 7,500 steel-cutting equipment. `` Actually, it's like throwing your money down the drain.'' `` It'' is the hassle created by the Great Phone Outage. It began May 8, when a fire damaged virtually all the vital hardware at an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> switching station. At first, the outage seemed only a minor inconvenience for customers in a handful of Du Page County communities about 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. But as <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> crews examined the smoldering cables and water-damaged electronics, the picture became much clearer _ and very bleak. Phones for 35,000 customers were dead indefinitely, silencing the simple crosstown call or the long-distance business deal. Limited local service has since been restored, but calls outside the immediate area are hit or miss. To offset the lack of phone service, towns increased police patrols. For several days, public employees also sat in vehicles on street corners watching for crime or fire or medical emergencies. There have been no reports of any law enforcement or fire problems linked to the outage, however. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> crews are working around the clock to replace the wrecked equipment, but the job may take until June. `` It's total confusion. It's been a disaster,'' said <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schramm </PERSON>, an officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Hinsdale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION>, with 16,700 residents, is one of the largest communities affected, but there is little industry here. With its cozy, colonial-style downtown shops and century-old homes, the village is a soothing retreat from the hectic pace of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. But to the south in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Willowbrook </LOCATION>, industrial parks sprawl along Interstate 55. Some of the country's biggest corporate names are here, including <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which employs 1,500 people at its headquarters `` Calls to downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> have been tricky,'' said <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lana </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrsam </PERSON> `` If one finally gets through, we might pass the phone around. Despite the fire we are able to keep operating. We were never totally without anything. `` We've been using a lot of resources,'' she added, `` Faxing and Telexing all over.'' `` It's driving me crazy,'' said <PERSON> Dirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Tweed </PERSON>, a salesman for <ORGANIZATION> Outdoor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Headquarters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Willowbrook </LOCATION>. `` At first I thought it was funny, you know, ` Hey the phones do n't work.' Now I guess it's pretty serious. `` I still run my regular route to stores that want hunting and fishing stuff, but I really ca n't tell what they might need if I do n't have a phone,'' Tweed said. `` Heck, I ca n't even call my boss in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.'' He said he spends much of his time reading magazines and talking to two secretaries. `` How are we coping? This is how we're coping,'' says <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Riendeau </PERSON>, chewing a candy bar with her legs up on the desk. `` If this keeps up, I'll be a raving lunatic. We've looked at the files and already rearranged what we rearranged last week. What else is there?'' Among the hardest hit are 24,000 florists nationwide that belong to <ORGANIZATION> FTD </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the flower delivery network. About half are hooked to a computer system in Downers Grove designed to relay an order across the country in a snap. But the line to the FTD computer network flows through the <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> station. `` We've been absolutely crippled,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON>, director of operations for <ORGANIZATION> FTD </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Floral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, who has the task of trying to find an alternative system. `` The flower business has not stopped _ people can still call and order. But instead of using the computer network, florists have to look up florists in other cities and call them one by one. That hurts.'' The switching station, meanwhile, has come to resemble a traveling circus. Big mess tents are erected for the dozens of laborers assigned to get the site back in order, and <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> executives call the shots from a row of trailers. Customers line up at a bank of portable pay phones trucked in by the utility. `` It's been a disaster, but it's folksy,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ging </PERSON>, a local psychotherapist, referring to the small talk between people waiting to use the phones. `` There are pluses as well as minuses,'' she said. `` One plus is people have to be resourceful. Most people do n't know how strong they are, how they can get along. ... I'm impressed with how well people have been coping.''
