<SECOND>PM-District Fight,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Something Happened on the Way to a Political Dynasty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOWLING GREEN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For years, Rep. <PERSON> Delbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> groomed his son to replace him when he retired from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But another well-known <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Republican had a different idea about who will go to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. After the elder <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> announced in January he would not seek re-election, it seemed only natural that <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> would declare his candidacy for <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s 5th District. But the Lattas did n't count on a challenge from within. The challenge came from Republican <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON>, who had irritated the Lattas just enough to prompt murmurs of a feud. <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> was the highest ranking <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> legislator in the state and candidate for his party's nomination for governor in 1986. Official vote totals from the May 3 congressional primary show <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> defeated <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> by 41 votes of more than 63,000 cast in a three-way race. But a recount is automatic because of the slim margin _ 28,680 to 28,639 _ and even the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> says the race is too close to call. `` I do n't think it divided the Republicans because I ran a positive race,'' <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON>, 49, said last week. `` I said before the primary race that I would support the eventual nominee. I expect they would do the same.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> has refused to concede, but the 32-year-old corporate attorney from Bowling Green said he will support <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> if <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> is the nominee. `` As a Republican for my entire life, you support Republicans,'' he said. Hoping to pick up the pieces is Democrat <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, a 51-year-old <LOCATION> Sandusky </LOCATION> attorney making his second run for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> believes the departure of the elder <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> will end <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> domination in the Bowling Green district, which now boasts more registered Democrats than Republicans. `` Nobody believed I could beat <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> in 1986, and they were right. It was like running against an institution,'' <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said. `` There's no doubt that he has the contacts in the district from 30 years of service, but I'm not sure the same can be said for any of the Republicans this time.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> may be chasing moonbeams. `` I think -LRB- the GOP primary -RRB- had the potential to be a real nasty kind of thing, but basically I think the candidates did a good job of talking about themselves rather than each other,'' he said. `` I think it makes it easier to put together a campaign in the fall for the winner. ... I just do n't see people flocking to vote for <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> said a rift occurred between <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Delbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> in 1982, when the Legislature was redrawing congressional district lines. At the time, <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> was president of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ a position he still holds. <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gillmor </PERSON> was trying to redraw the 9th Congressional District, a traditional Democratic stronghold that includes <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, so it would be more favorable for <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, a Republi