<SECOND>PM-Bolding Trial, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nursing Group Watches Trial Of Nurse Accused Of Potassium Overdose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPER MARLBORO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The verdict in the trial of a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> nurse accused of killing hospital patients with a common substance used for a variety of medical procedures will influence how all nurses go about their jobs, a spokeswoman for a nurses organization says. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON>, formerly a nurse at the Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> about 20 miles east of the nation's capital, is accused of killing three of her intensive care patients by injecting them with lethal doses of potassium and attempting to murder two others the same way. Potassium is found naturally in the body, but in large amounts can cause cardiac arrest. A guilty verdict would likely have a `` chilling effect'' on health care officials who routinely prescribe and administer common medicines like sodium bicarbonate and insulin, which can be fatal if used in large quantities, said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimaldi </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. Such a verdict `` would make it more difficult for people to carry on in an already stressful environment,'' she said. `` We usually see cases where people are accused of murder by turning off machines or poisoning, not the use of an organic compound,'' she said. The 180,000-member association represents registered nurses. Autopsies on the three victims all revealed inexplicably high levels of potassium. But no official cause of death was ever listed in any of the cases and no one witnessed <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> doing anything wrong. If <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> is convicted of murder, the case could have ramifications for the nation's health care industry, according to defense attorney <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>. `` If this case went unchallenged, there would be paranoia throughout the medical industry,'' <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> said. `` This case is a medical and legal nightmare.'' What makes the case so important is that potassium, an electrolyte found in the body, is also used for a variety of common medical purposes in hospitals, <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> said. Assistant State's Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Creech </PERSON> has called <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> `` a killer angel.'' He is basing his case on a study by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> that indicates more of <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON>'s patients died of cardiac arrest than did those of any other nurse at the hospital On the first day of trial in Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last Wednesday, defense attorneys scoffed at the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> report, and said the prosecution's case is based on the flimsiest of circumstantial evidence. On Thursday, <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON>'s attorneys got the pathologist for the intensive care unit of the hospital where the nurse worked to say that potassium levels normally begin to rise as soon as a patient dies. Dr. <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Matei </PERSON> said that once the heart stops _ and oxygen ceases to flow in the bloodstream _ tissues and cells begin to break down, releasing stored-up potassium. `` It's a normal process,'' <PERSON> Matei </PERSON> told the court. Cardiopulmonary resuscitation, in which a strenuous chest massage is used in efforts to restart the heart, also causes tissue breakdown, <PERSON> Matei </PERSON> testified. In addition, kidney failure contributes to high potassium rates because the bloodstream, which caries potassium, is not purified, <PERSON> Matei </PERSON> added. CPR was attempted on all three patients <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> is accused of killing, and at least one had kidney problems, hospital records indicate. `` We say it's impossible to tell whether potassium caused the heart attacks, or whether the heart attacks resulted in high levels of potassium,'' <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> said. `` This whole case is about doubt.'' The investigation of <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> runs from January 1984 to March 1985, but <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> introduced into the court record documents indicating high potassium levels for patients at the hospital during a 10-year period that encompasses the Bolding probe. <PERSON> Creech </PERSON> has relied on hospital records in an attempt to establish that <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> was present when the patients died, but hospital officials testified under cross examination that many others also had access to the alleged victims. None of <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON>'s former colleagues who have testified so far have questioned the nurse's work ethic or job performance. <PERSON> Bolding </PERSON> was indicted after a grand jury heard testimony last year on the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> study. The non-jury trial is expected to last up to eight weeks.
</TEXT>
