<HEAD>Poultry And Pork Consumption Grows With Meat Consumption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's biggest meat eaters are curbing their appetites for beef and looking for second helpings of poultry and pork. Per capita meat consumption in the major producing countries _ usually the richest _ grew about 11 percent over the last decade, says an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. But the gains were n't across the board. `` For instance, most of the increase came from poultry and pork, while beef declined,'' the report said. `` Consumption of lamb, mutton and goat stagnated worldwide.'' In 1975-77, Americans averaged about 127 pounds of beef and veal, 59 pounds of pork, 2 pounds of lamb, mutton and goat, and 51 pounds of poultry. By 1985-87, per capita consumption was: beef and veal, 106 pounds; pork, 63; lamb, mutton and goat, 2; and poultry, 73. Those are carcass weight equivalents before being divided and trimmed into retail cuts. Even in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, the biggest meat-eater of all, per capita beef consumption dropped to 174 pounds from 187 a decade earlier. Declines also occurred for lamb, mutton and goat meat, and poultry, each down 1 pound. However, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which has been striving to upgrade diets, boosted beef consumption to 62 pounds per capita from 52 pounds in 1975-77, while pork increased to 48 pounds from 43. Lamb, mutton and goat held steady at 3 pounds, but poultry consumption jumped to 23 pounds from 14 pounds previously. The report was included by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in the agency's quarterly <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> issued last week. Analysts noted that per capita meat consumption is affected by many factors, including local and world economies, religion, social customs and even climate. `` Most meat is produced and consumed in high-income countries,'' the report said. `` However, new technologies, like improved refrigeration and transportation, in developing countries have opened the door for meat imports and improved the distribution of such products.'' On the other hand, religion sometimes restricts the kinds of meats that are acceptable in certain countries. Moslems and Jews shun pork, and Hindus avoid all meat. Pork is the predominant meat in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, especially <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, as well as in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other Asian nations. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, alone, where about a third of the world's pork is produced, consumption rose to about 35 pounds from 18 pounds during the decade, the report said. Poultry consumption has gained the most, reflecting the relatively brief time span and less feed required to produce a pound of poultry meat, compared with other grain-fed livestock. `` Beef consumption predominates in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, where an abundance of forage is available for ruminant livestock production,'' the report said. `` Ruminants like cattle, sheep and goats can be raised without any grain, but this requires reliable sources of cheap forage.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite sharp differences over agricultural policy and subsidies, the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> remains the leading market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm products. In calendar 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, exports of farm products to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> were worth $ 6.8 billion, up by more than 3 percent from 1986. Although sales to the European bloc _ and farm exports generally, for that matter _ have not recovered to their record levels of the early 1980s, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts say further growth can be expected. But <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> leaders frostily reject a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal made in negotiations under auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade to phase out all trade-distorting farm subsidies by the end of the century. <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s top trade official, said in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> last week at a meeting of trade ministers that the trade bloc would never agree to the elimination of such subsidies, although it favors unspecified reductions. According to a recent analysis by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm exports to the EEC this year could rise by an additional 5 percent because of `` attractive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prices, favorable exchange rates and continued economic growth'' in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A dispatch from an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> trade official in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> says West Germans are eating more rice these days. `` Rice, noodles and additional vegetable consumption are replacing the traditional potato as the No. 1 German food item,'' says <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural counselor. `` Rice millers are confident that this trend will continue into 1988.'' <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s comments were reported in the June issue of Foreign Agriculture magazine. Competitive prices for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice pushed shipments up sharply last year and primarily replaced rice from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, he said.
