<HEAD>Rabbi Approves Demolition Of Hong Kong Synagogue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi has approved the demolition of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s 86-year-old synagogue to make way for a complex containing a new synagogue and high-rise apartments, a local Jewish leader said. The plan to demolish the Ohel <PERSON> Leah </PERSON> synagogue split the local Jewish community and enraged preservationists, who see the project as another blow to this British colony's heritage. However, supporters argued that the Ohel <PERSON> Leah </PERSON> synagogue is dangerously old and better facilities are needed for a growing Jewish community. The chief rabbi of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Commonweath </ORGANIZATION>, Lord <PERSON> Immanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakobovits </PERSON>, `` waived any religious objection'' to demolishing the Ohel <PERSON> Leah </PERSON> synagogue, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorfman </PERSON>, a synagogue leader. Synagogue trustees want to demolish the building and erect two 40-story towers and a new synagogue on the site.
