<FIRST>r a PM-OrganTransplants     05-23 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Organ Transplants,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Cuts Off Funds for Transplants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Holladay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> legislators all but voted to end her 2-year-old son's life by cutting off funds that would have paid for a bone marrow transplant. So she left southern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> this spring to seek welfare funds for a transplant operation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where her son <PERSON> David </PERSON> is awaiting a transplant at that state's expense. `` I left my home. I left my dog. I left my life,'' <PERSON> Holladay </PERSON> said. `` This was extremely frustrating because we had a home there, we had school there, we had our lives set up there.'' Her supporters in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> raised about $ 5,000 of the $ 100,000 needed. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> lawmakers voted last summer to finance only cornea and kidney transplants, joining a minority of states that do n't pay for transplant operations such as those of hearts, bone marrow and livers. The move drew little notice, until 7-year-old <PERSON> Coby </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> died Dec. 2 of leukemia as his relatives were raising private contributions for a marrow transplant. The resulting furor helped persuade the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which handles budget matters between sessions, to take up the issue. But the board voted against using emergency funds to reverse the Legislature's action. As a compromise, the panel created what's believed to be the nation's first transplant payment program to be financed by a combination of federal funds and private donations. The program is triggered when $ 85,000 in donations are turned over to the state. Some backers of restoring state financing said the compromise was better than nothing. Others were critical. `` I really think it was a spineless decision on the part of the state,'' said <PERSON> Tammi </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Coby </PERSON>'s mother. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> is leading a petition drive to put a measure requiring the state to resume transplant financing on November's ballot. `` The fact that the state stood by and let a little boy die like that has stirred up a lot of emotions,'' she said. `` If it was up to the public, all of these people would have transplants and would be on the road to recovery by now.'' <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Coby </PERSON>'s aunt, deplored a process in which she coaxed the boy to perform for television in his final days in attempts to raise money. `` I asked him to smile for the camera when, not 30 minutes before, he had been vomiting due to his illness,'' <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> said. `` I had to turn <PERSON> Coby </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> into a marketable product so the public would, in essence, buy him his life.'' Relatives and friends had raised about $ 70,000 toward the cost of the operation by the time he died. Forty-one states pay for bone marrow transplants, 36 pay for heart transplants and about 40 finance liver transplants, said <PERSON> Jeane </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorne </PERSON>, director of the state transplant program. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> spent about $ 500,000 toward 19 heart, pancreas, marrow and liver transplants in the two-year budget period that ended last June 30. Federal Medicaid funds pay 62 percent of the cost of transplants for qualified recipients. <PERSON> Thorne </PERSON> had projected the growth in demand for transplants would push the state's cost to about $ 800,000 this year. Senate President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitzhaber </PERSON>, a physician and co-chair of the emergency board, opposes renewed state financing for transplants. He says limited health care dollars must be spent in a way that will do the most good. That standard favors funding prenatal care for many low-income women instead of financing costly and sometimes risky operations for a few people, he said. `` We can not keep people alive forever. That is a part of life,'' <PERSON> Kitzhaber </PERSON> said at one meeting. `` What we can do with our limited money is to try to reduce the number of deaths ... to save as many people as we can save.'' Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, who hopes to restore state funds, said the publicity has disgraced <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. `` The national image that this controversy has brought to the state is horrendous,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said. `` How many more people actually have to die?'' he asked at the board's first meeting on restoring the funds. `` There's no logic to spend money on prenatal care and then let them die after they're born,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said.
