<SECOND>PM-Summit Planning,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planning A Summit in Moscow: `It's Just Different From Working
Here'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> has planned presidential travel to most of the 50 states and 18 foreign countries, including the economic summits in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. But President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this week was different. Preliminary preparations for the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit began in 1985 after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> met in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and said they wanted to visit each other's country. `` It's a whole different mind set,'' <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON>, director of presidential advance, said of the Soviets. `` They do n't deal with the kind of things we deal with. `` We are constantly pushing and urging and prodding for things that are just sort of anathema to their system.'' For instance, there was the matter of the private dinner <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are having at a country home outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Soviets insisted there be no press coverage. <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> reluctantly agreed, but said there should at least be an official photographer. The Soviets said no. `` I ca n't seem to get them to grasp the concept that this is an incredibly historic thing, or potentially historic, these guys eating dinner out there in this house in the country,'' <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` It would be like having a picture of <LOCATION> Roosevelt </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. `` They just do n't think like that. You really sense that instinctively there's a pullback from anything that's going to be other than exactly like how they do it and how they've done it for years and years, and that's, of course, very closed.'' <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> believes, however, that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or openness, does seem to be having some effect. `` There's a bit more than I expected of a willingness to let us work directly with ... some of the people at the places where we are going,'' he said. For example, he said, the advance team was able to work directly with the management of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will be visiting.'' He added, `` I do n't think we were turned down from seeing anything that we requested to see. `` On the other hand, you run into this kind of block with no explanation on certain issues as to why, once you are there in these places, you ca n't do certain things. The security people can override everybody else ... and they do n't feel a need to explain the reason.'' <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> said the initial preparations for the summit consisted mainly of checking with people who had been involved in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> visits before, including some members of the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration. More active preparations began after the two superpower leaders met in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in December and announced that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> sometime in the spring. Over a period of approximately two months leading up to the summit, three advance teams visited <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, one more than usual. For a domestic trip, as when the president goes to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, one person from the advance offices makes the initial survey, checking out proposed speech sites with an eye to establishing communications, security and the other facilities needed for a presidential visit. On a foreign trip, this group is increased to about 10 or l2 senior people who `` get a few concepts agreed to'' in consultation with their counterparts from the host country, <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> said. The final advance team, whether the president is going to <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Bali </LOCATION>, is a larger group of maybe 45 to 50, including technical people, to make specific arrangements. In the case of the summit, <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON>, Director of Communications <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Courtemanche </PERSON>, first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief of staff, made an extra visit `` to negotiate the finer points of the schedule,'' the advance official said The `` ambiguous phrase'' used by people who had been to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> suddenly became clear, <PERSON> Hooley </PERSON> said. `` They'd say, ` It's just different from working here.'''
