<HEAD>Shultz: Gorbachev's Mars Mission Proposal Needs Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proposal for a joint mission to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> `` has to be studied carefully'' and may be taken up under a U.S.-Soviet space agreement. `` That's something that's been talked about, but it's a long way from being agreed upon,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, appearing on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Week With <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> published Sunday, said he would ask President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to approve a joint, unmanned flight to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> when they meet in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for their May 29-June 2 summit. Asked if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would pursue such a venture, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> noted the superpowers reached an agreement on space ventures about a year ago under which particular projects are examined. `` I presume this will come up under that heading,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Sunday, adding, `` Obviously this has to be studied carefully. We always have to be careful with problems of technology transfer.'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> said Sunday he had told Soviets scientists 10 days ago about a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision in principle to take Soviet Mars-probe equipment along on a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space launch in 1992. <PERSON> Keller </PERSON>, the space agency's deputy associate administrator for space sciences, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> offer, the unmanned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` Mars Observer'' spacecraft would carry a Soviet receiver. If the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> craft still were operating when a 1994 Soviet spacecraft seeks to land on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, the Soviet receiver would improve transmissions to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, he said. The secretary of state also urged the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to approve the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles in time for the summit. `` It helps certainly to have completed something and to register that fact. ... It's good to register the fact that we can do it,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. The secretary, sidestepping any criticism of the president's conservative allies who oppose the treaty, lauded the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for its thorough consideration of the pact `` I think the process has gone well. I have only compliments for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the way in which they've handled this,'' he said, adding, `` I think there's been a time for hearings, a time for questions, a time for critiques and a time for debate. There also has to come a time to decide and I think we're about there.'' The pact, formally known as the Treaty on Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces, was signed by the two leaders at their December summit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Both the president and administration officials are eager to have the ratified treaty as a boost for negotiations with the Soviet side. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has turned aside a wave of amendments designed by its conservative opponents to kill the treaty, and debate is expected to continue through much of the week. Approval of the pact requires 67 votes, if all 100 senators are present. The secretary of state also echoed the positive remarks <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made in the interview with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reporters, in which the Soviet leader said he hoped he could sign an agreement slashing in half the superpower arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office. `` It's certainly possible,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of prospects for such a treaty. `` And I feel certain that at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit we will both want to agree to keep working on it hard. But whether it will actually happen or not, I do n't know. The issues are tough.'' Queried about talks on the disputed Strategic Defense Initiative, which has hampered agreement on a strategic missile pact, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has staunchly opposed any impediment to the development of a defense against ballistic missiles. `` That still leaves room for a lot of things,'' the secretary said.
