<HEAD>Firestone Workers Returning To Jobs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with some workers returning;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `The URW ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the 4,700 <ORGANIZATION> Firestone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> employees in six states who had been on strike returned to work late Sunday after negotiators reached tentative agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> on a new contract. Union spokesman <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said ratification votes on the three-year contract would be held this week at Firestone offices and plants in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Noblesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.; <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Workers at <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION> and Nobelsville plants started to return to work Sunday night. Workers in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION> were expected to be back on the job Tuesday morning. The <ORGANIZATION> URW </ORGANIZATION> members struck May 15 after <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> declined to accept the cost-of-living allowance provided in an industry pattern agreement the union negotiated with <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the new contract followed the <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> pattern reached May 17 `` Our major goal had been to keep pattern bargaining, and that had been all we really asked from Firestone,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` This is n't really a greedy contract.'' Firestone spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Troyer </PERSON> said, `` We believe this is a fair and realistic contract for our employees. The agreement recognizes the particular needs of Firestone's tire operation.'' He said the company was optimistic for early ratification of the contract. Under the agreement, <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> would: _ Maintain cost-of-living allowances in each year, with a one-cent hourly increase for every increase of 0.26 in the Consumer Price Index. _ Boost wages 25 cents per hour by deducting that amount from future cost-of-living adjustments in increments of 10, 10 and 5 cents. _ Increase retirement pensions for current workers by $ 3.50 to $ 23.50 per month for each year of service In addition, current retirees would receive a lump sum bonus of $ 200 before Dec. 1. _ Provide choice of first-dollar health insurance coverage or an 80-20 percent co-payment plan that includes a $ 1,000 enrollment incentive bonus. _ Make 35 percent matching contributions in the employee savings plan that is part of the 80-20 comprehensive health plan. Both plans provide for a 401-K savings plan. In addition, the pact assures continuation of the contract if a Firestone plant is sold to another company during the next three years, and contains a no-strike wage reopener clause in the third year. Negotiations resumed Saturday at 1:15 p.m. with the assistance of federal mediator <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorley </PERSON> and an agreement was reached at 5 a.m. It was the only session held since the strike began May 15. The strike was the first involving Firestone since 1976, when the <ORGANIZATION> URW </ORGANIZATION> struck all the Akron-based rubber companies except General Tire. In a related development, the union said a contract covering 15,000 <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> workers was ratified Sunday when Local 2 in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, which represents 1,700 members, `` overwhelmingly approved'' the agreement. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said seven of eleven locals at <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> had voted on the contract. Six locals representing a total of 8,060 members had approved it, and one with 231 members rejected it. Ratification had been assured Friday when a <ORGANIZATION> URW </ORGANIZATION> local in <LOCATION> Danville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, voted by 72 percent to 28 percent to accept the pact. It was the second <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> proposal to be put to a vote. <ORGANIZATION> URW </ORGANIZATION> members at three other <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> locals also were scheduled to vote Sunday. They had approved the inital contract proposal. Under the <ORGANIZATION> URW </ORGANIZATION> constitution, contracts must be approved by `` a majority of union locals representing a majority of members.''
