<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts of the face-to-face interview conducted Wednesday between Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and senior executives and editors of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>, and written answers to questions submitted to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in March. The excerpts are taken from the transcript which was prepared by the Post from the original English and Russian language used during the interview. The excerpts from the written questions and answers are taken from the English language text supplied by the Soviet government. Q: -LRB- <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Well, we are aware that you are following many things, in particular events in our country, and that you read a lot and remember everything -LRB- laughter -RRB-. A: Well, someone recommended me very well to you. I must extend to you Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s warmest regards. Q: Thank you. We had such a nice meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. I was hoping perhaps to be able to see her here, but if not please give her my best regards. A: She is not an easily manageable person -LRB- laughter -RRB-. Q: They say that about all of us. A: There is an interesting phrase, I think, of -LRB- <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Engels </PERSON>'. He used to say that a woman is an entire civilization. ... Q: Looking ahead to the party conference, we'd like your personal reaction to a number of specific proposals. For example, do you support the idea of fixed terms of office for party leaders, and, if so, would that include the position of general secretary itself? A: Well, you'll hear the answers in the coming days to all such questions. But I would say one word: Yes. Q: We hope you'll say a little more than one word -LRB- laughter -RRB-. A: Well, let me anticipate what you are going to read in the papers in five or six days. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> wants to find out earlier. Q: This is Newsweek. A: Your empire, then, wants to know things earlier. Q: Our empire is competitive within itself also, like all empires. Q: The interest in the party conference is so great, could you not perhaps, even in more general terms, discuss your hopes for this meeting, which is obviously such an important event. A: I certainly think that my expectations coincide with the expectations of our whole society. First of all, we want to take stock of what has happened over these three years, to sort out the history of perestroika, and, of course, we want that analysis of this period to be a critical one. We want to draw lessons _ perhaps that will be necessary. And based on that analysis, we may have to take some corrective measures in what we are doing in perestroika. But I think that the central question is the question of how to deepen this process, how to move forward with perestroika and make it irreversible. Therefore, the main questions at the conference will relate to deepening the economic reform and to deepening the democraticization of our party and society. This is the main thing. As for the rest of it, I think you will find out more. Q: Soviet editors have told us that Mr. -LRB- <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> endorsed the article in <LOCATION> Sovyetskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rossiya </LOCATION> that had some praise for the Stalin era. You personally endorsed an editorial in Pravda that refuted the Sovyetskaya Rossiya article. Can you tell us if the <ORGANIZATION> Sovyetskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> article reflected Mr. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s views -LRB- this second reference to the Sovyetskaya Rossiya article and <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> was dropped, apparently inadvertently, when the interpreter put this question to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in Russian -RRB-, and does this exchange suggest that there is a serious difference of opinion in the leadership about how far glasnost should go and the view of the <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> era itself? A: Well, my impression is that this whole theme of deep divisions in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership as to perestroika, as to the prospects of perestroika and the evaluation of the past, is being pushed not by Soviet editors but by the western media. That's my first reaction. I do n't know the motives behind the fact that this is systematically tossed up, and is then broadcast by various `` voices'' -LRB- foreign radio stations -RRB- in <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> and other languages into our country. ... The current leadership of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ including the Politburo and the government _ was formed basically after April 1985, when we set out on the course of perestroika, and all our leaders, both our political leaders and government leaders, are committed to perestroika and are actively involved in designing and implementing perestroika. ...
</TEXT>
