<HEAD>Last Days For Residents of Dwindling Trailer Park at Walden Pond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON> cooks his dinner every night, takes a drive once a day and is eager to show off the trailer he has occupied across from <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> for more than 40 years. <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON>, 94, is cheerful about his life and surroundings here in a wooded area writer <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> made famous. But there is a pall that hangs over the rustic trailer park. <PERSON> Walden </PERSON> <PERSON> Breezes </PERSON> is dying. When the state acquired the land 10 years ago, the owner insisted that the residents of the park called <ORGANIZATION> Walden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Breezes </ORGANIZATION> have life tenancy. But the state ruled that vacant trailers must be removed. State officials plan to make the trailer park part of <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> after the last resident has died or moved away. As a result, long cement slabs are all that remain of many trailer homes in the park. <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON>'s home is one of only 20 in <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Breezes </LOCATION>, which onced housed 70 trailers. But residents say they are used to the dwindling number of neighbors, in part because they all cherish their independence. But <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON>'s closest friend, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaffield </PERSON>, who lives across the park and `` will talk you blind if you let him,'' is sometimes nostalgic for the old days when <PERSON> Walden </PERSON> <PERSON> Breezes </PERSON> was bustling and family-filled. `` ` People are moving away or dying,'' said <PERSON> Swaffield </PERSON>, who also lives alone in his trailer. `` Every now and then you get a call that someone's passed on.'' <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Swaffield </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Breezes </LOCATION> after their wives died, and spend most of their time alone. As recently as last year they fished together at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> almost daily. Most of <ORGANIZATION> Walden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Breezes </ORGANIZATION>' remaining residents have outlived their neighbors and their spouses. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 80, a widower for three years, still wears his wedding band. He is philosophical about the sense of finality of <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Breezes </LOCATION>. `` It's kind of like, here today, gone tomorrow,'' said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, pausing between a strenuous raking of leaves around his trailer. `` When someone dies, they just go ahead and sell all the articles inside and get rid of the ... thing.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said he still feels `` young at heart'' and has resisted attempts by his children to move in with them. `` This is a place where elderly people can live independently,'' he said. `` Most people should realize that we do n't have to be put away.'' Independence at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Breezes </LOCATION> is so strong that remarriage among the widows and widowers is uncommon. `` No, I ca n't see why I would,'' said <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskett </PERSON>, 75, a 29-year resident whose husband died five years ago. `` We all know each other but it's more like friends. No romance.'' <PERSON> Haskett </PERSON> and one of her best friends, <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Weston </PERSON>, 77, often miss the old days at the park. But fishing is not what they remember most fondly. `` We used to have great parties by the lake or picnics by someone's mobile home,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Haskett </PERSON>, who lives in a fancy one-bedroom trailer with a mirrored living room. `` Now we're all being phased out.''
</TEXT>
