<HEAD>Former Philippine Rebel Barred From Travel To U.S. Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> _ The former head of the Philippine communist rebel army says he was denied entry into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for a weekend seminar, despite an invitation from a congressman and assurances from <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government officials that he is not a threat. `` Some absurd perceptions of some influential quarters in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration about Philippine problems prevented me'' from attending, said the former rebel, <PERSON> Bernabe </PERSON> <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON>. He spoke by telephone from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> to the Philippine-American group that had scheduled him as its featured speaker at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> seminar on the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, which ended Sunday night. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Huchel </PERSON>, said Sunday that <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON> was turned down for an immediate visa because of `` the unusual nature of his case,'' but he said the application was referred to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a possible waiver. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has no official spokesman available on weekends. <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON>, who is still widely known among Filipinos by his rebel name, `` Commander <PERSON> Dante </PERSON>,'' was jailed by ex-President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> but set free when President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> came to power in February 1986. In the late 1960s, he founded and led the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> which officials estimate now has up to 25,000 rebels fighting the Aquino government. <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON> has not renounced communism, but a <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said he carries a valid Philippine passport and is no longer considered a rebel or a terrorist. <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON> was an unsuccessful candidate for the Philippine <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last year. The Philippine official, who asked not to be identified, said top embassy representatives informally told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials they saw no reason why <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON> could not travel to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Huchel </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> was aware that <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON> also had an invitation to visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from Rep. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellums </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., and that he had been scheduled to speak Saturday at the national conference of the Campaign for Democracy and Independence The organization, known as CAMDI, includes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> groups that opposed ex-President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and originally supported President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> but have become increasingly critical of her 2-year-old government. <PERSON> Buscayno </PERSON>, in a statement translated for the group from <LOCATION> Tagalog </LOCATION>, said he applied for a visa April 27 and was interviewed on May 2 for three hours by <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> embassy vice-consul <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Matteson </PERSON>. He said Ms. <PERSON> Matteson </PERSON> asked him if he might have reason to seek asylum in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOC