<HEAD>Golden Temple Opens For Public Worship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 600 Sikhs filed solemnly into the Golden Temple today as it was opened to the public for the first time in two weeks. The temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine, was closed during a police siege May 9-18 that drove Sikh extremists from their temple hiding place. The separatists, who have been waging a guerrilla war for an independent homeland since 1982, had turned the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> into an armed camp. At least 46 people, mostly Sikh militants, were killed during the siege. Three militants committed suicide by taking cyanide capsules rather than surrender to police. No police or paramilitary forces were killed. Services in the inner sanctum of the temple, suspended on the second day of the siege, were resumed by priests on Sunday after volunteers washed the floor of the temple with milk to cleanse it. Police searched all 627 devotees today for weapons at an <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> police station, then moved them in four city buses to the temple for worship. Police and paramilitary troops retain a cordon around the shrine and enforce a curfew within 300 yards of its walls. The cordon is likely to stay in place until the government reaches an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which has so far refused its request to enforce a ban on militants re-entering the shrine. One death was reported in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> on Sunday night. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said a goldsmith was shot to death by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> gunmen in the village of <LOCATION> Murh </LOCATION> near the state capital at <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. Earlier Sunday, nine deaths were reported, including four Hindus killed in a bomb blast at a railway station in the town of <LOCATION> Ludhiana </LOCATION>, 80 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. Indian newspapers today said the bombing appeared to be the fourth attack aimed at Hindu migrant workers, who are in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> to help with the planting. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s most productive agricultural state. The latest slayings raised to more than 1,150 the number of people killed by Sikh extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since the start of the year. In all of 1987, 1,030 people were killed. Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatist cause. Sikhs claim they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>.
