<HEAD>Karoly Grosz: New Leader In Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s new <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, has built a reputation as a canny, pragmatic politician with a charisma not unlike that of his Soviet counterpart, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, 57, succeeded <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> on Sunday as general secretary during an overhaul of the party leadership. After becoming premier in June, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> established himself as a politician willing to tackle unpleasant economic issues while softening the blow of austerity measures with the promise of political reform. He has moved around the country, chatting with workers and apparently enjoying interviews with journalists from the state-run media. During a visit last month to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, he proved to be an unabashed admirer of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. These tactics overshadowed party ideologist <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Berecz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>'s main rival in the battle to become party chief, and <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> himself, who was left to shoulder the blame for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic crisis. Like <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who is two years his junior, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> comes from an impeccable background and got his start in politics during the turbulent times of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s death in 1953. Official biographies say <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was born into a worker's family in 1930 in the northeastern city of <LOCATION> Miskolc </LOCATION>. A Communist by 1945, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> followed his mother into work in a print shop. By 1949, he was in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> with the national party youth organization. Seizing a chance for promotion and education, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> entered the country's <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1950s, training as an officer for the Hungarian army, whose upper ranks had fallen victim to sweeping Stalinist purges. Within a year, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was a deputy lieutenant. He then served as full lieutenant stationed near the Yugoslav border who also was charged with the political education of his battalion. In November 1954, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was discharged from the army and sent to <ORGANIZATION> Borsod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to observe party organizations, factories and coal mines in his native Miskolc. Official accounts suggest <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> spent the turbulent year of 1956 in <LOCATION> Miskolc </LOCATION>, removed from the turmoil in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> emerged as undisputed leader after Soviet troops crushed an anti-Stalinist revolt and arrested liberal leader <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>. By 1961, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> had moved up to the central apparatus of the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> after a spell at the party academy and was named party head at state-run radio and television. Between 1968 and 1973, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was deputy head of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> propaganda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>, and from 1974 to 1979 was in full charge of the official propaganda machine He returned to <LOCATION> Borsod </LOCATION> as regional party head in 1979, and in December 1984 advanced to head the influential <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> party, which contains almost one quarter of the nation's 800,000 communists. At the national party congress in March 1985, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was elevated to the ruling party Politburo. When <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was named premier, he almost immediately acknowledged that some political reform was needed to complement stringent economic measures he pushed to control mounting foreign debt. He pushed through the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first value-added and personal income taxes, designed to deregulate price controls and tap the income from the second jobs many Hungarians hold to make ends meet. Although his austerity program is to last until 1990, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has stressed there is no target date for overcoming <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic crisis. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has outlined vague plans for parliament to have a larger and more supervisory role in government decision-making, and even countenanced dialogue with unofficial opposition groups who do not contest Communist rule. `` This government is not likely to go down in history as one of the victorious,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said last fall, `` but if we can succeed, we will be praised for taking an interest in the country.''
