<HEAD>Writers, Producers to Meet With Federal Mediator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Meeting begins at 5 p.m. EDT; lede prospects unlikely</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A scriptwriters' strike against movie and TV producers entered its 12th week with potential for a break as a federal mediator called both sides together for the first formal talks in more than a month. The meeting between representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> was set this afternoon. It was the third such effort and the first since a 20-minute session April 18. Recent informal discussions between the sides came to nothing, said <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an Alliance spokesman. Both sides have suffered from the walkout, which began March 7 over issues of payments for reruns, works distributed in foreign countries and creative control. The meeting was set only four days before guild members were scheduled to vote on proposed contracts with up to 24 independent producers. The vote could provide much-needed jobs for a substantial number of writers, said guild spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON>. Leaders of the 9,000-member union have granted only two waivers to independent producers but are recommending that West and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> members ratify the independent contracts in hopes of shortening the walkout, she said. `` It's showing that the proposals of the guild are reasonable and that businesses feel they can conduct their business profitably with those contracts,'' she said. But <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said: `` They've been saying that for 12 weeks, and we've been telling them their reasoning is unreasonable. ... There ca n't be a settlement if they're coming and demanding more.'' `` So far the only independents they've signed are none. Even the independents find their deal too difficult to swallow,'' he said, citing a decision by <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Tonight Show'' to broadcast shows despite the strike. On April 14, the union approved independent contracts with the `` New Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reitman </PERSON> Productions, which has produced such movies as `` Ghostbusters'' and `` Animal House.'' Although other independent contracts were considered, the guild voted against approval at the time. Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said more than 150 producers have asked to negotiate with the guild for independent contracts. None of the independents who negotiated separate deals are among the 200 represented by the alliance, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said the signing of the independents would not affect negotiations, because they represent less than 10 percent of feature film and 15 percent of television production. Producers say the strike has cost the industry more than $ 15 million in lost jobs and production time, with about 1,400 clerical workers, cast and crew members laid off due to the stop in scripts.
