<TEXT>
 Prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> dropped slightly today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and the dollar also fell after moving in a narrow range in lackluster and trendless trading. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 144.09 points, or 0.52 percent, after recovering some of its morning losses in the afternoon session. It closed the trading day at 27,249.76 points. The main market barometer had lost 248.79 points by the end of the morning session. Nothing really affected the stock market, said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Napier </PERSON>, vice president of the Japanese equities department at <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>. `` The problem is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has to open all by itself Monday mornings,'' <PERSON> Napier </PERSON> said. `` There's not really any market-moving news.'' He added that the `` stock market was very shaky in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> last week, which caused a general sell-off -LRB- in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> -RRB-.'' Volume share in the first section of the <ORGANIZATION> TSE </ORGANIZATION> was 700 million shares, down from its last Friday's 800-million-share total. In foreign exchange dealings, meanwhile, the dollar closed at 124.80 yen, down 0.02 yen from its last week close, but slightly higher than its opening today at 124.78 yen. The currency fluctuated in a narrow range between 124.71 yen and 124.82 yen during the day. `` With no specific market-moving incentives at hand, the dollar remains in a narrow range,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. He added that market participants were trying to keep the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency at a low 124-yen level. ` We're likely leading to a period where Japanese trade surpluses will be higher again, and we're concerned about that,'' <PERSON> Napier </PE