<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Economy     05-23 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Economy,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Plan Would Turn Japan's Strength Inward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economic strategists today gave Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> a five-year plan urging that the Japanese economy be directed at increasing domestic demand and reducing the country's massive trade surplus. The plan, made public after six months of research at <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s behest, puts an official imprimatur on the recent shift in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy, which achieved vibrant growth last year mostly on a boom in domestic housing rather than the traditional method of expanding exports. A summary of the plan for 1988 through 1992 said three major economic problems `` can all be resolved by promoting and consolidating the shift to a domestic-demand-led economy.'' The problems, it said, were how to reduce <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus, how to improve the quality of life for the 122 million Japanese and how to promote `` balanced national economic and social development.'' If the plan's aims are attained, it should please <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trading partners like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, who have complained for years that the export-minded Japanese were n't taking effective measures to reduce trade <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a task force reporting to the prime minister, to produce a five-year plan last November shortly after he succeeded <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>. The chairman of the council, <PERSON> Gaishi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiraiwa </PERSON>, who is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters in a briefing that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s previous 10 economic plans since 1955 had aimed at quantitative expansion, but the new plan envisions the transformation of economic structure and tries to attain `` qualitative enhancement. Attaining the goals will mean `` pain and burden to the people at large,'' he said. `` Therefore, I believe that the understanding and cooperation of the Japanese people are needed more than ever.'' The plan will be debated by <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s Cabinet in coming weeks and its general outlines are expected to guide <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economic development. The plan's directions are similar to those in a 1986 economic report requested by <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>. The Maekawa Report, compiled by a panel headed by former <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> Gov. <PERSON> Haruo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maekawa </PERSON>, also recommended a shift away from export industries to domestic demand _ the direction the economy has taken _ but did n't achieve the status of a report approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. The new plan predicts real economic growth averaging 3.75 percent annually over the five years. Domestic demand would provide a 4.25-percent average growth rate, it said, while exports would provide negative growth of a half-percent annually. It offers no target for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surpluses of trade and payments, saying instead they should reach `` internationally harmonious levels during the period of the plan.'' In the fiscal year ended March 31, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus dropped for the first time in eight years, from $ 89.7 billion in 1986-87 to $ 76 billion in 1987-88, according to government statistics. The high value of the yen, which has doubled against the dollar in the past three years, has increased the Japanese appetite for foreign goods while making Japanese exports more costly in overseas markets. Last year, for instance, Japanese automakers fell slightly short of their government-set quota of 2.3 million cars exported to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because Japanese cars are no longer so much of a bargain for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> buyers. The plan urges the introduction of the five-day, 40-hour workweek _ now many Japanese work six days a week. For foreign countries, the new economic plan offers the following directions: _ Improving access to the Japanese market so that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is `` a land of business opportunity for the world at large. _ `` Contributing to a better world'' through trade and investment and by increasing foreign aid and capital-recycling to developing countries. _ Contributing to stabilization of the international currency markets by cooperating with other leading industrial countries on economic policy
</TEXT>
