<HEAD>Naked Egg Drop, Weighted Balloon Events Challenge Science
Olympians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future chemists and physicists applied scientific principles to solving puzzles that included dropping raw eggs and slowing the ascent of balloons. About 1,200 junior and senior high school students from 36 states, who had already competed in local, state and regional contests, met here Saturday for the fourth annual National Science Olympiad. Junior high students competed in 22 events and high school students entered 23 events. The competition was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>. `` This Science Olympiad is the first thing I've seen in the last 18 years that has stimulated the minds of these students,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Goslein </PERSON>, an assiciate dean of instruction at <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, who presided at the balloon race. Two <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> teen-agers used motor oil, dough and foam to cushion the landing of a raw egg dropped 25 feet to win the Naked Egg Drop. <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>, both 16 and from <LOCATION> Tift </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION> -RRB- High School, said the key was the motor oil blended into the half-inch thick cushion. In the competition, medium-size raw eggs were dropped from great heights and caught with cushion containers designed to keep the shells intact. Cushion materials included marshmallow, peanut butter, Jell-O, raspberry jam, wet towels, axle grease, noodles on cotton, and soggy whole white bread on plastic foam. `` The problem was n't really keeping it from cracking but keeping it from bouncing off,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. `` The motor oil ... made it stick. It just sat there in the motor oil.'' In the balloon race, students dreamed up ways of slowing the ascent of balloons from the floor to a ceiling finish-line. <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinsen </PERSON>, a senior at <ORGANIZATION> Toledo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and schoolmate <PERSON> Hungman </PERSON> <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>, a junior, designed an accordion-shaped construction-paper anchor for their balloon. `` First you find the area of density of a piece of paper and then you find the buoyant force of the balloon,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Martinsen </PERSON>, who sat at a table in front of a scale, `` and then with math you find out how much paper you need to counteract the buoyant force of the balloon.'' Ms. <PERSON> Martinsen </PERSON> had flown to the competition from <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, where she participated in a three-day <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanities </ORGANIZATION> and Science Symposium. She was worried the two events would make her fall behind at school. `` When I get back I have five days to catch up on everything and then graduate,'' she said. Not all the events were strictly scientific. Eighth-grader <PERSON> Adrienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosier </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Caesar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, fashioned a bass fiddle from a potato chip can, broomstick handle and venetian blind cord for a competition called the Sound of Music. All contestants were required to play `` America the Beautiful'' on instruments from nonmusical objects. At the end, they formed their own orchestra. In addition to winners in the individual events, the school with the highest point total captured the division. <LOCATION> Haverford </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> -RRB- High School won the senior division, while <ORGANIZATION> Campus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Irmo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, captured the junior division title.
