<HEAD>Eight Injured in Stagecoach Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEYSERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A team of horses pulling a stagecoach bolted and ran out of control for almost a quarter mile before the coach slammed into a telephone pole, injuring eight tourists, authorities said. One woman was in serious condition at <ORGANIZATION> Healdsburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> after Sunday's accident; the others were treated for minor injuries and released, authorities said. The coach was part of a vineyard tour in <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Highway Patrol officer <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>. Tour guide <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dilworth </PERSON> was in a vineyard explaining grape growing when he started to get back in the coach. It was then the horses bolted. <PERSON> Dilworth </PERSON> grabbed the reins but the wheels rolled over them and broke them. The horses veered off the road and headed straight for the pole. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said half the team went to the left of the pole, the other to the right and the stagecoach rammed it. <PERSON> Gretchen </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> was the most seriously injured.
