<HEAD>FTC: Bogus Legal Group Took In $3.3 Million Fraudulently</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Atlanta-based group posing as a national prepaid legal services firm took in $ 3 million over a nine-month period, fooling nearly 400 would-be franchisees, federal officials say. The Lawyers Access Network sold distributorships for a prepaid legal services plan from March to December 1987, according to lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which has been investigating the case. Prepaid legal services programs offer consumers basic legal services for a flat annual fee, rather than an hourly rate. The firm gathered $ 3.3 million from 392 people around the country who believed they were buying franchises by investing amounts ranging from $ 5,500 to $ 25,000, <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said. The figure did not include any fees that might have been sent in by consumers, they said. At best, investors may recover only 10 percent of their investment, one <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> lawyer said. `` This thing makes the movie ` The Sting' look small-time,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> McQuade </PERSON>, a public relations director in suburban <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> who paid a $ 25,000 franchise fee in order to market memberships in the network. `` It was so well set up,'' he said. `` They just had all their bases covered.'' The firm used false market research, baseless earnings projections and bogus references to lure purchasers into believing its program was successful, profitable and well-established, <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> lawyers say. In a series of legal actions that began in March, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> has shut down Lawyers Access and its marketing arm, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operated out of the same office in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> suburbs. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> confiscated dozens of records from the office during a search. According to the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> representatives brought fancy brochures and a hard-sell pitch to franchise shows nationwide. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> also won a permanent injunction and default judgment for more than $ 3 million earlier this month against firm officials <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockton </PERSON>. However, <PERSON> Pasley </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said, `` The fact of the matter is, whatever representations that may have been made to -LRB- distributors -RRB- that turned out to not be true were not made by Mr. <PERSON> Pasley </PERSON> or with his knowledge.'' <PERSON> Stockton </PERSON> claimed, `` I did n't set up the company; I was just an employee.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoob </PERSON> signed an order freezing 13 bank accounts and other assets allegedly controlled by <PERSON> Pasley </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON> said, `` There does not seem to be a big pot of gold out there, at least that we or the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> have been able to discover.'' The victims, <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON> said, may at best receive restitution of 10 percent. `` Prepaid legal services is a growth industry, and a legitimate industry,'' <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON> told the Atlanta Constitution. `` A legitimate plan along these lines might well be profitable. It's just these guys went too far.''
