<HEAD>No Mention Of `Killer Rabbit' In Carter's New Outdoor Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLIJAY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> says that on second thought, he probably should have included the `` killer rabbit'' episode in his new book on his outdoor adventures `` just to explain there was nothing to it.'' `` An Outdoor Journal: Adventures and Reflections,'' published by <PERSON> Bantam </PERSON> <PERSON> Books </PERSON>, portrays the former president as an avid hunter and fisherman who relishes the solitude and physical and intellectual stimulation the activities provide. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> writes vividly of stalking wild turkey in the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> woods, bagging ducks in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, battling trophy rainbow trout in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and fighting a blue marlin in the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. But the 224-page book, scheduled for release this week, omits the most famous outdoor adventure of his presidency _ the 1979 killer rabbit episode, in which he beat back with a paddle a rabbit he said was swimming toward his canoe during a fishing trip near <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. `` I guess I should have -LRB- included it -RRB- just to explain there was nothing to it,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said in an interview at his mountain cabin near here last week. `` But I do n't want to get into another altercation with the press about it. That was a contrivance of the press.'' The episode prompted numerous editorial cartoons and jokes at <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s expense, and the rabbit was dubbed the `` killer rabbit'' or the `` banzai bunny.'' Some skeptics claimed that rabbits do not swim, but <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said a blowup of an official White House photograph showed the animal was clearly a rabbit. He told reporters at the time, `` It was a fairly robust-looking rabbit who was swimming, apparently with no difficulty.'' He said it would have been `` an unpleasant situation for me and the rabbit'' if the animal had gotten into the canoe.
