<HEAD>Court Will Take Up California Case Involving Court Jurisdiction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether two <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service workers involved in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> traffic accidents while delivering mail must face criminal charges in state court. The justices said they will hear a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration attempt to transfer the prosecutions to federal court. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last year that state courts have authority in the cases, which stem from accidents in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. In one, <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON> <PERSON> Mesa </PERSON> was accused of misdemeanor manslaughter after her mail truck collided with and killed a bicyclist. In the other, <PERSON> Shabbir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebrahim </PERSON> was charged with speeding and failing to yield after his mail truck collided with a police car. Both defendants initially succeeded in having their cases transferred to a federal court but the 9th Circuit court sent the prosecutions back to state courts. The appeals court rejected arguments that the cases should be handled in federal court to prevent possible bias against the mail carriers. `` The attentuated federal interest in ensuring that their trial be unbiased does not justify an invasion of the state's authority to police its streets,'' the appeals court said. `` There is simply no reason to believe that, on a systematic basis, postal workers will not get a fair shake in state court.'' The appeals court added that overburdened federal courts `` do not need a new category of pesky cases turning solely on state law.'' In the appeal acted on today, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the appeals court ruling violates a federal law aimed at protecting federal officials in the performance of their official duties. The appeals court decision would `` permit states ... to undermine federal policies and programs,'' the appeal said, adding that it `` presents a potential threat to federal -LRB- legal -RRB- supremacy anywhere federal policies encounter local hostility.'' The 9th Circuit court noted that the federal law providing for removal of such cases to federal court was enacted in response to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s opposition to a trade embargo declared during the War of 1812 between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Federal customs officials were given authority then to board vessels in order to collect duties, assuring they would avoid prosecution in state courts for any alleged misconduct in the performance of their duties. The appeals court said there is no claim by the two mail carriers that their allegedly illegal conduct was justified by the duties they were performing. `` There is no effort on the state's part to criminalize activity important to federal interests, as there was during the War of 1812,'' the appeals court said. The case is <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 87-1206.
