ho sue for libel must prove the sued-over statement was false and was made with actual malice _ either knowledge of or reckless disregard of its falsity. Private citizens who sue for libel have an easier burden of proof _ that the statement was false and was made negligently. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, because it ruled that Ms. <PERSON> Lipscomb </PERSON> is not a public figure, ordered the punitive-damages award against <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> dropped. But the state court upheld the $ 100,000 judgment, ruling that there was sufficient evidence of negligence. In the appeal acted on today, the newspaper's lawyers argued that Ms. <PERSON> Lipscomb </PERSON> should have been considered a public official who could not win her libel suit unless she proved actual malice. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Lipscomb </PERSON>, 87-1636.
