<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case the insurance industry was watching closely, today let stand a ruling that millions of so-called fixed annuities are subject to federal securities law. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that fixed annuities paying fluctuating interest rates may be regulated the same as stocks and bonds. Fixed annuities traditionally have been regarded as insurance contracts because investors never risk their principal. Annuity holders are assured of receiving the money contributed plus a certain amount of interest in payments made at regular intervals. In 1985, 10 million individual annuities representing $ 24 billion in present and deferred annual payments were outstanding, according to insurance industry sources. Some 33 million Americans were covered under private pension plans funded by group annuity contracts that received $ 35 billion in contributions during that year and paid out $ 10 billion in benefits. There also existed seven million `` universal life'' policies _ a form of annuities _ representing $ 564 billion of insurance in 1985. Holders of fixed annuities are assured of a minimum rate of return on contributions. And most annuity plans provide for `` excess interest'' paid at the discretion of the annuity company. In 1967, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that so-called variable annuities, those that do not assure any minimum interest payments on contributions, may be treated as securities regulated by federal law. But a ruling by the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last April 15 marked the first time a fixed annuity was treated as a security. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> sued the <ORGANIZATION> Variable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Annuity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- in 1982, charging the Texas-based stock insurance company with failing to disclose the method it used to calculate excess-interest payments. Her `` class action'' lawsuit was filed in behalf of all <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> residents who invested in <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION>'s fixed annuity program between Oct. 17, 1975 and Aug. 2, 1982. The suit contended that the fixed annuity is a `` security,'' and that <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> had violated anti-fraud provisions of federal securities law. A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that the fixed annuity is not a security. But the 7th Circuit court reversed that ruling, reinstating the suit. The appeals court relied, in part, on a 1986 rule issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> providing certain annuities with a `` safe harbor'' exclusion from federal securities law. The appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION>'s fixed annuity did not qualify for such treatment because its excess-interest rate on existing deposits could be changed at any time at <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION>'s discretion. In the appeal acted on today, <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> said, `` The court's ruling will unquestionably increase insurance companies' costs of doing business, which will make annuities more expensive for consumers and limit the availability of these policies.'' The appeal was supported in `` friend-of-the-court'' briefs submitted by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION>. The case is <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> vs. Otto, 87-600.
