<HEAD>Court Gives States Power to Enforce Safety Codes at Nuclear
Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today gave states some power to enforce safety codes at federal nuclear production facilities for hazards unrelated to radiation. The court, in a 6-2 ruling, said a worker injured falling from a scaffold at a nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> is entitled to seek a `` bonus'' compensation award. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, writing for the court, said federal law does not prohibit states from indirectly enforcing safety regulations at federal facilities by awarding supplemental workers' compensation for code violations `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' reluctance to allow direct state regulation of federal projects -LRB- does not bar -RRB- incidental regulatory effects arising from the enforcement of a workers' compensation law, like <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s, that provides an additional award when the injury is caused by the breach of a safety regulation,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. The court ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gaseous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diffusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The federally owned plant enriches and refines nuclear fuel used for civililan energy and for weapons and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> submarines and ships. <PERSON> Esto </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a mechanic, was injured on July 30, 1980, when his glove caught on a bolt protruding from the mobile scaffold on which he was working. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was pulled from the platform and broke his ankle falling to the ground some six feet below. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was awarded $ 9,000 in workmen's compensation. He sought an additional award of between $ 1,328 and $ 4,429 fgrom <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> because, he said, the scaffold was defective and violated <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> safety regulations. The <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1986 that <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> is entitled to seek the additional compensation. Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, in a dissenting opinion written by <PERSON> White </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not intend to expose federal facilities to such state regulation. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not take part in the ruling. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 86-1172.
