<SECOND>PM-Aging Research,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coalition Asks More Funds for Elderly Health Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two senators and an 11-member coalition of health groups called today for increased spending on disorders that afflict senior citizens, saying the money will be needed to cope with `` the largest senior boom in history.'' The Task Force for Aging Research Funding recommended that the nation spend $ 340 million above current levels on research into strokes, Alzheimer's disease and other afflictions. The figure is $ 278 million higher than what President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has requested for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. `` We wo n't be able to accomplish this budget, but we ought to push for it,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's very practical. It's an absolute must when you look at the demographics and the cost'' of health care. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON>, D-Mont., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>, said senior citizens groups are leading the push for the additional spending, but `` it's for the benefit of those to follow'' since the research wo n't bear fruit for 10 to 20 years <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, executive director of the nonpartisan <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, said one-third of the $ 450 billion spent annually on health care is on the 12 percent of the population over 65. With no medical breakthroughs, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said, by the middle of the next century there will be three times more hip fractures, four times as much demand for nursing home beds and eight times as many cases of dementia as in 1980. `` Our goal is not simply a longer life span but a longer health-span,'' he said. In its report, the task force says less than 0.5 percent of the $ 146 billion spent annually on health care for those over 65 goes for research to prevent and treat age-related problems. `` This represents a poor investment strategy for a nation soon to experience the largest senior boom in history,'' the report said. The number of Americans over 85, currently 2.7 million, is expected to double by the end of the century and quadruple in the next 60 years, the task force said. `` We can tinker with changes in the health care delivery system which can produce some savings ... but these savings will not equal the long-term benefits of dramatic medical and scientific changes that will alter the way we experience old age,'' the report said. The task force called for a national focus on research to help lower medical expenses and improve the health of older Americans, including higher investments in basic research and research targeted at specific diseases such as Alzheimer's; faster clinical trials; greater support and training for geriatric medicine; and further study of the psychological, behavioral and sociological aspects of aging. The agencies receiving budget increases under the task force proposal would be the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> on Aging; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neurological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communicative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disorders </ORGANIZATION> and Stroke; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arthritis </ORGANIZATION> and Musculoskeletal and Skin Diseases; and the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Members of the task force are the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>; the Alzheimer's Disease and <ORGANIZATION> Related </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disorders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diabetes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geriatrics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in Immunology and Aging; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in Neurological and Communicative Disorders; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Term </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Osteoporosis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>; and Paralyzed Veterans of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
