<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Child Porn,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees to Consider Reinstating Massachusetts
Child-Pornography Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider reinstating a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> child-pornography law a state court said could be used to prosecute parents who photograph their naked, infant children on the beach. The justices voted to review a <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling, reached by a 4-3 vote, that the state law too broadly interferes with a form of expression. The state court ruling overturned the criminal conviction in <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> of <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> for `` soliciting a child to pose for pornographic purposes.'' Prosecutors said <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> in 1984 induced his 14-year-old stepdaughter to pose for photographs while clothed only in bikini underpants and with a scarf draped around her neck. Police were contacted after the girl's mother discovered the photographs. When <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> appealed, the state's highest court threw out his conviction and dismissed the criminal indictment. The state court's 4-3 majority said photography is a form of expression with which the state may interfere only when the interference serves an important governmental purpose and is narrowly drawn to serve that purpose. Looking at the state law involved, the state court said, `` The overbreadth is substantial. It criminalizes conduct that virtually every person would regard as lawful.'' `` For example,'' the state court added, `` -LRB- the law -RRB- makes a criminal of a parent who takes a frontal view picture of his or her naked one-year-old running on a beach or romping in a wading pool.'' The state court's three dissenters said taking photographs is not a form of expression and the `` narrowly drawn'' test traditionally used in free-speech cases should not have been used. In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said a 1982 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision excluding child pornography from free-speech protections `` established that states are entitled to greater leeway in the regulation of pornographic depictions of children than might be appropriate in other contexts.'' The case is <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, 87-1651.
