<HEAD>Justices Broaden Study of Claimed Deductions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today expanded its study of whether payments made to the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION> by its members may be claimed as federal income tax deductions. The justices, who last month agreed to review the issue, today added one case to its study _ the test case used by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. A <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision is expected sometime next year. Scientologists make payments called `` fixed donations'' to the church. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says such payments for `` auditing'' and training sessions are not charitable contributions that can be counted as tax deductions. Scientologists say the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has singled out their church for unfair treatment and is interfering with their religious freedom. Federal law allows taxpayers to reduce their tax liability by declaring various deductions, including money or things of value given to charities or religious organizations. But such a payment is not tax-deductible if something of value is received in return. A practice within the Church of Scientology is a process known as auditing, in which members are expected to reach a higher level of spiritual awareness. Auditing is administered in a one-to-one session in which the church member's skin responses to questions are measured by an electronic device. Each branch of the church charges a `` fixed donation'' for training and auditing sessions, and almost never waives the payment requirement. The <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the fixed donations required by the church are not tax-deductible contributions but instead are non-deductible payments made for services. That ruling was upheld by the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in a case involving <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION> members <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rialto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The high court today said it will use the appeal of those three individuals to help it resolve conflicting rulings on the tax issue by federal appeals courts. The case is <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> vs. Commissioner of Internal Revenue, 87-1616.
