<HEAD>Congress' Sudden Hot Issue: Home Health Care for Everyone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public concern over the cost of longterm illnesses has become the driving force behind Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>'s determined campaign to force <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to vote on his plan to expand <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> _ and <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> taxes _ to cover the expenses of home health care With polls claiming enormous support for a government program to address those concerns, longterm-care proposals are proliferating on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` This issue is one that voters will carry into the ballot box,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Fried </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of 100 organizations with affiliates in 35 states. `` Virtually every family stands at risk of needing longterm home care at any time, and none of us are protected very well against that eventuality,'' Fried said. `` It cuts across age lines, it cuts across economic lines, it cuts across whether people view themselves as liberals or conservatives. This is what the population wants.'' Pepper's five-year, $ 30 billion proposal would expand <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> to pay for various home care services for the chronically ill of all ages. It would be financed by subjecting all income to the 1.45 percent Medicare payroll tax; currently only income up to $ 45,000 is taxed. No deductible or co-payment requirement would be imposed. Business interests are critical, partly because they would have to match the additional Medicare tax payments. And budget watchdogs predict the financing mechanism will prove inadequate, leading to higher deficits or costly premiums and co-payments. The plan advanced by Pepper, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., is encountering a lot of competition Rep. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Regula </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, has proposed what is likely to be the House Republican alternative: a $ 25 million, 30-month demonstration program in five geographically diverse sites. Medicare would pay 80 percent of home-care costs after a $ 500 deductible is met. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on health, has offered a plan of his own. Medicare would pay up to $ 2,000 for respite care; 80 percent of the cost of home health care after a $ 500 deductible is met; and 70 percent of nursing home costs after a two-year exclusionary period. And Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., plans to introduce an $ 18.6 billion Medicare expansion called `` Lifecare. The program would pay for home care services and six months of nursing home care with no co-payments or deductibles, and 35 percent of subsequent nursing home care, minus the cost of room and board. But Pepper's bill is the only one heading for quick action, probably early next month, for several reasons: He is chairman of the powerful Rules Committee; at 87, the oldest <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member, he is revered by senior citizens across the country as their advocate and he has campaigned for many of his colleagues. `` I'm trying to cooperate ... provided they do n't make us wait too long'' for a vote, <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> said last week. `` We're getting almost to the edge of our endurance.'' Initially, Pepper planned to offer his bill as an amendment to a catastrophic health plan designed to help the elderly deal with the heavy cost of acute illness. But <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders feared that tactic would sink the whole bill. Pepper withheld his proposal in return for Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s promise of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor vote on it Ordinarily, the bill would have gone to the Ways and <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, but <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> sped the bill out of his <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last November and has been waiting ever since. Ways and Means Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., doe n't hide his distaste for Pepper's bill He contends it is too expensive and technically flawed and should go through his committee for review. There is little doubt, given the political climate, that <ORGANIZATION> Pepper </ORGANIZATION>'s bill will win <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passage. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said, `` We'll do the best we can as fast as we can. Maybe it'll be this year, maybe it'll be next year. We do n't have to have a deadline.'' Those who work closely with Pepper say it is a mistake to count him out this year. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, staff director of a health subcommittee chaired by Pepper, noted that half the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> are up for re-election and longterm care is a staple on the campaign trail this year. She said a similar atmosphere existed two years ago when Pepper pushed through a bill outlawing mandatory retirement.
