<HEAD>Dino Grandi, Fascist Who Opposed Mussolini, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dino </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON>, who lost out to <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> in a 1921 bid for leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and helped depose the dictator in 1943, has died at the age of 92. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> died at his home in <LOCATION> Bologna </LOCATION> on Saturday, the state-run RAI-TV said. He had reportedly been suffering cardiac and circulatory problems. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> fought in World War I and joined the fascist squads that terrorized the Italian countryside. He failed to win the leadership of the fascists at a national congress in 1921 but successfully made a bid for a seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. He participated in the October 1922 march on <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> that led to <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>'s installation as head of government. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> served as undersecretary of the interior in 1924 and was foreign minister from 1929 to 1934. <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> clashed with <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>, urging him to support <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and not <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in World War II and opposing <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s active participation in the campaign. He urged King <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> to remove <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> from government. In July 1943, <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> presented the government resolution that deposed <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> later headed a puppet government, supported by the German Nazis, in northern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, until he was captured and hanged by Italian partisans in April 1945. A fascist tribunal in 1944 condemned <PERSON> Grandi </PERSON> to death but he had escaped to <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> and went on to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. No funeral plans were announced. News of <PERSON> Grandi </P