<HEAD>Reagan To Ask Gorbachev Support For Ban On Arms Sales To Iran,
Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, currying favor with <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, is likely to balk if President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asks him to back a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution barring arms sales to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say. The <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war is expected to be on the agenda when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> meet May 29-June 2 in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Soviets went along with a U.S.-sponsored <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution in July 1987 urging <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to end the war, which began in September 1980. The Soviets and the Chinese, however, have refused to support a followup resolution to stop the flow of arms to the belligerents. `` The chances of passing that resolution peaked about February or early March,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition he not be identified. Because <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> wants to continue the war, and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> wants to end it, the second resolution `` would amount to a de facto embargo on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' the official said. Also, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> does not want to offend <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, particularly as Soviet troops leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> remain at loggerheads in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, the experts say. The Soviets and the Chinese are key because they are permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and could veto any resolution. The Chinese, who supply <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> with close to half of its weapons, eased their opposition in February, increasing pressure on the Soviets, who are the major arms supplier to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. But pressure on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> fell after the U.S.-Iranian naval battle on April 18, in which American ships killed 44 Iranians and knocked out half the opposing navy by disabling two Iranian frigates and sinking or damaging four speed boats. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action in the gulf pushed the Chinese and the Russians away from backing the resolution,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source. `` The Russians had always been reluctant on the second resolution, but this gave them something to hang their hat on.'' <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> rode to power in 1979 on a wave of indignation against <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>, a long-time <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ally, but the ayatollah paired his vehement condemnation of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Satan </LOCATION>,'' with anti-Soviet rhetoric that was nearly as strong. Soviet-Iranian relations improved somewhat following the disclosure in November 1986 that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration secretly had sold arms to the <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> regime. And ties between <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> further improved after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision last year to offer naval protection to 11 reflagged tankers belonging to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, a non-belligerent ally of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the war. Lately, however, `` there has been nothing really terribly new'' in <LOCATION> Soviet-Iranian </LOCATION> ties, said <PERSON> Shireen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, an expert on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> faces a ticklish situation as he fulfills his promise to withdraw an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which not only borders <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, but shares much of its cultural, ethnic and linguistic heritage. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s cooperation is vital in repatriating 2.5 million Afghans who fled to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> following the Soviet invasion in 1979. An additional 3.5 million Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> pose a similar problem. Iranian cooperation also would assist the Soviets in assuring `` that a neutral state is established in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>. `` The Russians do not want a pro-Western government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' Additionally, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has been backing several groups of anti-Soviet Afghan guerrillas who share his fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> Moslem faith. As the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> pulls back from forward positions in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, `` the Iranians have the capability to make life difficult for the Soviets, at least in the outlying areas,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source. In at least one instance, the mujahedden guerrillas and the Soviets appear to have worked out a modus vivendi. `` The mujahedeen have been distributing leaflets in the area of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION> -LRB- in eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> -RRB- saying they will allow the Soviets to leave peacefully if the Soviets do not loot civilian houses as they depart,'' said the source, citing a diplomatic cable from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Similar arrangements may exist elsewhere in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.
