<HEAD>First Drug Treatment Center Scrapped After Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s first in-patient drug abuse treatment center has been scrapped following protests from residents, one of whom said addicts should be shot `` like vermin,'' a weekly newspaper reported. The treatment center was to have been housed in a small castle in <LOCATION> Tuchomerice </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, according to the popular weekly, <PERSON> Vlasta </PERSON>. Opposition grew rapidly once word of the plans spread in a TV broadcast before authorities informed residents, <PERSON> Vlasta </PERSON> said. `` The TV statement was premature, ill-considered and resulted in hysteria,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Klima </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> health official. `` Complaints poured in, then came a signature campaign of those protesting the plan _ simply, enormous pressure.'' He said the castle instead will be a center for the elderly, he said. <PERSON> Vlasta </PERSON> quoted unidentified doctors as complaining that drug addicts now can be treated only in a psychiatric ward in a <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> suburb or at a center for alcoholics. <PERSON> Vlasta </PERSON> first reported on drug addicts last fall and said its stories on the Tuchomerice case brought `` an unprecedented response'' from readers. Some letters were sympathetic, but others used strong language. `` I would send them to forced labor or shoot them like vermin,'' wrote one unidentified reader. Only recently has drug abuse been discussed in the state-run media. In 1986, according to the latest statistics, 703 people were prosecuted on drugs-related charges, <PERSON> Vlasta </PERSON> said. It gave no figures for <LOCATION> Slovakia </LOCATION>.
