<HEAD>Party Meeting Shaping Up as Face-off on Reform Pace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Next month's <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference is shaping up to be a face-off between supporters of radical change and advocates of just `` a little polishing up'' of the old Soviet system, party activists reported Monday. Despite efforts by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to draw only backers of his policy of `` perestroika,'' or wholesale rebuilding of Soviet society, some who fear reform is being introduced too quickly may be selected as delegates to the June 28 conference. A closed-door meeting of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> devoted to preparations for next month's conference selected <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to deliver the key address to the gathering, which will pass judgment on his reform program, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. But senior advisers on the economy and social trends made clear at a news conference that conflicting viewpoints on the pace of reform are becoming more apparent. It has not even been decided whether the party gathering _ the first of its kind since 1941 _ will be televised, according to delegate <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zalygin </PERSON>, editor of the journal Novy Mir -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> addressed the plenary session of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> before and after a debate among the more than 300 members, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. No details of his or other speeches were released. Kremlin No. 2 <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> told a foreign policy meeting later in the day that the plenum had `` a very interesting and lively debate'' over the proposals to be presented at the conference. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> has made clear in previous speeches that he favors a more moderate pace of reform. The theses put together by the ruling 13-man Politburo make `` a number of important suggestions and proposals relative to the implementation of perestroika, glasnost, democratization and the implementation of a healthy political atmosphere,'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said. He gave no details, but said the proposals will be published before the conference. Four of the nation's most respected advisers on perestroika told reporters the conference is heightening differences among policy-makers. <PERSON> Tatiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaslavskaya </PERSON>, the nation's leading sociologist and a staunch reform advocate, said if perestroika is to succeed, `` we will have to fight and struggle for it to see that we meet these goals.'' She indicated there are two groups which want perestroika carried out differently. Asked who heads the factions, Ms. <PERSON> Zaslavskaya </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is obviously the figurehead for the radical-reform branch, but she said she did not know any leading `` personalities at the head of the other movement.'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> is reputed to champion more conservative views on the Politburo, and last month was reported to have had a showdown with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> following publication of a defense of Stalinism in the party newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION>. But he has made several high-profile appearances, including his parliamentary address Monday, indicating he and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are putting out a unified front leading up to the important conference. In an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that was published Sunday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> labeled as `` Western media'' creations those accounts that he and <PERSON> Legachev </PERSON> are locked in a struggle for power, although he acknowledged that `` heated debate'' has developed over perestroika within the nation. Party conferences, which consider major changes in direction in social and economic development, can be called between party congresses, which take place every five years. They were held frequently until World War II. Ms. <PERSON> Zaslavskaya </PERSON> appeared to criticize the party's monopoly on power when asked about the system for selecting the 5,000 delegates to the conference. `` The fact that the party delegates are selected by the party machinery, by the party committees, effects the procedure, and not in every case can it be called a democratic effect,'' she said. It was not clear whether she was advocating extension of the delegate selection into non-party groups or criticizing some of the officials chosen. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms curry much less favor in rural regions and industrial zones outside the capital, where many entrenched party bureaucrats fear their jobs and privileges hang in the balance. In those areas, party conference delegates are likely to oppose radical change. On May 7, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealed for selection of those who would support his approach to reform. `` There must be no more quotas, as were the case in the past, specifying how many factory workers and farmers and how many women are to be elected, among others,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told a gathering of media representatives and ideologists. `` The principal political directive is to elect active supporters of perestroika to go to the conference.'' Little is known about the proposals to be put before the party conference next month, although several officials have said the delegates will consider limiting the tenure of the general secretary. There has also been speculation that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> might take the opportunity to replace as much as 25 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, ousting those who have not shown sufficient dedication to his reform programs. But <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON>, a prominent political scientist and writer, told the news conference that `` as far as I know there would not be additional elections during this party conference.'' <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Zaslavskaya </PERSON> and the other two officials who appeared at the news conference, is in the running to attend the party conference, although the selection procedures have not been completed. `` From my point of view the most important struggle is between those who want deep changes and others who want a little polishing up,'' <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> said. `` The struggle is continuing in these areas.'' Economist <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> restated <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s philosophy that economic change and broader democracy must go hand in hand. `` One without the other is unthinkable,'' <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said.
