y to the need for `` socialist pluralism'' in which opposing views would be allowed. It outlined the advantages of more foreign investment and joint ventures with foreign companies. Among political reforms endorsed were limited terms of office for party officials and laws guaranteeing freedom of association and other civil rights. `` The right of voluntary organization, assembly, association, freedom of conscience and religion ... and guarantees for the protection of individual and collective rights must be regulated by law,'' it said. A leading proponent of independent interest groups, <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, was among those elected to the ruling Politburo. The pollicy statement acknowledged his recent comments by saying local referendums should be held on issues of importance to Hungarians. Many interest groups have been formed recently that do not seek official approval and range in nature from sports groups to an independent labor union. Another notable appointment to the Politburo was <PERSON> Reszo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, the economist who pioneered reform in the late 1960s. He was ousted from the party's ruling body in in 1973 for advocating further changes. Thirty-one members of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, nearly one-third of the total, were replaced by young intellectuals and workers. Few came from the party bureaucracy. Six members of the Politburo are new, including two women, and the membership was reduced from 13 to 11. Its first meeting was scheduled for Tuesday.
