<HEAD>Oxford Blues: Prestigious Posts Vacant Due to Money Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it is leaving two of the world's most prestigious academic posts vacant indefinitely, citing a financial crisis. The regius chairs in Greek and modern history become vacant in fall 1989 and wo n't be filled for at least a year, said <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> spokeswoman. She said the regius chairs _ so named because they were created by royal command _ could remain frozen beyond 1990, depending on faculty priorities. The decision heightens longstanding concern over the ancient university's future as a citadel of scholarship and scientific research. `` There is a question mark over our status as a world-class university,'' Sir <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the retiring regius professor of modern history, said in an interview. `` We are being starved of essential resources.'' The regius chair in Greek was founded by King <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> in 1546, and the modern history chair by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> I </PERSON> in 1727. Both are widely regarded as being at the apex of scholarship. They being left vacant as part of a retrenchment program brought on by an 11 percent cut in government funding, Mrs. <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON> said. Under the program, any academic post that becomes vacant is frozen, usually for two years, until the <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> decides whether there is enough money to appoint a successor. As a result, 122 of <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION>'s 1,420 faculty posts in virtually all disciplines are vacant, Mrs. <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON> said. Failure to exempt the professorships in modern history and Greek from the retrenchment reflects the seriousness of <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>'s cash problem. <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> has a budget of about $ 186 million, and its deficit is running at about $ 3.3 million. The university has announced that it will launch a five-year, worldwide campaign in October to ensure the future of the university, which received its first charter in 1213. It has not said how much money it wants to raise in its campaign, but says it hopes to ensure the financial security of the university into the next century. `` <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> is beginning to seem like a place under siege,'' the author A.N. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> wrote Monday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. Commenting on the professorial vacancies, the deterioration of books and manuscripts in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>'s Bodleian Library and the planned closure of <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Playhouse </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said: `` When you have a university which ca n't afford professors of Greek and history; which ca n't afford to repair the priceless books on its library shelves; which ca n't afford to keep open one of the most famous undergraduate theaters in the world, then you are entitled to ask: What is going on?'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, who is retiring one year early to take up a newly created chair in military history at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1989, said his post could remain vacant for several years. `` There's simply not enough money to go around,'' he said. <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 44 other state-funded universities have long complained that spending limits imposed by the Conservative government are threatening the nation's scientific base and accelerating a brain drain to foreign universities. Critics say the government is denying support for research that has no apparent short-term economic or military benefit. In a 1985 protest, <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> denied an honorary doctorate to Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, herself an Oxford graduate in chemistry. `` There is a lack of understanding of the value of scholarship as an end of itself, irrespective of whether it contributes to the national income or not,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. Government officials contend the universities are overly dependent on state funding and have refused to aggressively pursue money from industry or even their own alumni. The regius professor of Greek, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd-Jones </PERSON>, who is leaving next year at the mandatory retirement age of 67, said the failure to name his replacement goes beyond government policy, and reflects the values of society at large. `` We have a society in which a footballer gets four times as much as Sir <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> and I get together,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd-Jones </PERSON>. `` Someone who displays himself on television can get 10 times as much.'' The base salary for each regius chair is about $ 48,620 a year. <PERSON> Lloyd-Jones </PERSON> said the vacant posts should serve as `` a reminder to anyone who thinks that we in the 20th century live in a civilized society.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> is moving fast to become self-sufficient, but `` there is a limit to what we can do over the short term.''
