<HEAD>Court To Study States' Power to Regulate Natural Gas Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 4, At issue, and graf 11, The use-it-or-lose-it, to
CORRECT spelling of Hugoton.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed Monday to study the power of states to regulate natural gas production, including `` use-it-or-lose-it'' rules designed to stimulate production. The court will review a ruling that upheld the power of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> officials to control production from what is believed to be the largest natural gas reservoir in the world. The justices are not expected to decide the case until 1989. The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 upheld rules adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that officials said would encourage production, prevent economic and physical waste and protect the rights of producers. At issue is gas from the <LOCATION> Hugoton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, which extends across portions of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. About two-thirds of the field is in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, containing some 4,000 wells as of 1983. Most of the gas is carried outside the state through pipelines. The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> since 1944 imposed rules aimed at assuring that each well will ultimately produce approximately the amount of gas underlying the land held by each leaseholder. The idea was to treat well owners equally, since gas can migrate underground from an underproducing area to a well that is overproducing. To assure equal treatment, the state fixed the maximum amount of gas that can be produced per month from each well. In practice, wells can not always be operated to meet monthly ceilings for various reasons. For example, a well may be shut in or there may be low demand in a given month and therefore the well underproduces. To allow for these variables, state officials permitted owners of underproducing wells to `` save up'' their production ceilings _ creating what are called `` underages'' _ and overproduce in future months to make up for shortfalls. To create a production incentive, the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> commission changed the rules in 1983 by declaring that underages must be used within specified periods of years or they would be canceled. The use-it-or-lose-it rule was challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the major buyers of the <ORGANIZATION> Hugoton </ORGANIZATION> gas for transport outside the state. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> said the 1983 rule change prevents it from purchasing gas reserves that it is entitled to by contract. The pipeline company said cancellation of the underages means that it unfairly may lose reservoirs of gas when they migrate underground and later are replaced by other migrating supplies. The pipeline company asked the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to strike down the 1983 regulations on grounds that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has exclusive authority over natural gas production. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration sided with <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> officials in urging the high court not to disturb the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> commission lawfully is regulating production and is not directly regulating the interstate pipeline companies that are subject to federal authority. The department said the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> case is distinct from a decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 that added a new limitation on states' power to regulate natural gas prices The court said then that <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> may not require an interstate pipeline to buy gas from all owners of a common gas pool when the pipeline had pre-existing contracts with only some of the owners. The case acted on Monday is <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, 86-1856.
</TEXT>
