<HEAD>Vote Tuesday On New Tahoe City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STATELINE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in several resort communities decide Tuesday whether to form a new city to be called <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>, a measure opposed by casinos but favored by residents demanding more for their taxes. The new city, with a population of about 6,500, would embrace the gambling resort of <LOCATION> Stateline </LOCATION> and would be situated along 15 miles of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>'s southeastern shore. Fewer than 3,000 registered voters in the <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> are expected to go to the polls Tuesday to decide on the measure, which has generated some 20 years of debate, hearings and court battles. If the plan is approved, another election will be held to organize the government. Proponents of the new city say the lakeshore communities comprise nearly 25 percent of the county's population while contributing 60 percent of the tax revenue. They say they do not receive a proportionate share in services. `` We want to keep our tax dollars here,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bigham </PERSON>, a leader of the movement to create the city <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Nino </PERSON>, leader of the opposition, said a city government will only raise taxes without a corresponding improvement in services The opposition has received financial support from the <LOCATION> Stateline </LOCATION> casinos, whose tax burden <PERSON> Nino </PERSON> said would rise by at least $ 300,000 yearly under a city government. `` What will they get for it? Not much,'' he added. <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> commissioners also advised against the idea. The county has said it stands to lose about $ 1.8 million in yearly tax revenue, most of it from the big <LOCATION> Stateline </LOCATION> casinos, if voters approve the plan, because property and gaming taxes will shift from the county to city. The plan also produced an unsuccessful challenge in state court last year and complaints from communities in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, on the western side of the lake, that the name <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Tahoe </PERSON> would create confusion in the public mind between <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> the lake and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> the city. The new city, which would embrace such communities as <LOCATION> Glenbrook </LOCATION>, Zephyr Cove, <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, Cave Rock and <PERSON> Marla </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON>, could n't start its business before July 1, 1989.
