<HEAD>Golden Temple Opened to Public After Bloody Siege</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh worshipers sobbed as they entered the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> on Monday for the first time since the sacred shrine was reopened after a two-week siege in which at least 46 people died, a city official said. Over 15,000 Sikh men, women and children waited solemnly in the 113-degree heat as security officials frisked them for weapons before allowing them to enter the 400-year-old temple. It was closed during a police siege May 9-18 aimed at driving Sikh separatists from their hiding places inside. At least 46 people, mostly Siklh militants, died during the clashes. Amitsar deputy commissioner <PERSON> Sarabjeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said no incidents of violence were reported Monday. `` We had a few emotional ourbrusts by some of the devotees,'' he added. Some wept as they walked past the rooms from which Sikh radicals shot back at <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> security men during the siege. `` I knew some of the boys, they were brave, maybe misguided,'' said <PERSON> Harbans </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 70, a Sikh farmer. `` The government operation has hurt our sentiment, there was no need to kill so many people,'' said Surinder Kaur of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> quoted a majority of the worshipers praising the government action. Religious services in the inner sanctum of the temple, suspended on the second day of the siege, were resumed Sunday after volunteers washed the floor of the temple with milk in a cleansing ritual. Police and paramilitary troops cordoned off the shrine to enforce a curfew still imposed on the area within 300 yards of its walls. Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said the cordon would be lifted after the government reaches an agreement with temple officials to stop the shrine from being used as a hideout for Sikh radicals. Sikh gunmen, meanwhile, shot and killed four people in other parts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state in overnight attacks, police said. Among the victims was a Hindu school headmaster, <PERSON> Tilak </PERSON> <PERSON> Raj </PERSON>, who was shot and killed Monday by two Sikh radicals in front of 400 students in the town of <LOCATION> Sangatpura </LOCATION>, 15 miles north of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. The assailants ordered him out of his office and shot him at point-blank range with a revolver, according to <PERSON> Gurmeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a police officer. A note left by the <ORGANIZATION> Khalistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commando </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, the most powerful of the Sikh separatist groups, said <PERSON> Raj </PERSON> was killed to avenge the siege of the Golden Temple. The note said more killings would follow. Sikh separatists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for an independent Sikh homeland in this agricultural state, where they form a majority of the population. The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s warring Hindus and Moslems, make up 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people. They claim they are discriminated against by the majority, which is 80 percent Hindu. Monday's killings raised to more than 1,150 the number of people killed by Sikh extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state since the start of the year. In 1987, 1,030 people were killed.
