<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Lining Up Business Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whose relations with the business community have been mixed during his tenure as Massachussetts governor, is not willing to concede business support to its traditional home in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Business leaders aligned with the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> front-runner's campaign hope to sign up a minimum of 5,000 executives nationwide for a national business coalition, with group leaders appearing on behalf of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at conventions and other events <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, with his entrepreneurial background and Republican pedigree, has a ready-made base of support in the business arena. But organizers of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> effort, to be officially announced when leadership roles are filled, say their venture into traditionally Republican circles has been well received because of dissatisfaction with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's handling of the trade and budget deficits. `` The conventional question about the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s candidates is their ability to make the hard economic decisions, the business decisions,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, a wealthy businessman and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' top fund-raiser `` For the first time in 20 years, we've got a candidate with credibility on the economy and a record of fiscal responsibility.'' The first phase of the effort involves recruiting professionals who have donated to the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign. Farmer has given <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Giesser </PERSON>, who is organizing the coalition, lists of contributors with business ties. `` That's where you start,'' said Farmer. `` If you already bet $ 2 on a horse race you're apt to root for that horse all the way around the track.'' <PERSON> Giesser </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachussetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, declined to list prospective members of the group. Among <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> businessmen working with <PERSON> Giesser </PERSON> are <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullinane </PERSON>, the founder and president of computer software maker <ORGANIZATION> Cullinet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Another recent addition is prominent <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, who promised to recruit 400 to 500 business officials in his state `` I think we will be able to organize such a group around the country that -LRB- it -RRB- will surprise people,'' said <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, who met with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> last week. `` Much of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> takes business for granted,'' he said. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, a political analyst at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, termed it unlikely that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> could pull support of a majority of top business leaders. `` But I think you're going to find that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is going to have some success in getting serious business support,'' he said. `` It can help. He's running the umbrella type campaign and trying to keep the umbrella as big as possible. The more support he gets from credible people in business and other groups, the more credence people will give to his message.'' <PERSON> Hensen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cullinane </PERSON> are among <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' top business backers in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> _ proponents of public-private partnerships that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has promoted to steer companies to economically struggling areas of the state. Many other high-tech officials have long battled <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on issues ranging from state spending to environmental policy, and small businessmen lately have criticized a new state law that requires most employers to give workers health insurance by 1992. Even his detractors believe <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will have at least limited success in lining up business support. `` We've been saying for some time that he has been overspending,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` But how many business people in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> are really going to care about that?'' The council was established in 1977, near the end of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' first term as governor, by high tech executives dissatisfied with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' record on taxes and economic development Lobbying pressure from the influential group led to several economic development programs that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> now touts on the campaign trail. Members of the high-tech group also have complained that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> takes too much credit for the state economy. But <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said the so-called `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> miracle'' and political momentum will attract business officials to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` Business and labor and every other constituency will be anxious to be with a winner,'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. `` That's human nature.''
