<FIRST>r i AM-Tate     05-23 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tate,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Royal Visit Symbolizes Port City's Rebirth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rum warehouse converted into a new Tate Gallery of modern art opens Tuesday as the crown jewel in the revived waterfront of this economically depressed port city. Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> accepted <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>'s invitation to open the `` Tate of the North,'' a permanent gallery housing more than 200 20th century works of art from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Tate Gallery. `` The prince's visit is symbolic of the turnaround in our city,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have been hit hard and we are delighted that His Royal Highness is coming here just as the tide is starting to flow economically again in <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>'s direction,'' he said in an interview. The Tate is on 140-year-old <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dock </PERSON> in the city that was founded on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> trade in cotton, tobacco, sugar, rum and African slaves. It is named after its Victorian benefactor, sugar cane magnate Sir <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, a Liverpudlian whose sugar was imported through the docks. The new northern gallery is the first endeavor by a state museum in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to show its works on a large scale outside the capital city. `` We will change the displays and exhibitions every nine months and I expect half a million visitors a year,'' said curator <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>. `` The aim has been to take works out of storage and put them in a place where they would be of benefit.'' The first displays include surrealist art such as <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s `` Lobster Telephone,'' British sculpture of the past 20 years and a room of abstract paintings by the late American <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON>. `` I am absolutely delighted at this move,'' said Sir <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowness </PERSON>, who directs the Tate Gallery holdings of 40,000 works, representing all British art and international 20th century art. `` Our space in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> is large enough to show only about 15 percent of our modern art _ because modern art works tend to be big _ and <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> will raise that to 25 percent.'' The international council of the Museum of Modern Art in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> visited <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> on Saturday to see how the five-story warehouse of red bricks and stone, supported by cast-iron columns, was converted at a cost of nearly $ 14 million by architect <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stirling </PERSON>. `` It was filthy and ruinous when I saw it, with dead pigeons lying everywhere, the roof collapsed and water pouring in,'' <PERSON> Stirling </PERSON> said. `` I was glad to work on it, as it is perhaps the most magnificent dock of its type ever built in this country.'' Said gallery staffer <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, 23: `` My friends here have a bit of a giggle about modern art, which is an unknown quantity in <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>.'' `` But there's a great spirit of pride in this city, and not just because we're the Beatles' hometown. We all want to get involved in helping it,'' she added. Government and business moved to help <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> with millions of pounds in cash grants in 1977 after the decline of the docks, shipbuilding and automaking. Investment expanded after 1981 riots by the unemployed in the <LOCATION> Toxteth </LOCATION> district led to one death, 3,000 arrests and streets of homes and shops set ablaze. The city of 476,500 people still has a jobless rate of 25 percent and is having to overcome a history of strikes and leftist political anarchy on the city council. Keynote of the revival is the transformation of the once-abandoned city center docks along the <LOCATION> Mersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> river </LOCATION> into a leisure area of museums, shops, offices, apartments and businesses. `` The first sign we had that things were changing was one year ago when employers reported shortages of skilled workers,'' said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. The docks are busy again because <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> businessmen are realizing that <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> is still the nearest port to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
