<FIRST>u a AM-CancerExperiments Bjt   05-23 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Experiments, Bjt,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Institute Hopes To Double Number of Patients in Cancer
Experments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will try to double over the next four years the number of patients who receive experimental treatments in an effort to speed up the search for ways to stop the biggest cancer killers. Largely because of physicians' reluctance to enroll their patients in cancer experiments, officials said, it may take 10 years or longer to assess the value of promising new therapies. `` We are not getting enrolled anywhere near the number of patients we need to get answers within a reasonable period of time,'' Dr. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of the cancer institute, said at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oncology </ORGANIZATION>. Currently, about 25,000 cancer patients each year are enrolled in treatment experiments, known as clinical trials, that are sponsored by the cancer institute. Through appeals to doctors and directly to the public, the institute hopes to double this by 1992. Clinical trials are medicine's primary way of figuring out whether new drugs and combinations of surgery and radiation are better than the standard ways of coping with the disease. Typically, patients are randomly assigned to have the standard treatment or the new form of therapy. Only about 1 percent of patients with colon or breast cancer are currently enrolled in clinical trials. <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> said the institute hopes to increase this to 10 percent. The goal is to enroll all the patients who will take part in an experiment within one year, instead of over three, five or even 10 years, as often now happens. Once patients are enrolled, doctors must wait five years to see which treatment worked best. <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> said patients are often worried about taking part in cancer experiments. `` The public is confused,'' he said. `` They think they are guinea pigs, that they will get nothing and we'll just watch their tumors grow. That's not the case.'' Instead, <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> maintained that participants in clinical trials get the best available treatment, even if they are assigned to the comparison group that does n't get the experimental therapy. However, experts said that the unwillingness of doctors, not patients, is the primary obstacle to increasing the number of patients in clinical trials. Dr. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>, who has been conducting clinical trials since the 1950s, said doctors often want to stick with the style of care they learned in medical school and are also afraid they will lose control of their patients' treatments Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wittes </PERSON>, head of the cancer institute's Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program, added, `` The main problem of participating in trials is that they take time.'' He said physicians are reluctant to spend time explaining the treatment trials to their patients and keeping up with the paper work involved. Another study, presented at the conference, suggested that many doctors believe they already know what kind of treatment is best. Dr. <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> of Princess <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> surveyed 300 physicians in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> who treat cancer of the bladder, kidneys and prostate gland. Seventy percent responded that if they had one of these kinds of cancer, they would not enroll themselves in a clinical trial. Instead, they would prefer the kind of therapy they already offer their patients. <PERSON> Wittes </PERSON> said the cancer institute is trying to appeal to doctors' sense of public duty `` We are saying, ` You will do good for society, and you will do good for your patients.''' <PERSON> Wittes </PERSON> said the cancer institute will concentrate at first in enrolling more patients in clinical trials of new treatments for <PERSON> non-Hodgkin </PERSON>'s lymphoma and cancers of the breast, colon, rectum and bladder.
</TEXT>
