<HEAD>New Rules Proposed for Liability When Carcasses Condemned for
Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed change in federal regulations would hold farmers and others in the marketing chain financially accountable for livestock carcasses condemned at slaughter plants because of illegally high traces of drugs, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. B.H. `` Bill'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Packers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stockyards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposal is intended to deter the sale of medicated aniamls for slaughter and shift economic responsibility for illegal drug residues from the meat packer to those who cause the violation. Under the proposal, a meat packer would be able to `` bill back'' the person from whom the livestock was bought if it is condemned because of illegal drug residues. In order to make the plan work, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said, each purchaser or selling agency in the marketing chain would be permitted to use the bill-back procedure. If a seller failed to settle up, the buyer or selling agency would be permitted to deduct from a subsequent purchase from the same person. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said that although a small percentage of livestock producers are selling medicated animals for slaughter, the illegally high drug residues continue to be a problem, notably in swine, culled dairy cows and young calves. The proposal will be open 60 days for public comment. Those can be sent to: <ORGANIZATION> Packers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stockyards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, Room 3039-S, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20250.
