<HEAD>First Soviets Visit Western European Chemical Warfare Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Soviet-Summit, Bjt
^By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Monday welcomed the first Soviet delegation to visit a chemical warfare facility in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Thirteen Soviet scientists and military experts will spend three days inspecting <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s chemical warfare defense center and related facilities in southwestern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and talking with British chemical weapons experts. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> stopped making chemical weapons in the 1950s and destroyed its stockpiles in 1957. The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said it will be the first exchange visit on chemical weapons between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and a Western European country. `` It is intended that the full range of chemical warfare-related issues should be discussed ... including production, assessment of the chemical warfare hazards, storage, trials, detection, protection, monitoring, decontamination, medical countermeasures and disposal,'' said <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, minister of state for the Armed Forces. The visiting delegation is led by <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON>, the chief Soviet negotiatior at the <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Disarmament and includes Maj. Gen. R.F. <PERSON> Razuvanov </PERSON>, commander of the Soviet chemical establishment in <LOCATION> Shikhany </LOCATION>, located on the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. The Soviets will visit the <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at Porton Down, which sprawls across 7,000 acres on <LOCATION> Salisbury </LOCATION> plain near the ancient Stonehenge monument, about 80 miles southwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Since <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s stockpiles have been destroyed, Porton Down now does only defensive work, making protective equipment such as gas masks, clothing and monitoring instruments for the armed forces and developing antidotes to chemical weapons. The Soviets also will visit the nearby <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where applied microbiological research is conducted, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> Defense Nuclear Biological and <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where instructors are trained to use defensive equipment to counter chemical weapons. In return, British scientists will in July visit the Soviet chemical warfare facility in <LOCATION> Shikhany </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> proposed the exchange in 1986, before the Soviets acknowledged that they possess chemical weapons. In early 1987, the Soviets conceded they have a chemical weapons stockpile amounting to 50,000 tons and accepted the British invitation later that year. Western estimates, however, put the Soviet stockpile at 300,000 tons _ the largest in the world. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which has been in the forefront of negotiations to achieve a worldwide ban on chemical weapons, said last week that such a ban, as well as reductions in conventional forces, must come before any further negotiations on cutting nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the only other country that acknowledges possessing chemical weapons, ended an 18-year moratorium on their manufacture in December and has an estimated stockpile of 30,000 tons. The massive Soviet stockpile has been a major stumbling block at the 40-nation <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. A 1925 <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> protocol bans the use of chemical arms.
