 An estimated 80,000 peasants marched on a half dozen <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> cities Monday, demanding land, nationalization of foreign oil companies and an end to what they call the army's `` dirty war'' against them. The military said leftist guerrillas organized the protests. There have been 20 peasant marches in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> in the last year. This is the first time the protests were aimed at foreign oil companies. There are approximately 30 such companies here. Newspapers and radio chains with reporters accompanying the peasants estimated the total number of protesters as about 80,000. In <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, the capital, troops occupied <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s national university after the rector, <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Palacio </PERSON>, said young people with guns organized protests that led to cars being stoned and to university property being destroyed. Peasants marched on the northern cities of <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Valledupar </LOCATION>, on <LOCATION> Bucaramanga </LOCATION> in the east and on <LOCATION> Barrancabermeja </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. In another development, guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> threw a bomb and hijacked a bus in the northwest city of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, police there reported. A police release said little damage was caused by the bomb explosion Sunday night at the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> headquarters of a banana plantation owners' association. Banana growers and banana pickers have been at odds for months. Right-wing death squads have killed 95 workers. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, known as the <ORGANIZATION> ELN </ORG