<HEAD>U.S. Farm Exports to Soviet Union Expected To Rise Sharply This
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural exports to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this year is expected to be at a three-year high of $ 1.4 billion, up 50 percent from $ 938 million in calendar 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` Behind the gain will be much larger wheat shipments at higher prices and much bigger soybean and soybean meal sales,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Farm product sales to the Soviets exceeded $ 1.9 billion in 1985 but plummeted to a 13-year-low of $ 658 million in 1986 before starting their rebound. A major factor has been large sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices under the department's Export Enhancement Program. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> value share of Soviet grain imports may be above 30 percent for the first time since 1984 and -LRB- may comprise -RRB- over 8 percent of total agricultural imports,'' the report said. Although total Soviet agricultural imports may increase 5 percent in 1988 from last year's estimated $ 16 billion, the value still will be below the $ 19 billion average during the first half of the 1980s. `` Grain imports now cost about $ 3 billion a year instead of $ 7 billion as in 1981-85,'' the report said. Despite a possible 20 percent rise in the per-ton cost of imported grain in 1988, this `` unit value'' will still be around one-third lower in the early 1980s. Earlier this month, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> forecast 1988 Soviet grain output at 215 million metric tons, up 2 percent from last year. It also would be the third consecutive harvest of more than 200 millon tons, a historic first for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Crops are off to a much better start than in 1987 following a good fall sowing, overwintering and spring planting conditions,'' Monday's analysis said. `` Barring unusually severe weather through the spring and fall, 1988 crop output should increase.''
