<HEAD>Envoy Says US Will Continue Seeking Iran Arms Embargo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDEL-JALIL MUSTAFA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American envoy <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said Monday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will continue pushing for an arms embargo on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> unless it accepts a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for a cease-fire in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, spoke to reporters before flying to <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, the fifth stop on a tour that also has taken him to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Omani officials would not comment on the purpose of the visit, saying only that it would last two days and they would discuss U.N.-related issues. In <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, the ambassador praised the government's refusal to free convicted terrorists despite pressures that included the hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet and the killing of two passengers. The release of 17 jailed terrorists convicted of bombing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies in 1983 was the hijackers' only demand during the 16-day hijack last month. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> refused to free them and the hijackers surrendered the plane in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> in return for safe conduct. Release of the 17 also has been the main demand of pro-Iranian Shiite Mosleh ` fxtremists holding nine American hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> met with <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s emir, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>; Crown Prince <PERSON> Saad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Rashed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> Rashed </PERSON>, minister of state for Cabinet affairs. Asked whether he and the Kuwaitis discussed the hijacking and several terrorist bombings in the sheikdom, he said: `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> thinks that the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> government demonstrated great courage during the recent hijacking. `` We are not here to make a deal about terrorists and in no way will the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ever bring any kind of pressure on the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> government,'' he said in reference to the hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Asked about <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> measure of last July 20 calling for a truce in the Iran-Iraq war, which began in SeptMm | er 1980, <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said Resolution 598 was `` unanimously approved and it's binding on every member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will never abandon its support of 598 and will work ... and urge our friends to support a second resolution and an arms embargo on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'' if it does not accept the resolution, he said. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has said it will accept the resolution, but only if <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> does. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> says <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> must be declared the aggressor before there can be a cease-fire. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980 after several border skirmishes.
