<HEAD>Denies Israel Helped Develop Missile China Sold to Saudis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> on Monday denied an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> newspaper report that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> helped develop surface-to-surface missiles that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> sold to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. The report in the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial sources and Saudi experts as saying Israeli scientists refined the guidance system used in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s medium-range CSS-2 missile. It became known two months ago that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had bought and deployed CSS-2s, which have a range of 2,200 miles and could reach any target in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> did not known of the deal in advance and could not persuade the Saudis to cancel it. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio: `` Israelis were never partners in... the transfer of technology or anything related to ground-to-ground missiles to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> If anyone ... is looking for an alibi about how the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was taken by surprise by a friendly nation, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> ... and is trying to pin the blame on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, let him look elsewhere.'' Saudi leaders told the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> they bought the missiles to defend themselves against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and pledged not to launch them at <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. In March, an aide to Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> hinted that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> might attack and destroy the missiles. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> do not have diplomatic relations but there have been reports of increasing agricultural and business links between the two nations. An Israeli newspaper said last July a joint company had been formed to help <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with agricultural and technological projects. The Sunday Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was sending technicians to modernize Soviet tanks and heavy artillery used by the Chinese army.
