<HEAD>TVA Investigates Second Nuclear Shutdown Since Sequoyah's Restart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An investigative team is looking into what caused <ORGANIZATION> Sequoyah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION>'s balky Unit 2 reactor to shut down Monday for the second time in 3 -LCB- days. The reactor automatically shut down at 12:28 a.m. Monday because of an instrument problem in its reactor coolant system, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION>'s assistant manager of nuclear power. <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON> described the incident at the twin-reactor plant outside <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION> as minor and said it represented no danger to plant employees or the public. The shutdown was the second at <LOCATION> Sequoyah </LOCATION> since May 13, when Unit 2 became <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>'s first reactor to go back on line since the federal utility shut down its nuclear program in August 1985 because of safety concerns. Unit 2 was approaching 75 percent power at the time of Monday's shutdown _ about the same level it had reached on May 19 when a water gauge problem caused the reactor to automatically power down `` It was a relatively minor instrumentation problem that we can correct,'' said <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, a plant spokeswoman. `` As we've said repeatedly, because of the complexity of any nuclear plant, it's not uncommon for a unit to automatically shut down. The reactor had restarted Saturday after repairs and adjustments, and plant workers were calibrating a transmitter that provides readings on reactor water flow when Monday's shutdown occurred. `` The plant's investigative team will be evaluating the cause of the shutdown,'' <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON> said. `` The transmitters will be recalibrated and Unit 2 will be returned to safe operation when all activities are completed.''
