<HEAD>SEC Suspends Investment Adviser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, in a warning to the financial planning industry, said Monday it was suspending a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> investment adviser for failing to tell clients she was earning commissions on the securities she recommended. Without admitting or denying guilt, <PERSON> Nida </PERSON> <PERSON> Rae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Westmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, agreed to accept an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> censure and a 120-day suspension from working as an investment adviser or securities broker. In what <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> officials said was a ground-breaking case, the commission found that beginning in June 1986, Ms. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, who was president of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> chapter of a national organization of financial planners, violated federal laws by failing to tell clients she would receive a commission when they bought into limited real estate partnerships she was selling. She also failed to tell customers they did not have to go through her to purchase the investment, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said, and some of the clients were not suited for investments of that level of sophistication and risk. Officials said it was one of the first cases brought against an investment adviser who is also registered as a securities broker. `` It is very important that when investment advisers are wearing these various hats that they have to bear in mind they have a fiduciary responsibility to their client,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> assistant regional administrator in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> division of investment management, said, `` Consumers seem to approach financial planners as trusted advisers and financial planners seem to market their services in that light: ` You can come in to us and you do n't have to worry about those brokers or insurance agents who are trying to sell you something.' `` However, many of them, if not most of them, are in fact just like the broker or the insurance agent that's trying to sell something,'' she said. `` We're saying they just have to make that clear to the consumer so they can evaluate the advice with a grain of salt. `` The action we brought hopefully will tell other financial planners: We're dead serious. These are rules you're subject to and you have to comply or else,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> did not immediately return telephone messages left Monday afternoon at <ORGANIZATION> Westmark </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>. A woman answering the telephone at the office said no officers of the firm were available to discuss the case. <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Covington </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, would not comment on the <ORGANIZATION> Westmark </ORGANIZATION> order but said the association investigates complaints against any of its 24,000 members and would reprimand or expel a member when justified. <PERSON> Covington </PERSON> said many investment advisers work only for fees, much as a lawyer or accountant, and accept no commissions on securities they sell, while others are paid both. `` Life is full of conflicts of interest and it is not necessarily nasty to sell something you're recommending, provided you make the proper disclosure,'' he said. Investment advising is a fast-growing field. About 12,000 firms are registered with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> as advisers.
