<HEAD>Lords Kill Attempt to Alter Thatcher Tax Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> gave Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> an important victory Monday, killing an attempt by rebels in her <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to amend tax legislation. The unelected upper chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> voted 317-183 against an amendment that would have mandated a closer link to a person's ability to pay It was the largest turnout in the Lords since 1971. Although the Lords and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> still may consider other amendments, the government's victory ensures passage of the major principles of the tax legislation, which was nearly defeated by a Commons revolt in April. Lord <PERSON> Chelwood </PERSON>, leader of the rebellion in the Lords, said during debate on his amendment that the <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> government proposals `` are a lot less fair'' than the current system. `` They have very little support,'' said <PERSON> Chelwood </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> member of the Commons. `` They are extremely unpopular in the country.'' He condemned suggestions by some peers that the chamber had no right to challenge legislation passed by the Commons. The Lords does not have the power to interfere with taxation, but some lords said it was not clear whether the poll tax was an issue of taxation or local authority. `` We are a revising chamber, seeking to exercise restraint on the otherwise unfettered power of the Commons,'' <PERSON> Chelwood </PERSON> said. `` If we can not ` tamper' with legislation, we really have nothing to do.'' Under the so-called poll tax, which critics say is unfair to the poor, property taxes are levied on each adult rather than on houses or apartments. Although the poor will get rebates, they must pay a tax of at least 5 percent. The legislation, a clause in the bill on local government finances, is central to Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s legislative program for curbing expenditures by local councils, most of which are controlled by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In the Lords on Monday, many peers echoed government assertions that people would be less likely to elect free-spending councils if they felt the pinch of the local tax bill. A rebel amendment was defeated 320-295 a month ago in the Commons, where the Conservatives have a majority of 101.
