<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday easily rejected three new Republican challenges to the medium-range missile treaty and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said `` it would be an embarrassment'' to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> if the pact is n't ratified before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> goes to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> next weekend. The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> told his colleagues, `` the ball is in our court, the Republicans' court'' as the Democratic-controlled chamber began a second week of work on the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty. Later, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators and urged approval of the pact before the summit. `` Here is a treaty that has been examined in more detail than any arms control treaty in history, by far,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said after the Capitol Hill session. `` There is a time to inquire and there is also a time to vote. ... It would be a good thing to have it.'' The first decision came when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 81-13 to kill an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, R-N. It would have prevented the treaty from taking effect until <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> reassures <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> about the accuracy of the number of triple-warhead Soviet SS-20 missiles which will be destroyed. Later, the chamber killed, on a 68-26 vote, an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., that would have required a change in the treaty's text to eliminate what he said was a loophole that would have permitted construction of some Soviet missiles Then, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected, 81-5, an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, that would have delayed the INF pact until the two nations agreed on a more far-reaching pact providing 50 percent cuts in each side's large arsenals of long-range atomic weapons. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> said, `` We ought to wait until we see the whole picture'' before approving any pact, but critics termed it a `` killer amendment'' designed to derail the treaty. Before the votes, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> told his colleagues again the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should approve the pact before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meets Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from May 29 to June 2. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> and other conservatives have blocked action by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, delaying the ratification that even critics say is assured. Ratification requires a two-thirds majority voting in favor. `` I'm still convinced it would be an embarrassment to the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to sit down with Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> later this week without the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have taken action to consent to ratification of the treaty,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. However, he added, `` We have some serious issues that, in some cases, may take several hours or days.'' The treaty, signed Dec. 8 by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, requires destruction within three years of all atomic missiles with ranges between 300 miles and 3,400 miles. For the Soviets, that includes 400 deployed SS-20s and another 250 stockpiled SS-20s. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has accepted the Soviet statement of 650 SS-20s, even though <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> analysts say the Soviets may be hiding more than 250 of the weapons. `` We were snookered,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` The estimates are that the Soviets have 300 to 600 more than the 650 thy admit to having.'' `` This is a gut issue,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` It could mean the difference between survival and destruction for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, or a good part of it.'' But Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., noted that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials have rejected <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' claim, although <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> conceded it is difficult to prove that no SS-20s are hidden `` It is akin to proving the <ORGANIZATION> Loch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ness </ORGANIZATION> monster does n't exist,'' <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., said that even if SS-20s are hidden, they could not be deployed without violating the treaty and their `` viability would degrade quickly'' without testing <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' amendment `` is not needed, it is unnecessary and it would hamper our efforts to get the INF treaty in place,'' <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> said. Wallop's proposal affected a part of the treaty which, he said, was written in such a way as to permit production of Soviet SS-25 missiles that would be interchangeable with stages in the SS-20. The SS-25 is not banned. `` This amendment just is to make certain that we do what we set out to do,'' <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON> said, explaining that he wanted to make sure that no SS-25s were produced that would be interchangeable with the SS-20. Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, agreed with Wallop that the treaty's language `` is awkwardly written.'' But <PERSON> Pell </PER