<HEAD>Quakes Shut Downs Businesses, Schools In Guatemala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONZO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of small and moderate earthquakes that began over the weekend forced schools, government offices and many businesses to close Monday in this capital city of 2 million people. The government ordered the one-day shutdown for <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and the surrounding area, except for hospitals and other essential services, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Some stores opened, along with banks and <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> operated normally. It is near a geological fault on the south side of the city, the epicenter of the quakes. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seismological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said at least 50 tremors measuring from 2.1 to 4.0 on the open-ended <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale had shaken the capital since midnight Friday. Many people living near the fault zone have been sleeping outside their homes. A few old walls cracked but no major damage was reported, according to news reports. On Feb. 4, 1976, an earthquake measuring 6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale devastated <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and killed more than 22,000 people. The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. A quake registering 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans. One of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage. Communications Minister <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> described the forced shutdown Monday as a precaution `` because of the situation caused by the constant and continuous earthquakes.'' He said the decision was made `` to avoid any -LRB- traffic -RRB- congestion and so that families can b