<HEAD>Jackson Unveils Budget Plans, Criticizes Dukakis' Version</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs with 3 grafs to include Dukakis comment;
SUBS 5th graf pvs with 2 grafs to UPDATE with later Jackson
appearances. Stands for political roundup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> unveiled a five-year budget plan that would raise taxes on the rich, freeze defense spending and increase support for social programs on Monday. He dismissed Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' earlier proposals as `` radically conservative.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential front-runner, defended his spending priorities, saying they do `` represent a fundamental change.'' And he indirectly criticized <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for trying to map out specific expenses so far in advance. `` There's no way you can prepare a budget today for 1989,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said after an appearance at a child care center in <LOCATION> Cranford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor spent most of Monday in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, while <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, leaving the campaign trail to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> made sure they were n't forgotten, attacking the budget policies of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and complaining that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' proposed changes were too timid `` We can not be fooled into thinking the Reagan-Bush deficits make social justice impossible,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` The <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> budget reduces the deficit and funds needed investments. This is a budget for a strong and secure America.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also made an appearance at a day care center and the <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear power plant, the object of a <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> area voters' referendum seeking to shut it down permanently, as he campaigned for his share of the 314 <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> delegates up for grabs in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s June 7 presidential primary. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> drew some boos from the Rancho Seco plant workers when he told them the nuclear power industry is `` a dangerous job option.'' His five-year federal budget plan would increase taxes on the wealthy by $ 244 billion and on corporations by $ 104 billion, cut defense spending by $ 164 billion by imposing a five-year freeze on projected spending hikes and increase spending on social programs by $ 344 billion. He said it would also cut the nation's deficit from a projected $ 134 billion in 1993 to $ 49 billion. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> repeatedly contrasted his budget proposals with those of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, which he characterized as inadequate to reverse the Republican priorities set over the past eight years by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has cut investment in health care, housing, legal services, day care, scholarships by more than $ 100 billion. Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rails against that as being wrong, but offers to offset it by only $ 775 million,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` That is radically conservative, away from the dreams and aspirations of most Democrats. Unless there is a commitment to economic justice and change, he will find himself taken adrift to sea by the Democratic constituents. Instead of leading them, he will be on a raft without a rudder,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` Our commitment is not to make bland beautiful. It's new directions,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> continued. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' issues director, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was unfairly criticizing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' plans for spending $ 775 million _ $ 500 million on the Fund to <ORGANIZATION> Rebuild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, $ 250 million on a teacher excellence program and $ 25 million on a literacy Corps. `` The way to make critical new investments in a time of triple-digit deficits is not to make unrealistic promises about massive new spending,'' <PERSON> Edley </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` We have to think of creative ways to use modest federal resources to pull in private and state and local funds.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, repeating a campaign theme, said he would raise up to $ 58 billion a year for social programs such as housing, education and health care by freezing the military budget at its current $ 300 billion level for the next five years. `` My plan allows for a significant new social investment, including doubling of the education budget by 1993, a new national housing initiative, and an additional $ 3 billion per year for the war on drugs. These investments and deficit reduction are made possible by a combination of fair taxes on the wealthy and corporations and a freeze on <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending for five years,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` I am for a strong defense. I also support a sound approach to the military budget. Our plan would freeze military spending,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` Cost overruns ... two additional aircraft carrier task forces, <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> and the Midgetman do not make us stronger. They undermine our economy and make us weaker. Even after the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> cuts, real military spending will be 25 percent higher in 1993 than in 1980,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also opposes the two additional aircraft carrier task forces and the Midgetman missile system, and would cut back the Star Wars nuclear defense program to 1983 levels. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has called for a `` stable'' overall defense budget, with increases in conventional forces coming from cuts in strategic systems. The biggest tax increase in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s budget plan would restore the top 38.5 percent income tax rate. `` It's just the top 600,000 taxpayers who earn $ 200,000 and above, who will return from 28 percent to 38.5 percent. They can afford it,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. Other revenue measures would increase the minimum tax rate on corporations, impose a 0.5 percent securities transfer excise tax to raise $ 10 billion annual revenue and discourage major corporate mergers and takeovers, limit deductions for business meals to 50 percent, and impose a $ 7-billion-a-year `` polluters tax'' on corporations. Among his proposed `` new investments'' are programs which by 1993 would spend an extra $ 20 billion annually on education and job training, $ 17 billion on housing programs, $ 12 billion on health and nutrition programs and $ 3 billion more annually on AIDS programs. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s budget proposals also include $ 5 billion more in transportation funding, $ 4.5 billion for scientific research in non-military fields, $ 1.7 billion annually on environmental programs, and $ 1 billion more annually for international economic assistance.
