<HEAD>Far Right Walk Out on First South African Joint Debates in
Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 White and non-white members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> took part in joint debates Monday for the first time. Members of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> walked out in protest. The party said in a statement the members wanted to `` record anew our deep-felt rejection of being co-governed by other population groups.'' The debates dealt with the budgets of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s four provinces and were conducted in the provincial capitals by members of the relevant committees in the white, Asian and mixed-race chambers of Parliament. The government, in revising parliamentary rules to allow the joint debates, stopped short of permitting joint voting on any issues. `` Until we can debate and vote together, this meeting today is an historical farce,'' said <PERSON> Marius </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The Asian and mixed-race chambers were created in 1984 under a new constitution which continued to exclude the black majority from national affairs. The white chamber, dominated by President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is able to get its way on all major legislative issues. The <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, with 23 of 178 seats, is the largest white opposition party. In <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> budget was debated, several legislators objected to stringent security checks conducted as they entered the meeting hall. `` We can not allow ourselves to be subjected to such demeaning checks,'' said <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON> <PERSON> Seedat </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> chamber after he and other lawmakers were ordered to empty their pockets, offer their briefcases to be searched, and produce their parliamentary identity cards. During the debates, government officials pledged to expand black hospital facilities, suggested that new laws would be enacted to control black squatters, and reported that the first `` recreation resort'' for blacks in the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> would be ready next year. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
