<HEAD>Trial Opens in Sex Discrimination Case against Harvard B-School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Tenure decisions ..., to correct that tenure
decision rest with president, sted committee; INSERTS 2 grafs after
7th graf, ``I believe ..., to UPDATE testimony.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former professor suing to become the fifth woman granted tenure in the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s 80-year history testified Monday that the academic guidelines were manipulated to deny her tenure because of her sex. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bund </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 44, who resigned in 1984, is asking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> to reinstate her with tenure and award $ 847,000 in lost income. Manipulation of the tenure process and the use of review procedures different from those used for men are `` the absolute core of the discrimination,'' Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> testified in the first day of her non-jury trial. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has also charged that the school destroyed documents requested by her to support her claim that less-qualified men received tenure from 1974 to 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> maintains in court papers that Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s academic work was substandard and that the tenure records were unwittingly destroyed by someone outside the business school. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> testified she was pressured into submitting new examples of her scholarship sooner than it was required. She also asserted that a faculty member threatened not to support her in her tenure bid because of conflicts over what material a course should cover. `` I believe this was done with the express purpose of discriminating against me on the basis of sex,'' she testified. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked repeatedly to cite specific incidents of sex bias she alleged against several faculty members. When she was unable to on one occasion, she said: `` To me bias is a spectrum and I do n't know where to draw the line in that spectrum,'' she said. In court papers, the school said that Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was given a `` virtually unprecedented'' second chance after she was denied tenure in 1981 and that the faculty voted by just 36-31 to support her 1983 bid, a low margin. A tenure committee rejected her. Tenure decisions at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> are submitted to the faculty to gauge support for the professor. The actual decision rests with the university president, who receives a recommendation from the school's dean. `` She was given an extremely thorough and fair review in 1981 and 1983 and the decision was made entirely on her academic qualifications,'' <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, said in court papers. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a marketing consultant, began teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> as an assistant professor in 1973. She was promoted to associate professor in 1977. In her first attempt at tenure, she failed to win support of the faculty, which cited inadequate scholarship. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was given a three-year extension on her appointment and submitted new academic work for review. Three of the 90 business school's tenured professors are women. Four women have received tenure in the business school's history, the first in 1961. The school said 27 percent of the 819 students in the class of 1988 were women. Legal experts say few gender bias cases make it to trial, and plaintiffs have won even fewer cases because judges are reluctant to rule on matters of academic merit. Nationally, 72 percent of male faculty members have tenure compared with 45 percent of females, according to a recent survey of 1,055 two - and four-year institutions by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professors </ORGANIZATION>
