INCLUDE Awad is Christian.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With AM-Israel, Bjt
^By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> heard an appeal Monday by an Arab-American advocate of civil disobedience who asked the judges to revoke a deportation order against him. He threatened to convert to Judaism and return to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> if the order stands. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>, 44, was ordered deported by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials on May 6. They said he had played a leading role in the 24-week Arab uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The three-judge panel reserved decision after Monday's appeal hearing, but did not set a date for its ruling. The decision is expected to have far-reaching consequences for the legal status of the 130,000 Arabs living in Israeli-annexed east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. During the three-hour hearing, lawyers for both sides focused on <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>'s legal status under Israeli immigration law. The court must consider whether the Jerusalem-born Awad and other east Jerusalem Arabs enjoy an irrevocable status as permanent residents, or if they can lose their rights under certain conditions, such as leaving the country for more than seven years. <PERSON> Nili </PERSON> <PERSON> Arad </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, argued that <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> should be deported because he forfeited his right to permanent residency by leaving <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for 13 years, from 1970 to 1983, and by accepting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Wapakoneta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, while maintaining a home in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Gal </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had no right to deport his client because, as a longtime resident of Arab east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> enjoys a special status that can not be revoked. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> annexed east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, but never defined the legal status of the sector's Arab residents, most of whom rejected offers of Israeli citizenship. Ms. <PERSON> Arad </PERSON> argued that since the annexation, the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> in practice has applied the rules of permanent residency to citizens of east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, and that <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> falls into that category. If the court rules in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, `` all east Jerusalemites are in danger of mass transfer,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> lawyer also representing the Arab-American. `` Those who grant residency permits can also take them away,'' he added. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>, who has been jailed since May 5, looked pale when he entered the packed courtroom wearing a beige suit and a blue-striped shirt. He kissed his American-born wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nye </PERSON>, and talked to reporters during recess. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> rejected government allegations that he had helped incite often violent anti-Israeli protests. He said he stood by his advocacy of non-violent action such as tax boycotts and strikes. He also said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s effort to deport him has helped popularize his ideas. `` My ideas have caught, thanks to the Israelis who put so much pressure on me,'' <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> seems fairly isolated in the Palestinian community, and underground leaders have not mentioned his case in the leaflets they distribute in the occupied lands. Asked what he would do if deported, he told reporters he had the option of converting to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> and coming back under <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Law of Return, which grants automatic Israeli citizenship to all Jews. Awad is Christian. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>'s troubles began in August when the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> refused to renew his identity card, issued by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1968. Since his return from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1983, <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> had stayed in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on tourist visas stamped into his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passport, but in November the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> refused to renew that permit.
