<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday overruled a decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> barring women from voting for the city's chief rabbi. The court ordered the council to hold new elections for its 10 delegates to the 30-member body which will elect the chief rabbi and warned it not to discriminate against women. The city's <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> faction last year elected two women, <PERSON> Haviva </PERSON> <PERSON> Avigai </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lili </PERSON> <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON>, to the elective body. The council nullified the choices under pressure from orthodox leaders, who said religious law forbade women from electing rabbis. Rabbi <PERSON> Yisrael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lau </PERSON>, Mayor <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahat </PERSON>'s choice for the vacant post, said at the time he would not submit his candidacy if women were on the elective body. Ms. <PERSON> Avigai </PERSON> hailed Monday's decision. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has again shown it is the guardian of human rights and that women have equal rights,'' she said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>: `` We have a problem. It has been customary to choose someone to fill a traditional post in a traditional way.'' <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> has been without an Ashkenazi chief rabbi, one representing Jews of European descent, since late 1986 because of squabbling over female representation. Monday's decision was the latest in a series which have pitted the secular law of the land against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s religious establishment. The court also went against the rabbis' wishes last week, when it upheld the appointment of <PERSON> Lea </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakdiel </PERSON>, the first woman nominated to serve on a religious council in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.
