<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Deplore Anti-Semitism in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops on Monday deplored recent demonstrations of anti-Semitism that have apparently occurred in reaction to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s policies toward Palestinians. The statement by the Italian Bishops' Conference followed charges by Jewish leaders that the Italian press, including <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> publications, have helped incite anti-Semitism through their reporting on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> conflict. The bishops' statement, published in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> daily <PERSON> L'Osservatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> and carried by <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, made no direct reference to the allegations by Jewish officials. But it strongly urged Catholics to distinguish between the Jewish people and the policies of the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> government or political parties. `` The tensions between <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and Israelis continue to provoke in the Italian milieu, and therefore also among Catholics, grave preoccupations for the risk of distortions of information and consequent emotive reactions, which in the extremist fringes, can explode into violence,'' the statement said. `` Anti-Semitism in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> seems to some a marginal phenomomen and uncharacteristic of Italian society,'' it added. `` Still, episodes of intolerance against Jews and Jewish institutions, occurring even recently ... provoke in our community feelings of profound preoccupation for the risk of painful civil and religious lacerations that can derive from them.'' The statement also stressed the need to `` promote a dialogue between Jews, Christians and Moslems and to be builders of peace together.'' Last week, <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi, <PERSON> Elio </PERSON> <PERSON> Toaff </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabban </PERSON>, president of the Jewish community, held a news conference to detail recent anti-Semitic incidents in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Among other things, they displayed packs of anonymous and threatening letters and dozens of photos of swastikas painted on walls. The two said the media, including <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> publications, fueled anti-Semitic feelings in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> with reports from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> that tend to compare Israelis to <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> because of the Israelis' policies toward Palestinians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> earlier expressed `` surprise'' at the Jewish allegations and noted that Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> has often spoken out against anti-Semitism. Riots began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. At least 194 Arabs have been killed, and an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldier and Jewish settler also have been slain.
