<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Saying `` what's passed has passed,'' defrocked evangelist <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> ended his three-month exile from the pulpit but conceded that not everyone will forgive him for his sins with a prostitute. `` I am sure there will be many ... that will see to it that I do n't forget. I realize it will be the hardest task,'' <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> said Sunday. In his first sermon since tearfully confessing on Feb. 21 to unspecified sins, the television evangelist reclaimed his pulpit with fire-and-brimstone fervor before 5,000 followers. `` Once you look up into his -LRB- God's -RRB- face, you will never be any cleaner than you are right now,'' <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> said.
