<HEAD>Three American Journalists Honored in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three American writers, ostracized and ignored in their own country during their lifetimes, have an organization in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> dedicated to remembering their contributions to the communist revolution. The Smedley-Strong-Snow Society of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, a wing of the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, was founded in 1984 to honor the three Midwesterners who were among the first to tell the world of the cataclysmic events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the 1920s and'30s. The most famous of the trio is Edgar Snow -LRB- 1905-72 -RRB-, the first Westerner to interview <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> in the caves of their guerrilla stronghold in northwest <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and author of `` Red Star Over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' his classic account of the communist leadership. He is joined by <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> Smedley </PERSON> -LRB- 1892-1950 -RRB-, a fiery supporter of revolutionary causes; and <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON> -LRB- 1885-1970 -RRB-, chronicler of socialist upheaval in both the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. In June, the `` 3-S Society'' marks the 50th anniversary of the publication of `` Red Star Over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' with a major symposium on the book at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The society, made up of more than 100 scholars and writers who knew the three Americans or studied their works, is also holding an essay contest on the book, and will invite students from schools in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Snow's hometown, to attend the symposium. `` We want young people to read history, to find out how <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> traversed this road and reached this stage,'' said former Foreign Minister <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hua </PERSON>, president of the `` 3-S Society.'' <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>, Snow's interpreter when he interviewed <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>, said young Chinese read too many books of `` love, martial arts and adventure.'' Works of people such as Snow `` should be popularized so their contributions to the Chinese cause will not be forgotten.'' Snow arrived in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> in 1927 for a planned six-week visit and stayed nearly 14 years. In one of journalism's greatest scoops, he found his way to the Red army headquarters in northwest <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Baoan </ORGANIZATION> in 1936 and spent five months observing and talking to <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> and his fellow communists He was the first Western journalist to break the news blockade <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>'s Nationalists had imposed on the communists. `` Red Star,'' published in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1937 and in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the next year, became the seminal work on the band of revolutionaries who were to change the face of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. His book gave not only the West but also many Chinese their first detailed look at the communist leaders, and many intellectuals trekked to communist headquarters after reading it. `` It's hard to imagine what our image of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would be today without <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>,'' said former <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON>, a prominent writer on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON> said Snow, whom he met in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in World War II, `` had been my hero as he had been the hero of a whole generation of newspaper men.'' Snow left <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1941 and worked around the world as a roving correspondent for such publications as the Saturday Evening Post, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. In 1959, after years of being hounded by anti-communist McCarthyites, he left the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. But he was to make one last contribution to his native land: In 1970, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> told Snow that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would welcome a visit by then-President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, setting the stage for <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s historic trip in 1972. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> showed its respect for Snow by sending a medical team to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in a futile attempt to save the life of the dying writer in 1972. Some of his ashes are buried in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and some on a university campus in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> where he once taught. Unlike Snow, who was never a Marxist, the two women writers were outspoken in their support for leftist causes. <PERSON> Smedley </PERSON>, born into poverty in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and raised in mining towns, was a strong advocate of women's rights and anti-colonial struggles in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. She worked with <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Yat-sen </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> Soong </PERSON> Ching-ling, and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous modern writer, <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xun </PERSON>. She wrote a biography of Red army commander <PERSON> Zhu </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> and, in 1937 in the communist camp at <LOCATION> Yenan </LOCATION>, taught <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> and other communists to square dance. In 1949, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> report accused her of spying for the Soviets, and she died in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in 1950 while trying to get back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Strong, a native of Friend, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, was a pacifist opponent of World War I and left for the newly founded <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1921. A resident of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for almost 30 years, she wrote some 30 books on revolutions around the world. She, too, made her way to <LOCATION> Yenan </LOCATION> in 1937, and interviewed <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> in 1946 when he made his famous statement, `` All reactionaries are paper tigers.'' She was arrested as a spy and expelled from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1949, only to be further attacked on her return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for her communist leanings. She died in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> at age 84 during the extreme leftist Cultural Revolution, isolated in her last haven by the suspicion that prevailed then against all foreigners. <PERSON> Dong </PERSON> <PERSON> Leshan </PERSON>, translator of a 1980 edition of `` Red Star Over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' that sold 1.3 million copies in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, said the works of the three writers were not always welcomed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` After the revolution Snow was still taboo because he told the real story of the party. Some in the party took a negative view of this,'' he said. It was only after the Cultural Revolution ended in 1976, <PERSON> Dong </PERSON> said, that `` Red Star'' and Snow found acceptance. End Adv PM Thur May 26
