<HEAD>China's New Premier Faces Tough Task</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After six months in office, Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> remains something of a mystery _ perhaps not an exciting one. Universally described as methodically attuned to solving problems rather than politicking, the 59-year-old <PERSON> Li </PERSON> is generally regarded as bland but the kind of leader <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> needs to solve problems slowing the decade-old modernization drive. Overshadowed by his predecessor, the urbane and nattily dressed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, and without power to singlehandedly formulate policy, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has yet to offer any bold initiatives. He has given few clues to his own vision of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s future or his goals as premier, other than reducing an 11 percent inflation rate. Although he is one of the five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most powerful policy-making body, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has been exceptionally cautious in public statements. He remains dogged by a widely held assumption that he owes his job to nepotism _ he is the adopted son of the late Premier <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON>. His rise to the premiership was meteoric. He was appointed acting premier in November, just eight years after being given his first government post, minister of power. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature, confirmed him as premier in April. A few days later, he became the target of satirical attacks in posters put up by students at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` If <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> can become premier, who ca n't?'' said one. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s main credentials for the job were his technical skills and connections. Trained as an engineer in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he spent most of his career running power projects and never ran a city or provincial government. After becoming minister of power in 1979, he rose in rapid succession to vice premier in 1983, Politburo member in 1985 and education minister later that year. As education minister, he escaped responsibilty for the widespread pro-democracy student demonstrations of 1986-87, saving himself by denouncing liberal intellectuals. Many intellectuals dislike him for that and for his failure to improve their salaries and living conditions. However, unpopularity is the least of <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s problems because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s premiers are selected by party leaders, not the ballot box. He must cope with inflation that has reached its current 11 percent from 6 percent two years ago. He also must unclog chronic supply bottlenecks and get rid of waste in government offices and state factories. But any dramatic initiatives to do all those things would need the approval of fellow members of the <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, including <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, his predecessor. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> had a mandate for change when he became premier in 1980 and many of his policies remain in force. That leaves <PERSON> Li </PERSON> with the task of trying to implement policies set by <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who may not look kindly on any changes in them by an underling. When <PERSON> Li </PERSON> took office, it was widely speculated he favored central planning over <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s market-style reforms. But <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s comments have given no sign he opposes those reforms. But <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s reforms have hit snags that <PERSON> Li </PERSON> now must try gingerly to resolve. One is economic incentives, such as bonuses, for workers who increase productivity. They were liberally distributed and had come to be automatic. In addition, the bonuses are said to have eaten into capital investment and helped fuel inflation. An Asian diplomat quoted Chinese sources as saying <PERSON> Li </PERSON> recently refused to approve automatic bonuses, maintaining the incentives should be more closely linked to production increases. That report remains to be confirmed. But <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has made city mayors responsible for decontrolling state-subsidized food prices. And in a profile of <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s first 130 days in office, the official weekly magazine <ORGANIZATION> Liaowang </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Outlook -RRB- credited him with playing a major role in working out a plan to streamline and reorganize the government bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
