<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs June 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ice Cream Entrepreneur Claims 751 Flavors, Including `Sex'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN M. ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ice cream entrepreneur <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> did n't believe vanilla and chocolate were enough to draw in customers, so he added such flavors as fire, flying fish _ and sex. `` Sex is the most exotic,'' the 37-year-old <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> said. Asked what's in it, he replies: `` Large, ripe, juicy <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> cherries that simmer in crystal-clear champagne until they pop.'' <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON>'s recipe for the flying fish flavor includes fish mash and smooth peanut butter, as well as milk, eggs and butter. The flying fish is the national symbol of <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>, a former British colony. `` I just invented a new flavor, to commemorate the island's 21st anniversary of independence,'' <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> said. The concoction includes 21 different kinds of fruit and is called, appropriately enough, `` The 21.'' It tastes like a very rich punch. <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> grew up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where he studied to be a clothes designer. He ran his own small store until his Barbados-born wife, <PERSON> Judy </PERSON>, suggested eight years ago that an ice cream shop in her prosperous and hot <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island might be more fun and profitable. <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> sold his business in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and went to <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, where he served an apprenticeship at Fragole <PERSON> Fabri </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s biggest ice cream factories `` I learned the basics, just enough to make vanilla ice cream,'' he said. `` After the first six months, I knew how to make ice cream, but I had to learn to improve it and then to master it.'' Today, he said, `` I am the king.'' <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> makes 18 flavors fresh each day. He claims he has created 751 in all, and is seeking an entry in the Guinness Book of Records. `` Every single recipe is different,'' he said. `` I do not take a vanilla base ... and simpl change the name as I add different ingredients.'' <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> also meets special requests. On Wednesdays, he prepares ice cream for diabetics, using artificial sweeteners instead of sugar. For vegetarians, <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> makes carrot and zucchini ice cream. Creamy avocado also is popular. Not every flavor is a bestseller. `` Tomato did not do too well,'' he said. `` Too acidic.'' Some flavors contain promotional gimmicks. The main ingredient in `` money'' ice cream is a tightly-rolled <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> dollar wrapped in plastic. <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> did not set out to become a one-man <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> or <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s when he opened Gelato five years ago in a chic mall in suburban <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michael </LOCATION>, one mile outside <LOCATION> Bridgetown </LOCATION>. But shipping delays, high costs and import duties convinced him he could not rely on importing the `` starters,'' or basic flavors, from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I first started experimenting with local fruits,'' he said. Now, his favorite sherbets are made with mangoes, watermelons and passion fruit. <PERSON> Sandford </PERSON> wo n't say what goes into his `` fire'' ice cream, which tastes like hot cinnamon candies. But he guarantees, `` This will burn your palate.''
</TEXT>
