<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv24   05-23 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 24 ,0604</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday May 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>Measure Your Finances Against This Standard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By almost any definition the annual inflation rate is under 5 percent and unlikely to move much higher than that in the near future. But, as you probably have suspected, that does n't mean your personal rate ca n't rise faster than that. If you are inclined toward so-called finer things, your inflation rate could be close to double-digit. But in all probabilility, the higher your personal inflation rate the more you can do about it, most directly by dropping your sights to alternative purchases that cost less and maybe serve as well or better. Evidence of this comes in the National Financial Planning Index, produced by the 24,000-member <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION>. This year it is 9 percent higher than 1987 for a very atypical basket of goods. The essentials: A $ 75,000 annual income, a one-child family, an upscale home, financing for a retirement plan, saving for a four-year private college education, payments for a new car, a one-week vacation, a $ 500,000 life insurance policy. After setting money aside for paying taxes, the association informs us, this family is likely to have only 25 percent left for food, medicine, monthly bills and clothing. But is the family pressed? Or is it pressed only because of its conception of what is important in life? The assumptions: _ A 7 percent, 25-year mortgage on a $ 258,098 home in an affluent suburb _ Financing, over a 25-year period, of a retirement plan to yield $ 169,000 a year _ Saving over a 12-year period to finance a four-year, private college education for the one youngster _ Financing a $ 16,162 car _ <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> LeBaron _ over a four-year period _ Saving for a one-week family vacation in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> to cost $ 2,334 -LRB- not including food and personal expenses -RRB- _ Annual cost of a $ 500,000 life insurance policy _ State, federal and social security taxes All this, according to those folks dedicated to helping you make ends meet, will cost $ 55,896, or 74.6 percent of gross household income, a 9 percent jump over similar costs in 1987. In offering this National Financial Planning Index, the association includes an unusual caveat: `` This family needs to readjust spending goals.'' Why issue such an index, especially in view of the statement by <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, the association's chairman, that `` we are not telling people they should be spending three-quarters of their income on all of these items.'' Rather, he continued, `` We hope people will look at this index, examine their own financial situation, set some realistic goals and objectives for themselves and then adjust their present budgets as necessary.'' Realism is n't difficult to apply to the association hypothesis. Why insist on an upscale home in an affluent suburb? Why assume it will not rise in value and thus afford the occupants a big gain toward their retirement fund? Why look forward to retirement with a plan that relies partially on the assumption that savings will earn 7 percent income while inflation amounts to 5 percent, for a net of 2 percent? Why would anyone save $ 6,648 a year for college tuition at a 7 percent rate while inflation also roared along at 7 percent _ which, in this instance, the index assumes? Who needs an annual vacation in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>? Who needs an upscale automobile?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday May 24</NOTE>
