<FIRST>s a BC-APN--GoneFishingII-Camp Adv05   05-23 1154</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Gone Fishing II-Camp, Adv 05,1187</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone-Fishing II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCK SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From the flat high desert of western <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> a traveler looks far back over his shoulder to see distant white clouds high in the northeastern sky. But what seems to be clouds are actually peaks that soar 13,000 feet high and straddle the Continental Divide for 120 miles. They are the <LOCATION> Wind </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> mountains, and no one knows them better than <PERSON> Finis </PERSON> -LRB- rhymes with highness -RRB- <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. At 87, he is one of the few living Americans to have a physical landmark _ 12,482-foot <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peak </ORGANIZATION> _ named after him by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey. It was the government's way of thanking him for helping it correct topographical maps. He has a near-perfect memory of the 2 -LCB- million acres of the Wind Rivers public patrimony. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> earned the sobriquet `` Lord of the Winds'' by hiking 15,000 miles, climbing 276 peaks -LRB- some two dozen times -RRB- and amassing more than 100,000 color slides of what he calls `` my back yard.'' He also is responsible for some of the finest fishing in the world. Along with his wife, <PERSON> Emma </PERSON>, his father and brother, and a string of pack horses, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> stocked 314 of the 4,000 lakes in the Wind Rivers a half century ago. From those, the fish migrated to 700 others in the chain. Steep waterfalls and hostile terrain had previously kept them barren of fish since their creation. `` These waters were all virgin and were just full of water lice, leeches, freshwater shrimp ... so those fish just gorged themselves,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> wrote in his book `` Wind River Trails.'' `` Some of the brook trout weighed 3 pounds the third year.'' Today the Wind River Range is one of the finest high-altitude fisheries anywhere. In 1906, when <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s daddy traded 40 acres in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> for 160 acres at the foot of the Wind Rivers, the family moved west in a boxcar with a wagon, two mules, a cow, a dog and a few household treasures. They arrived in <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> on April 26 and headed north only to find their new land was worthless. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s father started hauling freight at a penny a pound to feed his family, and 5-year-old <PERSON> Finis </PERSON> helped out. From then on, his life was a great adventure centered in the <LOCATION> Wind </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> mountains. `` The cutthroat trout were the only fish in the Wind Rivers,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` They weighed about 12 pounds apiece. There were no fish in the lakes unless somebody put them there. We think sheepherders may have packed a few fish up there to have something to eat.'' As a young man <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> explored the mountains every chance he got, but after marrying in 1925 he settled down in <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> to work for the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>. In 1930, the Great Depression cost him his job and the couple took their chances living off the land after a bank failure wiped out their savings. `` A hide buyer took us and all our stuff up into the mountains,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> recalled. `` I had 15 $ 20 bills. Two went to the hide buyer and we were on our own. `` We followed a wagon track left over from the sheepmen's and cattlemen's war of'03. When we got settled we decided to open a fishing camp. We asked the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for a permit and they said fine. We were the only ones doing it.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> cooked meals for 50 cents apiece, her husband borrowed 10 horses from friends and charged $ 1.50 a day to rent them to fishermen. Soon folks from <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> were coming up to <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s Fishing Camp for some badly needed fun in those hard times. `` Only Big <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>, Dad's, and a couple other lakes had fish in them when we got started,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. On their own, the <ORGANIZATION> Mitchells </ORGANIZATION> began stocking more. When Superintendent <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON> of the nearby <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatchery </PERSON> heard about it, he came to see them. `` He said to me, ` <PERSON> Finis </PERSON>, if you're going to run a fishing camp you ought to stock other lakes, too. We do n't have any money, but we'll bring you the fish free if you'll pack'em into the mountains,''' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> recalled. <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON>'s hatchery was less than a decade old when he struck his deal with <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. The state of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> provided a three-room log cabin for the superintendent, the hired hand and his wife, and their six children. Today the hatchery uses trucks with oxygen tanks and elaborate cooling systems, as well as helicopters, to haul fish to lakes and streams. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON>'s methods of transportion were more primitive. `` In the old days we used 5-gallon milk cans, a dozen at a time,'' he said. `` The fish were an inch long and there were 1,000 in a can. We covered the tops of the cans with burlap and steadied them by putting them in wooden apple crates which we tied to pack horses.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s job was to walk the horses around in circles as they arrived from the hatchery. That was to keep the water splashing inside the cans, distributing oxygen to the fish and keeping them from smothering. `` The men would all go inside our camp tent and eat and leave me outside walking those pack animals,'' she said, recalling those days with good humor. In 1939, the railroad recalled <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. When the couple broke camp and left the Wind Rivers to return to <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, they were $ 4,000 in debt. But, for free, they'd stocked 2.5 million cutthroat, rainbow, in many isolated lakes every trout caught by a happy angler is directly descended from the ones <PERSON> Finis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> packed in 50 years ago. `` Trout multiplied into the millions, only to reach weights of 4 to 12 pounds and then die without seeing a single hook,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> wrote in his book, a small guide to the mountains which he sells through mail order from his home. <PERSON> Finis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> walks with the help of two sturdy sticks now, but his aging legs have n't kept him from going to the mountains every summer. He's been honored by his state with an honorary doctorate of law, and by his nation when the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> gave him its outstanding achievement award. But his biggest thrills still come in the Wind Rivers, walking with young people. `` Children ask me who owns the mountains and I'm happy to tell them ` You own it,''' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` It's true, too.'' To remind Americans of their stewardship, he writes in every copy of his book: `` This is your wilderness. `` Take only pictures, `` Leave only footprints, `` Kill nothing but time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
