<FIRST>s a BC-APN--GoneFishingII-Flies Adv05   05-23 0974</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Gone Fishing II-Flies, Adv 05,1000</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHERIDAN, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tucked away in a corner of the <ORGANIZATION> Ritz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION> store, across the room from a lunch counter surrounded by a covey of good ol' boys drinking six cups of coffee on one quarter, sits owner <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mavrakis </PERSON>. When he is n't selling fishing licenses or tackle, or swapping lies with the coffee drinkers, he's holding court at the little table littered with beautiful bits of fur and feathers. Without looking up from his flying fingers, <PERSON> Mavrakis </PERSON> keeps up a running commentary about great fish he's known, famous people he's guided and the merits of one trout stream over another But it's not the colorful stories of visiting with Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> or fishing with <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> DiMaggio </PERSON> that keep his audience enthralled: It's his flashing fingers. Mavrakis is one of the West's best artificial fly tiers. Every fly he sells in his store, located in the heart of some of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s best fishing country, is hand-tied. And like thousands of other fishermen who've channeled their summertime love of fly fishing into wintertime fly tying, he needs very specific materials to create fake critters to lure trout straight out of a river and onto a hook. Without realizing it, <PERSON> Mavrakis </PERSON>, like fly tiers from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tasmania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, and all points in between, is largely dependent on three men. They are a <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> elk hide tanner, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> cotton spinner and a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> chicken farmer. Together they form the tripod of international fly tying because they provide nearly all the commercial raw materials needed to practice the art. Each stumbled into the lucrative business by accident. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennerk </PERSON>, owner of Rocky Mountain Dubbing in <LOCATION> Riverton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, was a hide tanner whose clientele dropped off because of his state's depressed economy. He now provides nearly all the wild animal hair used by foreign factories to manufacture the bulk of ready-made artificial flies. `` I export to 16 countries and have been named this year's Wyoming Exporter of the Year,'' said <PERSON> Kennerk </PERSON>, whose tanning techniques are self-taught and secret `` Last year I had gross sales of $ 225,000, with 90 percent of my business now concentrated in providing hair for flies. It's growing about 40 percent a year.'' He has a new catalog listing the 26 colors of the animal hair he tans and dyes, including caribou, Australian possum, deer, elk, moose and rabbit. Caught by surprise at the success of what started in 1981 as a sideline, <PERSON> Kennerk </PERSON> now has five full-time employees and pays 16 mentally handicapped youngsters to bag and label his products. He also buys hides from local hunters who pump that money back into <LOCATION> Riverton </LOCATION>, and is doubling the size of his building. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Danville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chenille </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has been in business 55 years. It began by providing chenille _ a cotton yarn twisted together around a hard core _ for ladies' hats and handbags. But fashions changed and in the late 1950s, when <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON>'s family bought the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> firm, its product was popular mainly with hobbyists. Most chenille was then sold for novelty items, such as pipe cleaners. Recently the boom in fly tying has created a whole new market for chenille, which forms the body of the fly. <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON>'s company is now the world's major supplier of the product named after the French word for caterpillar. `` We grossed $ 550,000 last year, with all but $ 50,000 of that from our fish and tackle business,'' said <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON>, who employs 11 full-time and five part-time workers. `` We have so many orders it's going like crazy around here. One-third of our sales are to fly factories in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, and to people in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> _ all over.'' Buck <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>'s chicken hatchery in <LOCATION> Bellville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, anchors the third corner of the raw materials triangle. His father, grandfather and uncle started the chicken farm in the late 1930s. `` It was a commercial poultry operation. We raised chickens for meat and eggs,'' said <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, who now runs the hatchery with his brother, <PERSON> John </PERSON>. `` We got into providing specialty neck feathers because I needed them to tie my own flies and they were very hard to come by. Before us, most of the hackles came hit-and-miss from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> bought his first specialty chickens in 1972 from breeds that had been genetically modified to produce unique neck feathers. `` My dad thought I was crazy when I paid $ 10,000 for 150 chickens,'' he said. Last year that division of the family business took in nearly $ 1.5 million, while the farm's regular chicken and egg sales totaled $ 3 million. `` I realized within two years that there was an unknown level of demand out there for our hackle production,'' said <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, referring to the prized neck feathers of his pedigreed poultry. `` We've been trying ever since to find out how big the market is, but it keeps growing faster than we can keep up with it. `` We have 35 distributors in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, as well as here, and we're far and away the largest feather supplier to fly tiers in the world.'' <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> now employs 60 full-time and 60 part-time workers to give his 100,000 pampered chickens the individual care they require. `` These are somewhat delicate birds, prone to diseases more than commercial strains of poultry, and each one has to be individually caged to protect them from each other,'' he said. <PERSON> Kennerk </PERSON>, <PERSON> Merrick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> all know about each other and their importance to fly tiers. They have another thing in common: They're avid fly fishermen who're now so busy working they do n't have time to go fishing anymore.
</TEXT>
