<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actress <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON>, making a return engagement as hostess for tonight's `` 1988 Tony Awards,'' wants to get back to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> where she collected her share of the prizes in earlier years. `` I think there's an electricity that takes place in the theater and nowhere else but in the theater,'' says <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON>, familiar to TV audiences as <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> on `` Murder, She Wrote.'' `` It makes you want to get back to it. Applause, applause, you know. It's meat and potatoes to us.'' Three musicals received 10 nominations for Tonys, which go to the best of Broadway from the season just ending. They're <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON>'s `` The Phantom of the Opera,'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s `` Into the Woods'' and a revival of <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>'s `` Anything Goes. The CBS producers of the awards presentations, which will be televised from Broadway's Minskoff Theater, invited Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> back for a second year as hostess. `` Last year, it intrigued and honored me enough that I felt I had to host it,'' Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> said by telephone from her home in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` Through my connection with ` Murder, She Wrote,' I knew I was going to be welcome in the nation's living rooms. Some people saw me glamorously gowned for the first time.'' Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> became known in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> at 17, became a star on Broadway at 40 in `` Mame,'' and became a TV star at 59, as <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, who writes and solves mysteries. She was nominated for an Academy Award for her first movie, `` Gaslight,'' and twice more, for `` The Picture of Dorian Gray'' and `` The Manchurian Candidate,'' where she played <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s mother. She also played <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>'s mother in `` Blue <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'' and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s sister in `` National Velvet.'' On Broadway, she was in only three shows, `` Hotel Paradiso,'' `` A Taste of Honey'' and `` Anyone Can Whistle,'' before she started winning Tonys. She has Tonys for the musicals `` Mame,'' `` Dear World,'' `` Gypsy'' and `` <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>.'' About her gown for this year's show, Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> says, `` That's a prime concern for a woman. We're going to try to outdo ourselves this year.'' Last year she appeared first in a gown of dramatically contrasting panels of black and white and later wore glittering gold. `` I'm lucky enough to be gowned by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackie </PERSON>, a great <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> designer,'' she says. `` He created one of the most stunning gowns I've ever seen last year _ the black-and-white creation. `` It's such a great dress I can not let it hang in a bag in a closet. I'm sure it will go into one of the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> museums _ if I can keep it away from my granddaughter. She's a big dresser-upper. She's only 3. `` My son _ her father _ is director <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>. He directed a lot of ` Murder, She Wrote,' which is very nice. My daughter has a restaurant with her husband in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.'' Another concern is the strike by the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` Last year, a tremendous amount of what I did say was me,'' she says. `` I told them I did n't want to get up there and spout a lot of things I would n't be comfortable saying. I wanted to talk from the heart. `` This year, I do n't know how they'll script. With everything that has been written about the shows, it would be possible for me to put together anything that's needed. If necessary, that's what I'll do.'' Earlier in May, the 62-year-old actress made an exercise and lifestyle tape. `` It's how to keep your body moving, light and graceful and how to keep your energy up,'' she says. `` I throw in all sorts of homilies about rest and exercise and how to get the most out of life.'' This season's `` Murder, She Wrote'' series kept her working long hours from last July 5 to early May, Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> says. `` We shot 25 episodes. Normally we do 22. We had the scripts so we decided we'd go ahead, so we'd have something to start the new season with. We hope to start back Aug. 1. We have no way of knowing. We're in the midst of this dreadful strike. People are rather grim about it.'' At the end of next season, Miss <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> says, `` My five-year stint on ` Murder, She Wrote' will be over. I can not stay, on a week-to-week basis. Perhaps we can work out an arrangement where I do several a year, which would leave me free to do other things. That's what I want. `` Especially when you get up in my years, if you're still energetic, which I am, and still love working in the theater, movies and TV, you want to feel you've got some time to do it. I really think I'm one of the luckiest people on two feet. I do have tremendous stamina and energy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
