<HEAD>Summit Takes Over Soviet Capital's Busiest Buildings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From the gilded splendor of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> reception halls to a mock-Western hotel frequented by foreign businessmen and <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> prostitutes, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s busiest landmarks are being pressed into service for this week's U.S.-Soviet summit. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Soviet Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, hundreds of staff workers and thousands of journalists will occupy just a few buildings in the city, but their presence will be dominating. The official meetings will take place in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, seat of Soviet power. And although they do n't live within the fortress walls, the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> will give a state dinner there for the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION>, who will be hosts for a reciprocal affair at their summit quarters, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador's residence known as <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The official American entourage and much of the White House press accompanying <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will be housed at the Mezhdunarodnaya -LRB- International -RRB- Hotel attached to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Center for International Trade. The hotel also will serve as headquarters for an international press corps now estimated to number at least 5,000. Many of the visiting journalists will stay at the mammoth 3,200-room Rossiya Hotel between Red Square and the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, although officials have said some outlying hotels also will be used to handle the flood of reporters, photographers and technicians. Here are historical notes and descriptions of the principal summit venues:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE KREMLIN:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The delta-shaped fortress that today encloses the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership behind russet, crenelated walls dates back to the 15th century at the site of a former `` White Stone'' Kremlin. Inside the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> walls, bordered by the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, Red Square and the Alexander Gardens that run along bustling <PERSON> Prospekt </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>, are a jumble of czarist palaces, cathedrals, government buildings and state museums, including the Armory, which houses Faberge eggs, gold, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> the Great's high boots and other Kremlin treasures and memorabilia. The leaders will likely meet at some time during the summit in the rose-and-silver-colored Hall of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>, a 19th century remnant of the Russo-Byzantine-style Imperial residence that is now the Grand Kremlin Palace. The most stringent security measures in a capital known for caution are practiced at the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, where the three main gates are manned by dozens of uniformed <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> border guards and access even to the roads leading up to the gates is restricted. During the meetings and festivities connected with the summit, the broad stretches of asphalt and cobblestone between the historic buildings will be black with freshly polished ZIL limousines used to shuttle Soviet dignitaries, as well as the American vehicles that will be flown in for use by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his senior staff.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SPASO HOUSE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The yellow New Empire-style mansion, which takes its name from the small <LOCATION> Spasopeskovskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> out front and a nearby Russian Orthodox cathedral, will house <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, and their personal staff during their five-day stay in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> will stay in the second-floor guest quarters that had been known as the Vice Presidential Suite but will be renamed in honor of its new guests, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy press attache <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. Ambassador <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>, plan to stay in their own quarters in the mansion for the presidential visit. <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a two-story dwelling with a columned front portico, was built in 1914 on the grounds inhabited in the 17th century by the czar's dog-keepers and falconers. Its wealthy builder, <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Vtorov </PERSON>, was killed shortly after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, and the mansion was expropriated by the Soviet government. It was turned over to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1933, when <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bullitt </PERSON> arrived as the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The mansion and its surrounding gardens have been the scene of raucous celebrations such as the one on Christmas Eve 1934, recalled in <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thayer </PERSON>'s book `` Bears in the Caviar,'' when animals borrowed from the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Zoo went beserk in the ballroom. Premier <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> attended lawn parties there when he was still in power. In World War II, a bomb shelter was built in the mansion's basement, and the ambassador and his staff evacuated to the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Kuibyshev </LOCATION> in late 1941 when German troops drew close to the city and air raids broke an occasional window The vaulted ceilings and doric columns that distinguish the interior are complimented by cream, navy and mauve furnishings. A collection of ultra-modern art, chosen by the Matlocks, hangs on the marble walls as part of the `` Art in Embassies'' program.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEZHDUNARODNAYA HOTEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The modern, slate-gray towers of the American-designed hotel and business complex known among foreigners as `` The Mezh'' is an island of Western life that is for the most part off-limits to Soviet citizens. The Mezh, derived from the Russian word `` mezhdunarodnaya,'' meaning international, is so different from most Soviet business and residential buildings that filmmakers use the interior to portray American venues. In the 1985 film `` We Accuse,'' about the U-2 spy plane s news agency says 5,000 reporters have sought accreditation for the summit, and the White House and Soviet Foreign Ministry agreed the second-floor <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> was the only place in the city that could accommodate a press center. Even so, it will seat fewer than 1,000 of those expected.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ROSSIYA HOTEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Twice ravaged by fire, the 5,500-bed <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> will serve as home and office for the world's broadcast media. Television and radio teams have built studio sets on the west-wing balconies overlooking Red Square and the Kremlim, from which the nightly news on all four American networks will be anchored. The 12-story hotel, which took 25 years of haggling, design change and behind-the-scenes debate to complete, opened its first rooms in late 1966 and was completed in 1971. It has restaurants, six bars, a film theater and a concert hall. Fire struck the north wing Feb. 25, 1977, and at least 30 people were killed. An exploding television set in one of the rooms was blamed for a Jan. 8, 1987, blaze that killed one woman. The hotel's location near the most popular sights of the Soviet capital has made it a favorite with tourists for the past 20 years. The familiar onion domes of St. Basil's Cathedral and a half-dozen small churches relocated to the site during construction projects around <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> stand in stark contrast to the modern steel, glass and concrete Rossiya. To the north is the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION>, GUM, and across Red Square are Spassky Tower, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> wall burial ground and <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s red-marble mausoleum.
</TEXT>
