<HEAD>EDUARD A. SHEVARDNADZE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The 60-year-old foreign minister has been the main Soviet contact with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> on summit planning. Earlier this month in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, he and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> tackled the final problems holding up <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratification of the treaty banning medium - and shorter-range nuclear weapons The two also tried to resolve the differences over a treaty to cut in half the superpower arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, the only non-Slavic member of the 13-member ruling Politburo, succeeded <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> as foreign minister in July 1985, less than four months after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power. The white-haired <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> has given <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> diplomacy a more personable face than <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, frequently smiling and joking with reporters. He and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> have developed what both describe as a good rapport in their frequent meetings. Before becoming foreign minister, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> headed the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the Georgian republic, where he gained a reputation for cracking down on rampant corruption.
