<FIRST>s a BC-Bowling Adv29-2Takes   05-23 1206</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bowling, Adv 29-2 Takes,1248</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sport's Identity Crisis _ Purple Balls? Heated Bags? This is
Bowling?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NANCY SHULINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every evening around 7, the thudding, rumbling and clashing that have filled the convention center for 11 -LCB- hours suddenly cease. For 15 minutes, there's silence. Then the organ swells. Spectators cheer. Gold curtains snap open. And 200 bowlers, their faces flushed with pride and embarrassment, march up the center aisle, flanked by 20 gleaming bowling alleys. Uh, strike that. We do n't use `` alley'' anymore. And hey! Get your mind out of the gutter. Take it from the American Bowling Congress: `` Gutter'' is out. `` Channel'' is in. Ask <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON> and you get a different opinion. `` A gutter's a gutter,'' says <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>, better known as 33-year-old <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Haemmerle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. Chosen at random to represent bowlers everywhere, he was crowned Feb. 13, opening day of the 85th annual <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> tournament that ended in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> last week. Question: How long does it take 38,000 bowlers from 50 states and nine foreign countries bowling 18 hours a day, seven days a week, to bowl 341,430 games, thereby toppling 58 million pins? Answer: 103 days, which is about 102 longer than it takes to realize that bowling is experiencing an identity crisis. Gutter or channel? Recreation or sport? <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramden </PERSON> or <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>? Do n't be fooled by the plastic bowler-in-a-seashell, the `` beer frame'' keychains and other doo-dads for sale at the tournament. Out on the lanes, bowling's taking the high road: No smoking. No shorts. No collarless shirts. No drinking. NO HOT DOGS. You're here to bowl, not to eat. What's gotten into bowling? Where'd all that high-tech equipment come from? A black rubber ball in a zippered bag was good enough for <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramden </PERSON>. Today, it's three, four, five balls. Rubber balls. Urethane balls. Polyester balls. In purple. Blue. YELLOW, for heaven's sake. Carried in _ are you ready for this, <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>? _ battery-heated, insulated, temperature-controlled bowling bags. Behold the modern bowling pin: Laminated on the outside, holes on the inside. The slightest tap and it's to the moon, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>! Consider the lane: Spread a little oil on today's urethane-coated surfaces and it's bang, zoom To the pocket, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>! `` Nah, I do n't practice,'' says <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON>. `` If you're not hitting your shot, you just buy another ball. I carry five of the urethanes.'' Alas, five are n't always enough. In his first official act, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON> opened the tournament with a gutterball. What do you want from a guy forced to bowl in front of 2,234 people while wearing a robe and a crown? Bowling's split personality begins to make sense when you consider that there's bowling the sport, and then there's bowling the game. Bowling the sport is math, physics and sophisticated terms like `` coefficient of friction'' and `` kinetic energy.'' Bowling the game is nachos, chili dogs and simple terms like `` Miller'' and `` Bud.'' Unlike the sport, the game has no image problem. It could n't care less, an attitude that irks the sport no end Let the sport compile all those demographics about how young-bright-affluent its 68 million participants are. Let it lie awake nights worrying about the impression it makes. The game has better things to do, like order another cheeseburger. The American Bowling Congress, gatekeeper of the sport and recipient of $ 10 million in dues from 3.4 million league bowlers, stresses skill, complexity, pride and tradition. The National Bowling Council, the industry's advertising arm, and <ORGANIZATION> AMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION>, its largest manufacturers, stress leisure, recreation and fun, fun, fun. <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, a 9-year-old who pushed his bowling ball two-handed to a near-perfect 299, was immortalized in the early'80s in a <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> ad promoting easy-to-topple pins. In the same era, the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> put an orangutan on the cover of its magazine, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> enthusiastically promoted a `` Real People'' segment featuring a bowling pig. Fun for all ages! Anyone can play! You do n't have to be good. You do n't have to be a grown-up. You do n't even have to be human! Bowling's critics say it's going to the dogs. Its kingpins say it's going to the Olympics. What's a swell game like bowling doing in a mess like this? It did n't get there overnight. The ancient Egyptians were bowlers; it's been traced back to 5200 BC. Germans bowled in the 6th century; <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> in the 16th. In those days, the game was called ninepins, `` lawn bowling'' in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> banned it as `` a form of vicious gambling.'' No respect, even then. Lawn bowling and `` skittles,'' a Dutch game, got a warm welcome in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> World </LOCATION>, where tavern owners embraced them as a way to boost beer sales. It did n't take long for gambling charges to resurface. Prim and proper <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> banned ninepins in the late 1830s. That might have been the end of that, had not some enterprising soul _ evidence points to one <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> _ circumvented the law by adding a 10th pin. Bowling was legalized in 1841. Like other German immigrants, bowling headed West in the 19th century. It settled in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, still bowling's stronghold with <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> No. 1. Bowling generally thrives wherever blue-collar and shift workers are found. `` If you work from 7 to 5, you do n't have time for daylight sports like golf or tennis. Bowling is something you can do at night,'' says <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>, a bowler who owns a pizzeria in <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Almost from the beginning, would-be bureaucrats descended on bowling, bent on organizing, standardizing and merchandizing what was, until the late 1800s, a haphazard affair involving however many pins of whatever shapes and sizes happened to be on hand. That all changed in 1895, when the American Bowling Congress first met, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Formed to represent bowlers' interests, the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> quickly adopted the 300-point scoring system and set uniform standards for pins, balls and lanes. And what did it get for its trouble? It got trouble. The bickering started almost immediately: High scores vs. high standards. Commercial interests vs. bowler interests. Sport vs. game. Bad press dogged bowling from the beginning -LRB- Ever read `` Rip van <PERSON> Winkle </PERSON>?'' -RRB-, only to be replaced many years later by something infinitely worse: no press at all. Legislators picked on bowling. In some states, it was illegal for minors to walk to or from a bowling alley unless accompanied by an adult. Those laws were repealed in the 1950s. By that time, bowling had reached new heights of respectability. The glamorous beer teams, touring the country in their all-white, good-guy outfits, helped boost bowling's image, along with sales of <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON>'s, Falstaff, Budweiser and <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON>. Automatic pin-spotters brought respectability, just as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was about to crack down on the low pay and late hours given erstwhile pinboys. And women developed an affinity for the game, prompting proprietors to class up the joints. As <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramden </PERSON> went, so went the nation. Between the mid'40s and the mid'60s, the number of league bowlers quadrupled. Suddenly, everyone was going bowling _ 4.5 million people regularly, in ABC-sanctioned leagues.
</TEXT>
