<FIRST>s a BC-Bowling Adv29-1stAdd   05-23 1205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bowling, Adv 29-1st Add,1246</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>JACKSONVILLE: ABC-sanctioned leagues.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 From 1955 to 1960, membership in the Women's <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rose by 150 percent. Entrepreneurs were quick to spring into action. A little too much action, it turned out. In 1944, there were 38,203 bowling lanes. By 1964, there were 159,079. So ended `` The Competitive Era'' of bowling. So began `` The Commercial Era.'' So says Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, a former college professor with four decades of involvement in bowling and a Ph.D. in finance. He's also the author of two scholarly volumes on industry trends that combine a desire to drag bowling's leaders behind the woodshed with a penchant for capital letters. `` NO INDUSTRY OR ORGANIZATION HAS AN INHERENT RIGHT TO EXIST FOREVER,'' he writes. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> considers bowling a sport, and he'd like you to. Actually, what he'd really like is for you to consider it `` a microcosm of life itself,'' but what the heck. He's a reasonable guy. Besides, this is no time to argue. `` Bowling,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> warns, `` is on the verge of extinction,'' done in by bouncy pins and urethane balls with built-in hooking power, unscrupulous lane conditions and greedy commercial interests. If it's true that the sport of bowling is dying, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> thinks the business of bowling is what's killing it. `` We have eroded the integrity of the SPORT of bowling to create the RECREATION of bowling,'' according to the text of a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Proprietors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. Meanwhile, recreational bowlers are scoring up a storm. The same 213 average that made one Detroiter the highest-ranked bowler in his league in 1987 puts him between 50th and 60th on this year's roster. Consider the perfect game: 12 strikes, for a score of 300, once so rare that the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> gave a 14-carat gold ring to anyone who managed to pull it off. Today, the same ring costs a bowler $ 350. The free ones are silver-plated _ a good thing for the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, considering the number of perfect games bowled last year: 8,537, up from 1,375 a decade ago. Honor scores in general _ 300, 299 or 298 for a single game or 800 for a three-game series _ totaled 21,022 for 1987, exceeding the totals for 1977, 1978 and 1979 combined. During a single day of competition at a tournament in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, in April, there were four perfect games. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>, who works the counter at <LOCATION> Bowl-Era </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanes </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Hammond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, still remembers the excitement of the center's first 300 game. `` It was a big day. Of course, that was five years ago. So far this year, we've had six.'' At <LOCATION> Bowl-Era </LOCATION>, `` 180 used to be considered a high average. Now we're seeing 225 averages. Last year, my own family brought home 16 trophies. Finally, I told them, ` Enough!''' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has had enough, too. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> is a self-appointed guardian of the sport's integrity _ what's left of it, anyway. He'd sooner lock bowling in its room than let it strut its stuff as scheduled in a one-day exhibition the day before opening ceremonies at the summer Olympics in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. `` Bowling is not going to any parties until it cleans itself up,'' vows <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a former pro coach who now manufactures his own line of `` honest'' pins and lane finishes, products he insists would solve the whole problem. Products he claims the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> refuses to approve. The <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> says he's never asked. Bowling, says <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, `` has become a low-life game. A 24-year-old with a 227 average just bowled his 14th career 300 game. If the great bowlers of the past were here instead of in their graves, they would shoot him. `` A bowling lane today is the equivalent of a concave golf green with a 36-inch cup,'' contends <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, who, using a speed trap of his own invention, recently clocked a bowling pin at 42 feet per second. `` In the old days, they traveled 16 feet, 17 feet per second. Now they're flying all over the deck.'' Next to bouncy pins, nothing makes <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> madder than `` blocked'' lanes. Oil is applied to bowling lanes to protect them from the friction of the landing ball as well as to provide a `` skid'' area, thereby enabling the ball to follow the `` skid-roll-hook'' pattern required for effective delivery. How to apply that protective coating is infinitely more complicated. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> believes _ and he has lots of company _ that less-than-scrupulous bowling centers have `` learned how to place oil on the lanes to reguide errant shots into the pocket. This lane blocking, along with today's powerful balls, has made bad bowlers appear good. We have horrible bowlers now.'' Not so, says <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Proprietors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Fairlanes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 4,000 lanes, more than any other chain. `` What we have today is an extremely skilled sport. Technical improvements may well have helped. But I do not agree that today's bowlers are n't as good `` Some proprietors _ not the majority, but a few _ are using oil as a marketing strategy,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> concedes. `` But the average bowler is n't able to exploit those conditions.'' The oil crisis has been under closer scrutiny than <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> by the ever-vigilant <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, whose previous efforts to resolve it have succeeded only in further depleting its stock of honor-score rings. `` We want to see any rule change result in a condition that is fair and competitive to all bowlers, and that will leave the pride of accomplishment in the hands of the bowlers instead of the maintenance people,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> assistant secretary-treasurer <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellermann </PERSON> says through clenched teeth. At the tournament in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, lanes were constantly monitored to ensure the same conditions for each bowler, as well as to prevent lanes from becoming blocked. This meticulous maintenance may have accounted for both the low numbers on the scoreboard and the long faces in the parking lot. `` A lot of people take bowling too seriously,'' confides <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON>, whose mother went bowling the night she gave birth to him. `` Mom was tough. I grew up with, ` Head down! Do n't bend your wrist! Keep your damn shoulder up!' She used to be a killer. Now she's in it for fun.'' For what it's worth, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON> has never done well at the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> tournament, either. `` But no matter how bad you do, you always come back.'' Indeed, bowling badly at the championships is an annual tradition, right up there with the march up the center aisle and the crowning of Joe Bowler. Like today's bowling pins, bowlers are mighty resilient. `` Conditions are always rough,'' confirms <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, whose 50th tournament appearance won him a diamond lapel pin and warm applause when he marched up the aisle in April. The organist played `` Over the Rainbow.'' <PERSON> Ahler </PERSON> bowled 177. Like 60 percent of this year's bowlers, he's planning to try again next year, when the tournament moves to <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> `` It's an impossible tournament,'' says <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` But you keep wondering: When's your lucky year gon na come?'' One of these days, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>. One of these days.
