<HEAD>`Dirty Dozen' Films Fox TV Series in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was only a matter of time before `` The Dirty Dozen'' arrived as a weekly series. <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> recently snatched it up, and a cast and crew from <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> is busy re-creating this fantasy version of World War II on location in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. It began as a hit movie in 1967 with an all-star cast, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> revived it three times, once with <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> reprising his movie role as the tough, good-guy leader, and twice with <PERSON> Telly </PERSON> <PERSON> Savalas </PERSON>, who played a bad guy in the original movie, as the leader. It's a great concept. Take a bunch of convicted murders, offer them an outside chance of freedom and send them off on a suicide mission against the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. The bad guys suddenly become the underdogs and capture audience sympathy. Everybody's happy, except the Germans, who reportedly are a little miffed at once again being the patsies in a war film. `` They're the classic underdogs,'' said executive producer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Furia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. `` They've made mistakes of various kinds and are looking to redeem themselves by heroic action.'' <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> stars in the weekly series, which <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> began running Saturdays last month. He plays Lt. <PERSON> Danko </PERSON>, the head of the group. But this time he's also a convicted felon. <PERSON> Danko </PERSON> assaulted a colonel he says was responsible for getting 80 of his men killed in combat. `` <PERSON> Danko </PERSON>'s a no-nonsense career soldier who does n't want to be there but does n't know what else to do,'' said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, also speaking from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. `` It's sort of the story of my experience. I've never done a series where life imitated art so much. It's like going to war for a year. You leave home, go to another country. `` Our accommodations are better than barracks, but the filmmaking process is very much like being in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. You have periods of hurry up and wait, then periods of intense work. I think it's the toughest show on television in terms of man-hours, hardships and the effort that goes into it.'' <PERSON> Furia </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION> is like a big studio backlot because of its old buildings, various architectural styles, cobbled streets and variety of countryside just outside the city. `` There are n't many places left in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that still look like the 1940s,'' said <PERSON> Furia </PERSON>. `` In addition, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has a lot of equipment, military and otherwise, from the period. It's very economical to shoot here. We have an excellent local film crew. `` Our shows are a combination of melodrama, action-adventure and strong characters. We have a good cast and the luxury of being able to tell many different kinds of stories within the framework of the series. We've done stories on teen-age partisans, the Cossacks of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and one that was supposed to be set on an island off <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.'' The show also stars <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Slattery </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tenney </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> DiAquino </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. That does n't add up to a dozen, but various guest actors are brought in for each episode. They're usually casualties by the end of the show. `` <PERSON> Danko </PERSON> keeps a certain distance from his men, because of rank and age, but there's also a comraderie,'' said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` He's a 40-year-old lieutenant. I've been in four war movies, and in one 20 years ago I played a lieutenant. I've never gone beyond that in rank. In ` The Winds of War' I was a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said he spends his off time playing tennis with his Yugoslavian buddies. `` They have nice courts here,'' he said. `` We found one the other day on an army base. My buddies talked our way in. If I can play tennis a few times a week I have few problems being anywhere.'' <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has become a major film site in recent years. The sequel to `` The Great Escape'' was also filming there. `` War and Remembrance'' had been there earlier. The movie `` High Road to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' and an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> miniseries on <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> were also filmed there. `` They make a lot of World War II movies on their own,'' said <PERSON> Furia </PERSON>. `` So they're used to our special effects bombs and the machine guns. We're blowing up so many buildings and trucks I sometimes think we're laying waste to half of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' Furia is an old hand at working abroad. In recent years he's produced `` Rage of Angels'' in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, `` The Sun Also Rises'' in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and `` We Are The Children'' in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> `` Dirty Dozen: The Series'' began filming in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> last December and will not complete 13 episodes until July. It takes 10 days to make each episode.
</TEXT>
