<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Artists' Colony Thrives Among Pastures and Balloons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONEYDEW, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On the first weekend of every month, thousands of art lovers take a walk on the wild side through some of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s loveliest farmland. It's the Crocodile Ramble, stretching 28 miles near <LOCATION> Honeydew </LOCATION>, a village in the mink-and-manure belt, so called because of the area's wealthy, horse-keeping inhabitants. Civil servants from government offices in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, businessmen from <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and young families getting their first taste of serious art walk and drive along dirt trails, through cow pastures and <PERSON> bush </PERSON>. Artists and craftsmen open their workshops and chat with all comers about form, color and price. Visitors who do n't buy can still enjoy coffee, wine and light lunches. Bands play. Hot-air balloons float overhead. Water sportsmen head for <ORGANIZATION> Hartebeespoort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dam </ORGANIZATION>, a nearby lake. Enthusiasts of early humans prowl among the caves at <LOCATION> Sterkfontein </LOCATION>, a few miles away. Zulu tribesmen dance for tourists in a kraal of tree-branch walls set up by a local hotel. Artists have lived for decades in the gentle hills around the <LOCATION> Crocodile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, their thatched houses secluded but still close to showrooms in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The idea of the Ramble came a year ago to potter <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON>, who specializes in bonsai. `` Art should be accessible to everybody, including people who are frightened of going into a gallery. Children should be confronted with art,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. `` The problem with this society is it's flush and it's plastic. People are susceptible to easy forms of entertainment _ beer, rugby, braais -LRB- cookouts -RRB- and video. It's essential that these things are counterbalanced.'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> encouraged some 25 friends to open their studios to the public once a month, creating a vast attraction for both connoisseurs and tourists. Property values soared. Jewelry-maker <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Scrimgeour </PERSON> bought her farm for $ 90,000 just before the Ramble opened and said it's now worth $ 170,000 Some artists, uncomfortable dealing with the public, dropped out. Others welcomed their freedom from the demands of galleries, which take up to 40 percent of selling prices, and found new customers by taying home. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said he took in $ 2,500 on a recent weekend. In a country where nearly all human endeavors are affected by the prolonged conflict over apartheid, the Ramble remains a non-political patch of Western taste set incongruously in the African countryside. The artists and craftsmen are white, some born in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Some incorporate African themes in their work. Others, such as <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, draw on Northern Hemisphere traditions. The only studio devoted to black African art was hit by lightning and burned down in February. The success of white farmers and artists masks poverty among black seasonal farm workers, residents say. Scrimgeour said a 1987 survey by a local church listed 25 percent of black children under 6 years old as dangerously malnourished. She said the Ramble has increased black employment. The Ramble includes <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, who charges up to $ 3,500 for his hand-forged knives. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>'s wife, Sue, paints on silk. Muralist <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Korzennik </PERSON> spent decades decorating corporate headquarters before he lost a contract he had pursued for a year. The disappointment made him rethink his life and his art. `` Now I stay here and do what I want, and let people respond,'' he said. His large wood and steel sculptures sell for up to $ 8,000. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Yatt </PERSON>, a furniture designer, and his wife, <PERSON> Fiona </PERSON>, an interior decorator, opened a gallery of paintings by a friend, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nel </PERSON>, who died three years ago. `` We had about 60 of them and at first we did n't know what to do,'' <PERSON> Yatt </PERSON> said. `` Now they're being sold and when they're all gone, I'm not sure what will happen.'' <PERSON> Sarie </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> sells unglazed ceramic birds and plant holders and small bronze animals at a farm that's been in her family for 100 years. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Worsley </PERSON> produces rustic furniture. `` I employed 52 people in a two-story factory in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Then a customer brought me to the <LOCATION> Crocodile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and I saw what I was missing _ geese charging around the garden, dogs playing. I had lost out on life. `` I sold my house and almost everything I had and bought a farm here. I became a one-man business again, and have only 10 people working for me now. Living since then has been total bliss.''
</TEXT>
