<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: First-Time Novelist Astounded by Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the new kid on the literary block, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> should have plenty of tips for aspiring writers after his first novel earned him a record-breaking $ 155,000 advance. The 24-year-old Wunderkind does n't have any words of wisdom, though. Getting `` The Mysteries of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'' published was just plain luck, he tells fledgling authors somewhat sheepishly. His coming-of-age novel was actually his master's thesis. An unsuspecting <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> turned it in last year to a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, who, instead of critiquing the manuscript, sent it to his agent. The agent was impressed, as was <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which offered $ 155,000 for the hardcover rights. Since its April release, `` The Mysteries of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'' has jumped onto best-seller lists, with 130,000 hardback copies in print. Foreign rights have been sold to editors in 13 countries and bids for the paperback rights are in the six figures. A movie deal also is in the works. The book is about a gangster's mild-mannered son who spends the summer after college graduation with new, flashy friends, including a young woman and man who vie for his affections. The protagonist, like <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON>, attended the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>, and the drama unfolds in this city. `` To me, it's the first novel. It has all the weaknesses of first novels. I mean, it's the first time I ever tried to write a book,'' the slim, soft-spoken <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> said on a recent visit here. The pricetag is irrelevant, he said, `` because it seems so inflated to me. I just ca n't correlate it with the worth of the book. All I ever really wanted was just to get my book published, or get a book published.'' Always an avid reader, <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> decided while growing up in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> he was going to become a writer. He honed his talents at <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, where he received a bachelor's degree in 1984. After living in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> six months, he applied to the two-year writing program at <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>. He began working on `` The Mysteries of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'' in May 1985 in preparation for graduate school that fall. `` I just thought ... there are going to be all these serious writers there, real writers, and I'll bet they're all working on novels and I've just been doing short stories,'' he recalled. By the time he arrived in <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> had written 100 pages, 80 of which he quickly scrapped. Over the next 1 -LCB- years, he spent every evening working on the book, required for his master of fine arts degree. He took his title from `` The Mysteries of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>'' by 19th-century French novelist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON>. `` I substituted the word <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and I went, ` Ooooh, neat,''' he said. <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> finished the 297-page novel in February 1987 and, eager for some feedback, dropped off the manuscript with novelist and English professor <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Heiney </PERSON>. Three days later, he was informed a copy of his thesis was on its way to <PERSON> Heiney </PERSON>'s agent in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It did n't look like student work. It had the look of professional work,'' <PERSON> Heiney </PERSON> said. A month later, nine publishing houses took part in an auction for the rights. <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> is unimpressed and, in fact, feels downright uncomfortable with all the praise. `` I like what I'm writing when I'm writing it and for about two weeks thereafter. It has a very short half-life in my esteem,'' he said, laughing. `` After that, I'm even assailed by intense doubts. No amount of praise from other people can convince me of the worth of what I've done. `` There's entire stretches of the novel that I ca n't read without wincing. I say, ` Ooooh, why did I say that? It's so clumsy.''' <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> has since sold several short stories to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> and other magazines. He's working on a second novel as well as the screenplay for `` The Mysteries of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>,'' to be directed by <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pakula </PERSON> of `` All the President's Men'' and `` Sophie's Choice. Despite his good fortune, <PERSON> Chabon </PERSON> has made few changes in the quiet life he leads in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, with his wife, <PERSON> Lollie </PERSON>, 32, an English doctoral student and poet. Their splurges include a new car, a color television and a honeymoon in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. `` Our strategy has been pretty much the same,'' he said. `` We just basically pretend that it's not really happening.'' Naturally, though, `` It's all real. And I'm just still me.''
</TEXT>
