<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: `Junk Food Junkie' Stars on Radio Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Singer-songwriter <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> says his 1976 novelty hit tune `` Junk Food Junkie'' was a prelude to some of the music he has performed on his radio show, `` Mountain Stage.'' The two-hour program, originating from the Capitol Plaza Theater in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, is carried by about 125 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> stations across the country The show, similar to the defunct `` Prairie Home Companion,'' features an eclectic group of performers who sing country, bluegrass, folk, blues, jazz and classical. Others recite poetry or tell their favorite stories. <PERSON> Groce </PERSON>, as host of the show, has performed a routine in which he intertwines the names of country music stars and song titles with the names of classical music greats. He has introduced numbers such as <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' `` Bourbon and Water Music,'' <PERSON> Waylon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s `` Mommas Do n't Let Your Babies Grow Up to Be Valkyries'' and <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bach </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' `` Branding Iron Concertos. To sing some of them, he has assumed the identity of <LOCATION> Plastico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flamingo </LOCATION>. Although the show focuses more on music than on humor, the 40-year-old <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> says `` Junk Food Junkie'' was similar to the spoofs he has been doing on the program. `` It gave a preview of that,'' he said in an interview from his rural home near <LOCATION> Philippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` I poked fun at organic food and junk food eaters `` I'm fairly knowledgeable about country music and sort of knowledgeable about classical. I like to hit both targets. I've done this in the past. In `` Junk Food Junkie,'' which <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> wrote, he sang about eating natural food such as yogurt by day and enjoying `` a genuine junk food high'' at night. He rattled off a list of his favorite munchies in a tune that caught the public fancy like few others. `` I had always admired satire and humor in songs,'' he recalled. `` I had written others like it _ satires of common, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> things. I felt this was a natural. `` I poked fun at myself, and I had no idea so many others fell in the syndrome I do. The response was more than I thought it would be. It got a lot of exposure in the press because of the odd nature of the song.'' He wrote the tune based on his experiences while working in an organic restaurant in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` After work, the cooks would go out and get a hamburger,'' he said. The peculiarity of the song tended to stereotype him, he said. `` I like the song; it's clever and I'm not ashamed of it. But they assume you're an oddball and ca n't sing. Actually my career has been based on singing.'' Since the hit, he has been the opening act on concert tours, performed to smaller audiences in coffeehouses and worked in arts programs. `` I did pretty much what anyone does who's not a big star,'' <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> said. Included in his work are a half-dozen albums for the <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, including two volumes of `` Disney's Children's Favorites'' that sold 2 million each. `` They have n't made me famous but they are known quite a bit,'' he said. He's just completed a special for the <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> on cable TV, `` <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> in Concert.'' He's been doing `` Mountain Stage'' since 1984, first on <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> and then branching out coast-to-coast in July 1986. <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> says `` Mountain Stage'' stresses music more than `` Prairie Home Companion,'' in which host <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> touted his fictional <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> town, <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wobegon </LOCATION>. `` We do very different things,'' he said. `` We tend to feature music and showcase the performers. They are the star of the show as much as our regulars. Ours is a little more of a true variety show where the guests take a bigger role. We give them much more time, and our show is not so much anchored in me.'' Guests have included bluegrass acts such as the Doug Dillard Band from the `` <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> Show,'' comedy by Dr. <PERSON> Demento </PERSON>, poetry by <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsberg </PERSON>, blues by <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bookbinder </PERSON>, country music by <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattea </PERSON>, classical music by the <PERSON> Montani </PERSON> String Quartet and jazz by the <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> Trio. `` This show takes chances and it's on the frontier of music in certain ways,'' <PERSON> Groce </PERSON> said. `` We specialize in singers and writers to a great degree. We do n't tell them how to act, how to look or what to sing. They appreciate that. There's no pretense. We just do it. `` Our role is to get people who are trend setters, even though they may not be well-known.'' He still gets the inevitable question: What is your favorite junk food these days? `` I stick with my old favorites like Dr. Pepper and Chee-tos. I also am kind of addicted to peanut butter crackers. Actually, anything with sugar in it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
