<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Looking for a different way to celebrate a birthday or anniversary? Try `` VideoScrapbooks'' _ a line of cassettes featuring the cultural highs and lows of bygone years. Using still photos, TV, film and newsreel footage, Halcyon Days of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> has created videos for nostalgia junkies. The 1958 cassette shows <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> in uniform and television ads for that bold sound innovation, hi-fidelity stereo _ `` with you in the middle.'' There are also gasps at space shots, fun with hula hoops, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> and that legend in her own time, <PERSON> Barbie </PERSON>. The 1938 video has jitterbug marathons, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fibber </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> on radio and the <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION> joke of all time, `` The War of the Worlds.'' The VHS cassettes retail for $ 19.95 and feature the years 1958, 1948, 1938 and the 1920s. Meanwhile, for students and others in need of a little `` style,'' Paperback Visual Publishing has produced a video adaptation of the <PERSON> Strunk </PERSON> and White English handbook, `` Elements of Style.'' The cassette, narrated by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> newsman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Osgood </PERSON>, features a color-coded screen to serve as index and to facilitate rewinding and forwarding to specific chapters. Videos reviewed this week: `` Overboard'' and `` The Couch Trip.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Overboard'' -LRB- CBS-Fox, VHS @ Beta, $ 89.98, Rated PG -RRB- Take one insufferably rich, perpetually bored blonde, throw her into the ocean, add a case of temporary amnesia and stir it up with a hunky handyman bent on revenge, and you've got `` Overboard,'' a charming comedy that looks better on tape than it sounds on paper. Goldie Hawn is <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Stayton </PERSON>, a `` Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous'' poster girl who changes bathing suits every 15 seconds and gets her jollies by making other people miserable. Enter Dean <PERSON> Proffitt </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Hawn </PERSON>'s real-life honey, <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a widowed carpenter who comes aboard the <PERSON> Stayton </PERSON> yacht to remodel a closet. <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> stiffs him and tosses his tools overboard. Later that night, she falls overboard herself and emerges from the drink with no idea of who she is. Seeing a chance to make her pay for her nastiness, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> convinces her she is his wife, <PERSON> Annie </PERSON>, mother of his four no-neck monsters and keeper of the disaster area they call home. The shock of real life almost kills her, and the transformation from rich witch to human being is fun to watch, though predictable. Hawn, always at home with funny stuff, makes Joanna-Annie alternately despicable and lovable, and <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> actually shows some comedic flair in the hands of director <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> `` Happy Days'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>. Clean enough for the kids, intelligent enough for the adults, `` Overboard'' is one of those warm, fuzzy little comedies guaranteed to make the whole family feel good. _ By <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryckman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Couch Trip'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION>, VHS @ Beta, $ 89.98, Rated R -RRB- `` The Couch Trip'' sets an enormous challenge for itself by trying to be fresh and funny while using one of the most hackneyed plot lines in the book: Psychiatrists are crazier than their clients; mental patients are more madcap than mad, and often possess, exclusively, truths of a very high ethical order; and said patients appear crazy but it's really the rest of the world that's lost its marbles <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Aykroyd </PERSON> stars as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, a small-time criminal institutionalized in a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> mental hospital where his specialty is cheering up the other patients, making it with the receptionist and driving the head shrink nuts. Meanwhile in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, big-time radio shrink <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Maitlin </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Grodin </PERSON> -RRB- is having a breakdown _ that's what movie shrinks do best _ because he's had an affair, or his wife has had one with his best friend, or something like that. He wants to leave it all behind for a sabbatical but he needs a replacement for his radio program. Through some complicated machinations, <PERSON> Aykroyd </PERSON> schemes his way out of the hospital, impersonates the head prison psychologist and wins the spot as <PERSON> Maitlin </PERSON>'s radio replacement, providing the film's few hilarious moments Along the way, <PERSON> Aykroyd </PERSON>'s ruse is discovered by, who else? another loonie, played by <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthau </PERSON>. They have their little quarrels but mostly seem to enjoy conversing in the higher-truth patois of the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> insane. <PERSON> Aykroyd </PERSON>'s most ardent devotees may see something to like in `` The Couch Trip,'' but only if they do n't mind the constant stream of genital humor and four-letter words. _ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
