<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Serious Slammin''' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ Pointer Sisters Side 1 of the Pointer Sisters' latest album is awful _ dance music as mindless and soulless as anything that surfaced in the disco craze of the 1970s. The sisters redeem themselves a bit on the second side of `` Serious Slammin'.'' Still, it's hard to believe this is the same group that turned out one of the decade's best pop records, `` Breakout,'' just five years ago. One problem with `` Serious Slammin''' is that June, <PERSON> Anita </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> and producer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> have n't changed their formula a bit since `` Breakout,'' and the sisters sound tired of it. They're still singing uptempo dance tunes over synthesizers and drum machines and, for a change of pace, mixing in steamy ballads over synthesizers and drum machines Another reason for the droopy energy level could be the material, all provided by outside writers. The tunes are tuneless, the lyrics lame. The nadir is `` Shut Up and Dance,'' which begins, `` All I want to do with you is dance; I do n't need no verbal expose.'' There must have been something else the Pointer Sisters could have recorded instead. When the songs are decent, so is `` Serious Slammin'.'' `` My Life,'' which opens Side 2, is the first cut that creates any kind of rhythmic momentum. The mid-tempo `` I Will Be There,'' which closes the record, deserves a place alongside such past hits by the group as `` Slowhand'' and `` Fire.'' Alas, most of `` Serious Slammin''' is pointless, sisters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` That Special Part of Me'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Onaje </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> <PERSON> Onaje </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> is unknown despite the company he keeps. The veteran producer, composer and pianist has worked with such jazz artists as <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nat </PERSON> <PERSON> Adderley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobham </PERSON>, but `` That Special Part of Me'' is his first album in more than a decade. Much of the record is terrific. Jazz is the common thread, although there are also elements of pop and rhythm & amp; blues. <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> writes melodies that give his instrumentals instant appeal, and yet the improvisations _ particularly by <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> on piano _ are intricate and reward listeners who play the record through more than once. There are few frills but plenty of variety in the arrangements. `` Shadowlight'' features a trio and gives <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> a chance to stretch; the <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett-like </PERSON> `` The Dancer'' is <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> playing one grand piano part overdubbed on another. The R & amp; B influence comes into play on the title cut and `` Quiet Passion,'' which find a groove and stay there. The pop element, however, is incorporated with less success. <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> makes <PERSON> Muzak </PERSON> with his cover of `` Did n't I Blow Your Mind -LRB- This Time -RRB-,'' while `` All My Love -LRB- For You -RRB-,'' the only tune featuring vocals, unfortunately sounds like a duet between <PERSON> Dionne </PERSON> <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Osmond </PERSON>. Aside from the two awry crossover ventures, `` That Special Part of Me'' represents a welcome and successful try by <PERSON> Gumbs </PERSON> for a higher profile.
</TEXT>
