<HEAD>National Sharing of `Cadillac Kidneys' Gets Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The first time <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> entered a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> hospital for a kidney transplant, the donated organ ended up being sent halfway across the country. A week later, it happened again. The kidney, her ticket to a dialysis-free life, was shipped a thousand miles away at the last minute. `` I'm sure the person who got it is very deserving, but it's still very disappointing,'' said the 57-year-old <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> woman `` You find yourself feeling guilty about your feelings because I thought, ` Well, I would n't feel quite so badly if it had stayed in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. But to ship it out ...''' She knew she was competing not only with local patients but also with those waiting and praying, just like her, around the country. One of those waiting and praying was <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, who got the second kidney thanks to new national guidelines designed to make transplantation more efficient and equitable. `` I'm just happy it happened,'' Ms. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> said. `` I was prepared to be on dialysis for a while. I did n't think I'd get one for a long time.'' Because of an unsuccessful kidney transplant March 16, 1986, two years to the day before her latest operation, <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>'s immune system had built up an unusually large number of antibodies Her best hope was a perfectly matched kidney, a rare and therefore prized possession. When such an organ became available in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in mid-March, the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> was forced to relinquish it under the new rules. After a computerized search by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was found to be the best candidate. And <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> was sent home, once more, to wait. Her wait ended May 20, when she received a new kidney at <LOCATION> Hermann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. That's the way it goes under the 8-month-old program, which requires <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s 201 kidney transplant centers and 120 organ procurement agencies to share all `` six-antigen'' kidneys. Antigens, simply, are features of alien organisms or tissue that can provoke an attack by the immune system. If antigens of a transplanted organ match those of the recipient's body, the immune system usually does not attack. The six-antigen organs, only 2.6 percent of all donated kidneys, had been snapped up where they were procured until the new rules were implemented. `` The nurses and doctors say it's a fair system,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. `` Of course, I can only believe what they tell me.'' The kidney-sharing policy was adopted last summer by the 31-member board of directors of <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> and implemented Oct. 1. The Virginia-based computer center operates the <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, to which all transplant centers must belong to receive <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> reimbursements. The network was recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Organ Transplantation, formed under the 1984 National Transplant Act. <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> also instituted a standardized scoring system for distributing other increasingly scarce organs, like hearts, livers and lungs. Patients are awarded points based on medical urgency, length of time on the waiting list and proximity to the donor, among other things. `` It's a great improvement over what existed before, which was a mish-mash of politics and old-boy networks,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. More than 13,550 people are awaiting organ transplants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 12,200 of whom need new kidneys, according to <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Transplantation. Virtually all of the kidney transplant candidates are on dialysis, the exhausting, week-after-week mechanical elimination of impurities from the blood. To increase the number of nationally shared kidneys and help more hard-to-match, sensitized patients like Ms. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, the network in March expanded the guidelines to cover certain kidneys with fewer than six identified or detected antigens. Failure to comply with any of the guidelines could result in suspension or expulsion from the network, and loss of Medicare funding. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION>, expects the change to double the number of perfectly matched kidneys <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> offers. There were 115 organ donors reported to <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> from Oct. 1, 1987, to April 30 who matched a potential kidney recipient for all six antigens. Not all were transplanted, for various reasons. Whether it's sharing kidneys or assigning points, the transplant surgeon still has the final say, according to Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> and of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>. `` The physician has the option of using his best medical judgment. Now he has to defend that.'' The guidelines have not `` changed what they -LRB- centers -RRB- have been doing in terms of getting the right organ to the right patient, because they were doing that anyway,'' he said. `` But it has reduced that process to a written policy which they are able to follow and defend and argue about.'' Reaction has been mixed, and <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said, `` One can not have a national organization of this type with everybody being perfectly happy about it. There is no organized group out there that is in opposition. No rebellion is going on. No centers have refused to participate and abide by these guidelines.'' Mandatory kidney sharing has produced the most grumbling. Some experts maintain that the long-term success of kidney transplants depends on careful matching of the donor and recipient. Others argue that does not justify flying kidneys all over the country since the more they are moved and the longer they go unused, the less viable they become. Donated kidneys can be preserved outside the body for up to 48 hours, four times longer than livers and nearly 10 times longer than hearts. `` Obviously, some people are a little upset when they have to send them out. They could have used them locally just as well,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. `` We keep trying to remind them that when you give, you get back. If everyone is cooperating, and they must, then there will be a fair distribution.'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Broznick </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, winces every time he sends a `` Cadillac kidney'' out of town. `` I do this job because I want to see people transplanted. Period. But I'm a Pittsburgher. I'm very proud of the program here. I want to see this program work. I do n't want to see my kidneys go to waste or share them with everybody.'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> LaCombe </PERSON>, transplant coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Hennepin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, is ahead of the game. As of early May, she had given up one prized kidney but got back three, one of which went to Ms. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>. <PERSON> Broznick </PERSON> had shipped out two perfect kidneys, but got only one back. In <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, four went out but none came in. `` We provided four people with kidneys and a chance they might not have otherwise had,'' said <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION>. `` On the other hand, it just so happens that twice the same patient -LRB- Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> -RRB- was asked to come in for the potential transplant and twice told, ` I'm sorry, we have to ship these kidneys out.' `` It's a very difficult, very touchy issue. But if you look in the global viewpoint, we're probably doing what is correct.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
