<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sketches of Transplant Law, Organizations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Transplant Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the law governing organ transplant, the task force that grew out of it, and the network under contract to help implement it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Organ Transplant Act</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The National Organ Transplant Act was passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 in response to the growing need for a national transplant system and medical and ethical guidelines. It called for formation of a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> and mandated establishment of a national <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> to be administered by a private group with oversight of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. It provided grants to organ procurement groups to help increase their effectiveness and promote organ donation. It also called for establishment of a registry of recipients.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Task Force on Organ Transplantation</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Organ Transplantation is a 25-member panel that made 70 recommendations to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and to the secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. The panel of doctors and experts, which no longer exists, recommended: _ That hearts and livers go to Americans whenever possible and that foreigners make up no more than 10 percent of the total kidney recipients at any transplant center _ A ban on the exportation of donor organs, except when no appropriate recipients can be found in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ That all states pass laws under which hospitals would be required to approach families about the possibility of organ donation _ That a federal entity be established for organ transplantation That entity is the Division of <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>United Network for Organ Sharing</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> is a non-profit organization based in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, that was given a federal contract in 1986 to set up the national <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, which links by computer all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> transplant centers, organ procurement agencies and tissue-typing laboratories. Membership is mandatory in order for these institutions to receive federal Medicare reimbursements. <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION>' 31-member board in 1987 approved mandatory guidelines for allocation of donated organs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
