<HEAD>Forecasters Are Getting Better _ But Not Very Quickly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Beach days still turn to deluge with no regard for forecasters' promises, but the tricky art of predicting the weather is actually getting better. How much better? So accurate, according to one official, that people are starting to believe them. `` It's my impression that there is much more reliance on weather forecasts today,'' says <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Glahn </PERSON>. `` People will use them, whereas 20 years ago, they probably would n't.'' There are many statistical ways of interpreting forecasters' track records, says <PERSON> Glahn </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in Silver Spring, But in general, studies show that `` a 48-hour forecast now is almost as accurate as a 24-hour forecast was 20 years ago.'' According to the weather service's way of keeping time, a 24-hour forecast is this morning's prediction of what it will do this afternoon. A 48-hour forecast is today's prediction of what will happen tomorrow. Another example of the improvement, says <PERSON> Glahn </PERSON>, is forecasters' growing avoidance of big errors Last winter, there was a 6 percent chance the weather service would be off 10 degrees or more on tomorrow's temperature. Twenty years ago, there was a 13 percent chance. Other ways of looking at forecasters' prowess produce numbers that are n't quite so impressive. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, a meteorologist who retired four years ago from the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, notes that it isn' ~ enough to be right most of Anybody can do that. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, for example, it rains one day in three, so a daily forecast of `` no rain'' will be right 67 percent of the time. In <LOCATION> Yuma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, it rains just seven days a year, making the same forecast right 98 percent of the time. So <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> and others who keep track of such things compare the forecast to the average weather, what's known as the climatological norm. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, forecasters give the correct next-day forecast about 82 percent of the time _ halfway between 67 percent, which requires no skill, and 100 percent. So the forecasters are said to have a 50 percent skill level. From 1966 until he retired, <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> and his students predicted the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> weather every day. Their accuracy was a little better than the weather service. And over time, he found that their skill improved about 5 percent a decade. A similar analysis by <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> found that the weather service is improving 5-10 percent a decade. Forecasters attribute most of the improvement to computers, which let them create three-dimensional pictures of the atmosphere. Using complex formulas, they fast-forward the weather to create an image of the winds, pressures, temperatures and moisture in tomorrow's skies. `` I think the improvement in the future will be a little greater than it has been,'' says <PERSON> Tzvi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gal-Chen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm not willing to bet my house on it, but maybe my car. I have a very old car.'' <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> foresees no breakthroughs in forecasting precision. But he quickly adds that his prediction probably does n't mean much. `` Big breakthroughs are always unexpected,'' he says. `` That's one of the interesting things about fishing and science.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
