<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv26   05-23 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 26,0725</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for May 26 in summary form.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The first time <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> entered a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> hospital for a kidney transplant, the donated organ ended up being sent halfway across the country. A week later, it happened again. Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, 57, knew that under new national guidelines designed to make transplantation more efficient and equitable she was competing not only with local patients but also with many of the more than 12,200 people awaiting kidney transplants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. When a perfectly matched kidney _ only 2.6 percent of all donated kidneys _ became available in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in mid-March the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> had to relinquish it under the new rules. A computer search by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION> found that instead of Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, the best candidate was <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn </LOCATION>. The kidney-sharing policy was adopted last summer by <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> and implemented Oct. 1. <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> operates the <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, to which all transplant centers must belong to get Medicare reimbursements. The network was recommended by a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Organ Transplantation formed under the 1984 National Transplant Act. <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> also instituted a standardized scoring system for distributing other increasingly scarce organs, like hearts, livers and lungs. Patients get points based on urgency, time waiting and proximity to the donor, among other things. Reaction has been mixed, and Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> UNOS </ORGANIZATION> and of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` One can not have a national organization of this type with everybody being perfectly happy about it. `` There is no organized group out there that is in opposition. No rebellion is going on.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Steere </PERSON> is making his spring rounds, spreading the word that tourists wearing shorts and sandals are easy prey for ticks carrying the disease he identified. Since <PERSON> Steere </PERSON>, director of the Lyme disease clinic at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, classified it 13 years ago after an outbreak in <LOCATION> Lyme </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, cases have been confirmed in 33 states, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. Lyme disease is transmitted by a tiny deer tick, but the real culprit is a bacteria. Infected ticks have been found in wooded areas from <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Tick bites mainly occur from mid-May through July, but those bitten are unlikely to contract the disease if the tick is removed with tweezers within 24 hours of the bite. Early signs include a circular rash and flu-like symptoms. Patients given antibiotics early generally are cured without lasting effects. If untreated, 60 percent of patients develop arthritis-like symptoms. Complications can include hepatitis, breathing trouble and damage to the heart and nervous system. The ticks bite humans at `` mouse-belly height,'' putting people with exposed feet and legs at highest risk, said Dr. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. In high-risk areas, people should wear light-colored pants, making the tick easier to see, and tuck the cuffs into socks. Fifteen-hundred <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cases are reported each year, but <PERSON> Steere </PERSON> and <PERSON> Spielman </PERSON> said many go unreported because victims believe they have other ailments. Scientists predict more Lyme disease cases this year because of an increase in the deer population and a corresponding rise in the number of deer ticks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Satellite information and computer models have improved weather forecasts so much that people are even starting to believe them. There are many ways to interpret track records, says <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Glahn </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in Silver Spring, Md. But in general, studies show that `` a 48-hour forecast now is almost as accurate as a 24-hour forecast was 20 years ago.'' A 24-hour forecast is this morning's prediction of what it will do this afternoon. A 48-hour forecast is today's prediction of tomorrow's weather. Another improvement, says <PERSON> Glahn </PERSON>, is avoiding big errors. Last winter, there was a 6 percent chance the weather service would be off 10 degrees or more on tomorrow's temperature. Twenty years ago, there was a 13 percent chance.
</TEXT>
