<HEAD>New Cell-Preservation Process Could Help Eye, Tissue Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A freeze-drying process that creates undamaged tissue specimens for microscopic analysis is under study as a way for eye banks to store human corneas indefinitely for transplant. <ORGANIZATION> LifeCell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> researchers have used the process developed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> to store baboon and rabbit corneas a month before reattaching them, said <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Requard </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Tissue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit network of 11 eye and tissue banks. <ORGANIZATION> TBI </ORGANIZATION> has awarded a $ 15,000 grant to Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON>, a cornea specialist at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wilmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> who will assess the process' value in humans. Corneas now are viable up to about seven days. In the <ORGANIZATION> LifeCell </ORGANIZATION> process, a sample is cooled so rapidly _ using a liquid nitrogen-chilled copper bar at minus 196 dugrees Centrigrade _ that it bypasses the phase when ice crystals form, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Frison </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> LifeCell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> president. It then is transferred to a molecular distillation dryer, which evaporates most of the water and returns the sample to room temperature, saving laboratories the cost of refrigerated storage. Current chemical processes alter the proteins, enzymes and genetic components of tissue, freezing produces ice crystals that harm cell structures, and use of dimethyl sulfoxide to reduce ice damage alters cells, <PERSON> Frison </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> LifeCell </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Woodlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, is a profit-making enterprise set up in 1986 to market technology developed at the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> health center. Investors include <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Venture Capital Division, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ventures </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>
</TEXT>
