<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Economy,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Extends Wage, Price Freeze for Three Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says it will extend for three more months a freeze on wages and the prices of federally regulated goods and services as part of its battle against inflation. President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> decided to hold wages, prices and the peso-dollar exchange rate steady until the end of August, the government news agency <ORGANIZATION> Notimex </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. `` We will not be able to sing victory in the fight against inflation until -LRB- the rate -RRB- gets to comparable levels with the trading partners of our country and ... stays -LRB- at that rate -RRB- for several months,'' the news agency quoted de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> as saying. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> unveiled the program, called the Economic Solidarity Pact, in December in an effort to bring under control the nation's skyrocketing inflation rate. Consumer prices soared a record 159.2 percent in all of last year. When the program was announced, government officials said its goal was to reduce the monthly inflation rate to 2 percent to 3 percent by year's end. But the government reported earlier this month that consumer prices rose 3.1 percent in April, well under the record 15.5 percent posted in January. Budget Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said last week that May's inflation pace may run about 2 percent. The economic program, as initially drafted, called for the monthly indexing of wages and prices. But administration officials quickly turned the plan into a quasi-shock program featuring the wage and price freezes. Prices on government-controlled goods and services, such as tortillas, subway fares and gasoline, have been frozen since March. The exchange rate for the peso currency also has held steady since then, trading at about 2,260 pesos to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. By extending the wage-price freeze through the summer, the government appears to have guaranteed that inflation will be low for the crucial July 6 presidential elections.
</TEXT>
