<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An auto dealership fired two black salesmen for racial reasons and must reimburse them for back pay and rehire them if they want their jobs back, a federal judge ruled. <LOCATION> Perillo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> violated the Civil Rights Act when it fired <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilyard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> in 1986, Judge <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> ordered full back pay for the men, who are black, and ordered <PERSON> Perillo </PERSON> to rehire them if they want their jobs back. <PERSON> Gilyard </PERSON>, 48, and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 60, said they were among four blacks on a 10-member sales staff when new management took over the dealership in 1986. Within 60 days no blacks were employed at the company, the two men claimed. In ruling on Friday, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreeger </PERSON>, new-car sales manager at <LOCATION> Perillo </LOCATION>, `` manifested the agonies of the damned'' as he tried to defend the firings when he testified. `` We should have had a videotape of Mr. <PERSON> Kreeger </PERSON>,'' the judge said. `` He trembled, licked his lips ... telling a phony story for <ORGANIZATION> Perillo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pontiac </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Kreeger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Scala </PERSON>, <PERSON> Perillo </PERSON>'s general manager, argued that they fired <PERSON> Gilyard </PERSON> because of absences and insubordination and fired <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> because he was rude to customers and used ethnic slurs. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said the allegations of rudeness were `` absolute falsehoods,'' noting that the customer who allegedly overheard the slur `` has amazingly never been found.''
