<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs May 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Chinese Fleeing to Canada and Investing Heavily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S. unless specified as Canadian. Also
moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese first came to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as cooks and launderers in the gold rush 130 years ago. Today they're flying in from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> with millions of dollars to invest in businesses and real estate. For the large majority, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is a hedge against <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s reversion to Chinese Communist sovereignty in 1997 While <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> entrepreneurs find easy entry under <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s `` investor immigrant'' program, hospitals in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> in British <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> report an increase in the number of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> women who come to have babies because the infants automatically become Canadian citizens Other Chinese come as students and professionals. But the entrepreneurs and investors often get a special welcome. `` They have no problem flipping down 5 million dollars -LRB- $ 4 million -RRB- for a house because in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it would be 20 million -LRB- $ 16 million -RRB-,'' said Premier <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. One recent buyer was <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON>, whose casino and ferry empire in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> makes him one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s richest men. He paid 5.5 million Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 4.4 million -RRB- for a 25-room mansion on Bridle Path, <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s millionaire's row. Across the country in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ka-shing </PERSON>, whose companies represent 20 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, won the bidding in April for the right to develop the choice 210-acre site of Expo'86. Through his 25-year-old son, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>, a Canadian citizen, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> plans to spend $ 1.6 billion to turn the choice downtown strip into `` Pacific Place,'' a high-rise complex that will consist of a 24-hour global financial center, a 400-room hotel, manmade islands with 10,000 housing units and a 630-berth marina. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> and his son also control 52 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Husky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s 12th largest oil company, and his <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought the ailing <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> this past November. Officials estimate the current flow of Chinese investment at $ 1.6 billion a year, half of it in real estate. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> own one-third of the shopping malls in the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> suburb of <PERSON> Scarborough </PERSON>, one of three metropolitan Chinatowns. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hou </PERSON>, a Canadian-Chinese community leader, said his real estate company deals with 100 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> investors a month. After the first Chinese came for the gold rush and later to work on the construction of the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> discouraged further immigration by imposing a tax of $ 50 a head on new arrivals. Those who stayed were denied citizenship until 1947. Today, 600,000 Canadians are of Chinese descent, including more than 200,000 in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and 175,000 in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>. At any one time, 18,000 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> students are enrolled at Canadian universities. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has become the leading source of immigrants to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, with 22,100 visas issued last year. `` I came in 1967,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lam </PERSON>, a 65-year-old <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> real estate magnate who has donated more than $ 5 million to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> universities and the Sun Yat-sen Classical Chinese Garden in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, a replica of the ancient gardens of <LOCATION> Suzhou </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> pulled off the biggest real estate deal in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>'s history in 1972 and has since built a fortune as a conduit for other <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> investors `` Now we're seeing more than just flight capital,'' <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> said in an interview. `` There's a second strata of people, young professionals who see the writing on the wall for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and are afraid.'' The Chinese Communists have agreed to allow <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to maintain its capitalist system for 50 years after the reversion of sovereignty, but many <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> are hedging against that. `` <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is seen as desirable because of its political stability and large <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> population.'' said <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Eng </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> realtor. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s `` investor immigrant'' program offers a visa in exchange for investment of 150,000 Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 121,500 -RRB- to 500,000 dollars -LRB- $ 405,000 -RRB- in approved businesses. Government figures show <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> investment under the program totaled 776 million Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 628 million -RRB- last year and created 4,500 jobs. Premier <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> said he welcomes the well-heeled arrivals. `` <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has been built by foreign capital _ over 50 percent of our manufacturing industry is foreign-owned,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thursday AMs May 26</NOTE>
