<HEAD>Administration Drops Legislative Push to Lift Phone Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has decided against offering legislation this year to remove antitrust restrictions on the Bell telephone companies, officials said Monday. Although the administration remains convinced the prohibitions against <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies entering certain competitive phone businesses should be removed, the timing of such a proposal will not allow it this year, the officials said. `` It's late into the final year of this Congress and they have a full plate,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Spurlock </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency. White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> sent a two-paragraph memo to members of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet-level </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> saying that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> decided to stop efforts to persuade <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to support legislation that would either relax or remove the restrictions, according to <ORGANIZATION> CommunicationsWeek </ORGANIZATION>, a trade publication, which quoted unidentified sources in this week's issue. The memo also said the administration had not changed its opinion that the restrictions should be lifted, the publication reported. White House spokesman <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> declined to comment on the memo, but said, `` There has been a policy decision that we are not going to introduce legislation on that topic this year.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been behind the push within the administration to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies to offer electronic information services and manufacture telecommunications equipment. Restrictions prohibiting the companies from entering those businesses and from offering long-distance service were imposed by the antitrust decree that broke up <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in January 1984. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, who supervises the consent decree that broke up <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T, last year ruled the Bell companies could transmit information services, but he refused to allow them to generate the information itself. He said the companies continue to control access to local phone networks, which would give them an unfair advantage over competitors.
