<SECOND>AM-Great Lakes Plan, Bjt,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Lakes States Reveal Economic Development Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials from six <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states signed an agreement Monday to showcase the region's strengths and promote economic development through a program of joint lobbying and marketing. The Council of Great Lakes Governors revealed the 13-point plan, based on recommendations made by a commission appointed by the council a year ago. The governors could not put a price tag on the plan, but said some of the programs would involve existing state programs. Any costs will be shared by the states, or the council will seek outside funding, they said. The plan includes a marketing campaign highlighting the region's business climate and recreational attractions under the theme `` Great Lakes @ Great Future. `` The -LRB- agreement -RRB- represents a blueprint for our future,'' said <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON>. `` Following it, we expect to fashion and sustain economic progress across our region.'' <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> signed the agreement, along with <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> did not attend Monday's announcement but had endorsed the agreement, the council said. The governors agreed to participate in a joint trade mission next year, and <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> suggested <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as a possible destination. A trade office also is being planned. The agreement also includes: _ An inventory of educational opportunities in the region _ A campaign promoting research capabilities _ The establishment of a <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to provide supplemental financing for small - and medium-sized _ Creation of a Buy Great Lakes computer network of goods and services _ Development of telecommunication projects for agricultural use _ Appointment of a liason to work with state offices in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON>, responding to a question, said the agreement did not specifically include a provision preventing the states from trying to lure businesses from each other, but said he did n't think that was a problem. `` I think very few of us these days invest any time or energy in really going into our neighbor states to try to lure business away,'' he said. `` From time to time there are companies who propose a move within the region, and we're obliged as governors to talk to those companies in the interest of our own citizens.'' <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> said the Great Lakes states' toughest competition is n't coming from among themselves or other areas of the country but from foreign countries According to the council, the six <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states include the headquarters of about one-third of the Fortune 500 companies. About one-fifth of the nation's manufacturing is within the region, including 70 percent of the steel producaiton, 55 percent of machine tool business and over half of the automobile production. The Great Lakes region also has a $ 12 billion annual tourist industry, the council said.
</TEXT>
