<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poor management practices accompanied losses that drove the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, into insolvency last week, a farm credit official said Monday. `` As of last Friday the bank's liabilities exceeded its earning assets by aproximately $ 500 million,'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thor </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on agricultural credit. `` This means that the board of directors and management of the bank have lost over $ 300 million in the past three years,'' he added. <PERSON> Thor </PERSON> said sour loans, high debt costs and heavy operating costs had plagued the bank. He said the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bank sought $ 410 million to $ 610 million in assistance this year but was unable to come up with a workable plan to get out from under. `` It seems you have indicated a lot of what you might call poor management practices down there,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>. `` I would say that's a fair assessment,'' said <PERSON> Thor </PERSON>, whose board was established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year to bail out the ailing Farm Credit System. Lawmakers expressed dismay that the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bank had been allowed to go downhill until it was beyond rescue. They prodded officials to avoid any recurrence at other land banks. `` We want to avoid another <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>,'' Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON>, D-S.D., said. Meanwhile, the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bank reopened its doors Monday to provide information to borrowers. A key federal regulator expressed hope for quick action to restore loan service under supervision of a receiver. `` We are trying very hard to work out an agreement to restore service with the cooperation of some of the other system institutions,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told a news conference. <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, stressed that the receiver, <ORGANIZATION> REW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, was not authorized to make loans to customers of the bank, which serves 90 local lending associations in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. Thus it would be necessary to reach an agreement with other Farm Credit System banks to make loans through the receiver-operated, billion-dollar lending cooperative, whose doors were closed Friday afternoon after months of losses averaging $ 4.5 million. Such loans would be on an interim basis while the receiver winds down the activities of the bank, <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> institution is one of 12 Federal Land Banks within the massive Farm Credit System, a $ 50 billion, nationwide network of borrower-owned banks and local lending associations. The system, largely unknown to city folk outside the financial industry, is a longtime bulwark of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agriculture. Doldrums in the farm economy in the early 1980s combined with unfavorable credit agreements plus high overhead within the system brought some of the banks into hard financial straits in recent years. That prompted <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass a major bailout bill last year. The <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bank received $ 30 million in aid under the bailout bill but the assistance board that makes such decisions turned off the tap last week and instead asked the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the system's federal regulator, to place the institution in receivership. `` Our responsibility will be to wind down the activities of this institution,'' <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> said, adding that it should take less than a year. <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> was asked if the administrartion's action meant there soon would be a rash of foreclosures. `` Quite the contrary,'' he said. He said those whose loans are not performing would get the full benefit of `` borrowers rights'' provisions under last year's bailout legislation. The receiver's task also would involve placing the bank's business with other lending institutions, <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> said He said it was expected that some other system lender would move into the three-state area to take over the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> business but that it was too early to say which one. `` We would expect fairly quick action,'' he said. He said it would be legal for the receiver to sell assets to private lending institutions. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> `` certainly will be reviewing all significant actions in the district.'' <PERSON> Nayor </PERSON> said there is `` evidence of a turnaround for many'' of the Farm Credit System institutions during the last year. `` There are still several land banks facing serious problems, but they're working their way through them,'' he added The <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bank's porfolio of more than 21,000 loans totaled $ 1.68 billion at year's end, but 40 percent of that amount was tied up in loans classified either as nonaccrual or high-risk. Liabilities, meanwhile, reached $ 1.909 billion on March 31.
