<DATELINE>UPPER SADDLE RIVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday reported a $ 625.2 million first-quarter loss, most of which resulted from costs connected with the telecommunication company's reorganization The loss, blamed on the costs of a major restructuring, compared with a loss of $ 18.8 million in the same period a year ago. Special charges of $ 603 million in the first quarter resulted from write-downs connected with the planned unloading of the company's microwave and voice-switching facilities, officials said. The write-downs reflect the company's exit from the business of providing communications facilities to focus on specialized business and consumer services. The charges also resulted from severance and pension costs stemming from its previously announced plan to lay off 1,800 employees, or 25 percent of the work force, by the end of the year, and from costs related to the curtailing of a management pension plan. Revenues were $ 235 million, compared to $ 205 million for the previous first quarter. Figures in 1987 do not include revenues from <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s international telex unit. <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was acquired in December 1987 as part of <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s down-to-the-wire restructuring Savings from the layoffs were not reflected in the 1988 figures. President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Amman </PERSON> said the facilities sales would `` help reduce the burden of fixed costs associated with the operation of a nationwide telecommunications plant.'' The company's stock on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> dropped to $ 3, down 12.5 cents, on the news. One analyst said he looked on the write-downs as expected and not unwelcome, and usually a good sign in the telecommunications business. `` It's better to take them right off, get the bad egg out and move ahead'' rather than let old wounds fester, said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>
