<HEAD>Court Says Fixed Annuities Fall Under Securities Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped word ``involved'' in 8th graf, The insurance
...; picks up 9th graf, Among these ....</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Versions also moved on general news wires
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday let stand a ruling that put millions of so-called fixed annuities under the jurisdiction of federal securities laws. Under the lower court ruling, fixed annuities paying fluctuating interest rates could be regulated the same as stocks and bonds. Insurance industry officials had opposed the rule, claiming it imposed a heavy regulatory burden that would raise company costs and translate into higher prices for consumers. In other business-related actions Monday, the high court: _ Agreed to study the power of states to regulate natural gas production, including `` use-it-or-lose-it'' rules designed to stimulate production _ Refused to unravel a merger between units of <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fuqua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> that created the nation's largest wholesale photofinishing operation _ Gave states some power to enforce safety codes at federal nuclear production facilities for hazards unrelated to radiation The insurance industry had been watching the annuities case closely, since it involved policies held by millions of customers and representing billions of dollars. Among these, fixed annuities traditionally have been regarded as insurance contracts because investors never risk their principal. Annuity holders are assured of receiving the money contributed plus a certain amount of interest in payments made at regular intervals. Holders of fixed annuities are assured of a minimum rate of return on contributions. And most annuity plans provide for `` excess interest'' paid at the discretion of the annuity company. In 1967, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that so-called variable annuities, those that do not assure any minimum interest payments on contributions, may be treated as securities regulated by federal law. But a ruling by the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last April 15 marked the first time a fixed annuity was also treated as a security. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> sued the <ORGANIZATION> Variable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Annuity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- in 1982, contending that the fixed annuity is a `` security,'' and that <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION> had violated anti-fraud provisions of federal securities law. A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that the fixed annuity is not a security. But the 7th Circuit court reversed that ruling, reinstating the suit. The appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION>'s fixed annuity did not qualify for such treatment because its excess-interest rate on existing deposits could be changed at any time at <ORGANIZATION> VALIC </ORGANIZATION>'s discretion. By refusing to hear the case, the high court let that ruling stand. `` We were hoping the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> would take the case,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Adney </PERSON>, an attorney representing the Washington-based industry group, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, on Monday. He noted that under the appeals court ruling, fixed annuities contracts must be filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, `` and be subject to their regulation _ not just regulation by state insurance departments.'' `` That means considerable expense and complications for the insurance companies _ and for the situation of the policy holders,'' he added. While big companies can afford those added expenses, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> NALC </ORGANIZATION> feared that the increased costs could mean that `` smaller companies might not be able to shoulder the increased risk, or to compete in the market.'' In the natural gas case, the high court said it would review a ruling upholding the power of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> officials to control production from what is believed to be the largest natural gas reservoir in the world. The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 upheld rules adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> covering gas from the <LOCATION> Hugoton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, most of which is carried outside the state through pipelines. Since 1944, the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> permitted owners of underproducing wells to `` save up'' their authorized production ceilings _ creating what are called `` underages'' _ and overproduce in future months to make up for shortfalls. To create a production incentive, the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> commission changed the rules in 1983 by declaring that underages must be used within specified periods of years or they would be canceled. The rule was challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the major buyers of the <ORGANIZATION> Hugoton </ORGANIZATION> gas for transport outside the state. It asked the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to strike down the 1983 regulations on grounds that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has exclusive authority over natural gas production. In the <LOCATION> Kodak-Fuqua </LOCATION> case, the court rejected a competitor's arguments that the deal violates antitrust laws The competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Phototron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, sought to block the merger pending the outcome of its antitrust lawsuit seeking $ 300 million in damages. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, temporarily blocked the merger but the 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in March overturned the injunction and allowed the merger to occur while Phototron pursues its suit. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> and the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Fuqua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> merged to create <ORGANIZATION> Qualex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, combining the <LOCATION> Fuqua </LOCATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Colorcraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with Kodak-owned laboratories. In a ruling on injuries, the court, said a worker injured falling from a scaffold at a federally supervised nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, is entitled to seek a `` bonus'' compensation award under a state law. The court ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gaseous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diffusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.
